<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--OilRigDisaster     11-23 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Oil Rig Disaster,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Occidental Agrees To Pay $180 Million In Compensation In Oil Rig
Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Occidental Petroleum Corp. has agreed
to pay $180 million in compensation to victims' families and
survivors of the Piper Alpha oil rig disaster.
   Lawyers for the families of 126 of the 167 people killed and for
50 of the 62 survivors of the July 6 fire in the North Sea said they
will urge their clients to accept Tuesday's offer from the Piper
platform's U.S. owner.
   A source close to the negotiations said the average payment would
be $1.08 million for each family.
   ``Some will receive payment before Christmas,'' said Occidental
spokesman Alex Blake-Milton.
   Some of the remaining families planned to sue Los Angeles-based
Occidental in U.S. courts, where they believe they may get larger
sums and see the disaster investigated more thoroughly than in
Britain.
   It was not known how many families or survivors would sue.
</TEXT>
