<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EastGermany-Soviet     11-23 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-East Germany-Soviet,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Moscow Defends Soviet Magazine Banned By East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's dispute with the Kremlin over a
reformist Soviet magazine intensified when Radio Moscow defended the
publication as mirroring a ``plurality of opinions in the Soviet
press.''
   In a related development on Tuesday, a West German newspaper
reported that East German authorities have pulled five
anti-Stalinist Soviet films from theaters around the German
communist state.
   On Saturday, the East German Communist Party newspaper Neues
Deutschland said the government in East Berlin had suspended
delivery of Sputnik, a Soviet periodical that contains a selection
of articles from the Soviet press.
   Neues Deutschland charged that the magazine's articles ``do not
contribute to cementing Soviet-East German relations and instead
contain articles that distort history.''
   In recent issues, Sputnik has carried articles containing frank
appraisals of the Stalin era, along with letters and commentaries
critical of Kremlin policies.
   Radio Moscow's German-language service, heard in Berlin, on
Tuesday said the ban resulted from a misunderstanding.: ``Here at
the editorial side of Radio Moscow we have understanding for the
motives which have been given for this decision.
   ``But we believe that in this case there is a misunderstanding.
The publication of the magazine Sputnik ... only mirrors the
plurality of opinions in the Soviet press. ... We hope that this
regretful incident will be settled over time,'' it said.
   The West German newspaper Die Welt said East German authorities
have pulled five anti-Stalinist Soviet films from theaters in East
Germany.
   Die Welt said the order came from the East German Culture
Ministry and took effect on Saturday. The newspaper did not identify
its sources.
   East German leaders have resisted Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or openness, contending that a such
critical discussion of problems in East Germany is unnecessary.
   Gorbachev enjoys enormous popularity among East Germans, who hope
the Soviet leader's influence will bring about similar reforms in
their country.
   In recent months, East German authorities have cracked down on
the nation's Lutheran Church press, censoring or banning
publications dealing with human rights issues.
</TEXT>
