<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--WindmillFraud     11-23 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Windmill Fraud,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Guilty To Windmill Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who had nearly 100 people chasing
windmill dealerships has pleaded guilty to fraud.
   Joseph Leo Romah, Jr., 30, of Pittsburgh, pleaded guilty Tuesday
to 13 counts of mail fraud and two counts of interstate
transportation of fraudently obtained securities.
   Prosecutors say Romah operated Riggs Wind Energy Systems in
Carnegie from January 1983 to September 1985 and made false
representations regarding the ability of the company to provide
tested windmills, most of which were ostensibly to be used for
dealerships.
   The government said 74 people paid Romah more than $340,000 in
dealership fees and 20 people paid more than $140,000 in deposits on
the windmills.
   He entered his plea after a week of trial in which the government
had presented 20 witnesses.
   Romah faces up to 85 years in prison and a fine of $570,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
