<1ST_LINE>u a AM-JewelHeist     11-23 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jewel Heist,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Make Off With Nearly $4 Million In Jewels From Store</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five gunmen wearing Halloween masks
robbed a jewelry store of nearly $4 million in goods Tuesday using
smoke bombs to cover their escape and later firing at a pursuing
officer, police said.
   The robbers stormed the H.T. Stuart jewelry store in the Town
Center mall about 6:20 p.m., disarmed a security guard and pointed
automatic weapons at three employees.
   Witnesses said one man scooped the diamonds and jewelry into a
bag, and the gunmen detonated smoke devices before fleeing through a
side door.
   Several minutes after the heist, Palm Beach County sheriff's
Deputy Darryl Cates stopped a white van used by the robbers, who
fired at Cates' car. Windshields on the patrol car were shattered,
but Cates was unharmed.
   The van was later found in a nearby parking lot with the masks, a
loaded automatic pistol and some of the stolen jewels.
   Store owner Stuart Dopplet said he did not know the exact losses,
but offered the $4 million estimate, noting that the value of one
diamond necklace taken was about $2 million.
   ``To me it's an absolute nightmare,'' he said.
</TEXT>
