<1ST_LINE>r i PM-JealousyKillings     11-23 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jealousy Killings,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Policemen Kills Five People, Then Self</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LECCE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a jealous rage, a policeman killed his
former live-in lover, her three children and her aunt and then shot
himself to death with his service revolver, authorities said.
   The slayings occurred in Campi Salentina, a small farming town
just north of this coastal city in the Apulia region in the heel of
the Italian ``boot.''
   A Carabinieri spokesman identified the assailant as Giuseppe
Pagano, a policeman assigned to guarding maritime offices in the
nearby city of Brindisi. He was believed to be in his 40s, but his
exact age was not immediately known.
   The spokesman, speaking under ground rules of anonymity, said
Pagano entered the apartment of his ex-lover, 40-year-old Cosima
Leo, and opened fire with his revolver.
   The gunfire killed the woman, her 71-year-old aunt, her
16-year-old daughter and two sons, aged 12 and 2, the spokesman
said. Pagano then shot himself through the temple.
   The spokesman said Pagano apparently acted in a fit of jealousy,
but he would not elaborate. The Italian news agency AGI said Pagano
was jealous because the woman had decided to return to her husband.
   It was the second mass slaying involving Italian police in a week.
   On Nov. 16, five Carabinieri were shot to death in their barracks
near Ravenna in central Italy. Investigators said they believe one
of the policemen went berserk, sprayed the other four with
submachine-gun and pistol fire and then shot himself.
</TEXT>
