<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WaterQuality     11-23 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Water Quality,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Push For Program To Improve Water Quality Nationwide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ranking members of the Senate Agriculture
Committee are pushing for expansion of a major soil conservation
program in an effort to improve the nation's water quality.
   The lawmakers, led by panel chairman Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., are
asking Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng to broaden the focus of
the Conservation Reserve Program, which began in 1986.
   To date, some 25.5 million acres of farmland have been taken out
of production under the program, which is bringing participating
farmers an average of $50 a year for each acre not planted with
commercial crops.
   Most of the land falls into the category of highly erodible
terrain, which is stabilized with vegetation to minimize loss of
topsoil from precipitation and wind.
   But Leahy, Richard Lugar, R-Ind., Wyche Fowler, D-Ga., and
Christopher Bond, R-Mo., told Lyng in a letter released Tuesday that
they think it's time to broaden the program beyond combating soil
erosion.
   They said the eligibility guidelines should be expanded ``to
include croplands whose continued intensive use threatens surface
and groundwater.''
   ``With its emphasis almost entirely on highly erodible lands, the
department is missing a crucial opportunity to protect public health
and the environment,'' the senators wrote.
   Runoffs of pesticides and fertilizers are becoming an increasing
problem for both surface water and underground aquifers, according
to Kenneth Cook of the Conservation Foundation, a Washington
research group.
   The senators said that soil conservation also would be served by
allowing enrollment of land that is not classified as highly
erodible.
   ``The (department's) Economic Research Service has estimated that
targeting water quality could reduce the delivery of 90 million tons
of sediment to U.S. water annually,'' they said. ``This respresents
a 20 percent improvement over the existing program.''
   Jack Webb, chief of the department's land retirement and water
quality branch, said steps are being taken to make more than just
highly erodible land eligible for the $1.86 billion a year program.
   He said that earlier this year eligiblity was extended to
so-called filter strips _ parcels of land abutting waterways.
   Webb also said officials are preparing to propose rules that
would make another 10 million or more acres eligible for inclusion.
   These proposals are aimed at two areas: the Mississippi River
bottom lands from Baton Rouge, La., to Cairo, Ill., and the
so-called prairie pothole region of the northern Great Plains,
according to Webb.
</TEXT>
