<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 0109EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GOPGovernors     11-23 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GOP Governors,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Chiefs Claim Mainstream Position For Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POINT CLEAR, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican governors, folding the tent
on their national conference, are giving up jellybeans for fried
pork rinds.
   As Alabama Gov. Guy Hunt sees it, the jellybeans favored by
President Reagan are now giving way to ``the new symbol'' of the new
administration _ crisply fried hog skins, which President-elect
George Bush claims as a favorite snack.
   ``I guess it means we skin the hogs,'' Hunt quipped Tuesday as he
passed out packages of the fried rinds to members of the National
Republican Governors Conference as it closed its four-day meeting at
the Grand Hotel resort.
   The light moment came after Bush spoke to the GOP governors,
saying Republicans ``are on our way to becoming the majority party
in America, if we don't lose sight of what is driving our success.''
   ``We're off and running on a very positive note with this
administration as Republican governors,'' said Kansas Gov. Mike
Hayden, the new chairman of the conference, which heard from Bush
and several members of his new White House team.
   Delaware Gov. Michael N. Castle, outgoing chairman of the
conference, said the sessions made clear there has been ``a
fundamental change in the way the country is looking at its
governing and its policies.''
   ``You begin to realize it is very much the Republican Party that
is in the mainstream,'' said Castle.
   ``It's a changing scene,'' said Hunt, host of the conference at
the coastal resort.
   ``We're not the party of big business,'' said the Alabama
governor, a Primitive Baptist minister. ``I was born on a farm.''
   Hunt said before the conference that about $200,000 was raised
from private sources to put the meeting together at the resort.
Hosts for the meeting included several major oil companies with
interests in offshore tracts near the Alabama coast, along with
Waste Management Inc. and other corporations.
   Hunt, however, emphasized the GOP's ties to grassroots voters.
And Bush, in his speech, said Hunt ``is a man who has never
forgotten his roots.''
   Bush said Hunt's religious faith and political courage were
emblematic of the modern GOP.
   ``He still preaches on Sunday at his home church in Holly Pond, I
believe (is) the name of it,'' said Bush. ``Two years ago Guy had
the courage to step up into the fray or what Teddy Roosevelt called
the arena against what were considered enormous odds, and ... he
showed those pollsters wrong. And what an oustanding job he's doing
for Alabama.''
   Hunt, who got help from a fractured Democratic Party when he rose
from also-ran to winner in 1986, was cited often at the conference
as an example of a new Republican South.
   Republicans suffered a net loss of one governorship in the
November election, dropping from 23 to 22. But GOP leaders said it
was actually a strong showing, with more significant losses often
expected for a party already in power in the White House.
   Hayden said Bush's speech indicated the new president will be
``very close to the Reagan administration on economic policy.''
   But he said Bush demonstrated again that ``he's his own man.''
   Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad said the GOP conference at Point Clear
was the first such meeting ever held ``in the heart of Dixie.''
   Branstad, who will become chairman of the National Governors
Conference next year, said he looks forward to that group's meeting
at nearby Mobile in 1990.
   ``This humble country preacher really knows how to put on a great
conference,'' he said of Hunt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
