<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BudgetDeficit     11-23 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget Deficit,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drop In Deficit Gives Little Comfort To Budget Watchers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10.9 percent drop in the October federal
deficit over last year is offering little comfort to financial
markets and economists who expect only minimal improvement in the
budget gap this year.
   The Treasury Department said federal spending exceeded revenue by
$27.4 billion last month, the first month of the 1989 fiscal year,
down from $30.8 billion in the corresponding month a year ago.
   However, the $3.4 billion improvement was more than accounted for
by several special factors. Farm subsidy payments were down $2.3
billion thanks to higher commodity prices triggered by the summer
drought.
   And, military pay fell $2.6 billion because a year ago the
government shifted a pay period from 1987 to 1988. The accounting
trick made the 1987 deficit abnormally low and the 1988 budget gap
worse than otherwise.
   The Reagan administration is projecting the budget deficit in
fiscal 1989 will shrink to $145.5 billion, down from $155.1 billion
in the year ended Sept. 30. The Congressional Budget Office
forecasts $148 billion in red ink.
   But, most private economists are projecting a 1989 deficit little
improved and perhaps worse than 1988. In fact, fears in the markets
concerning President-elect George Bush's ability to curb the deficit
without breaking his no-tax pledge have driven the value of the
dollar down since his election.
   ``Foreign investors, who are financing a significant portion of
the seemingly endless budget deficit, are concerned about the
prospects for reduction in the Bush administration,'' said David
Jones, an economist with Aubrey G. Lanston & Co., a government
securities dealer in New York.
   He cited several factors, including the cleanup of the
government's nuclear plants and the rescue of the savings and loan
industry, that will demand new and higher government expenditures.
   In October, the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., which
backs S&L deposits up to $100,000, spent $1 billion, compared with
$98 million a year ago.
   Also, the administration's economic forecast underlying its
budget projection _ higher growth and lower interest rates _
conflicts with the more pessimistic view of most private analysts.
   Beryl Sprinkel, President Reagan's chief economic adviser, said
Tuesday that the economy as measured by the Gross National Product
will grow 3.5 percent. Private economists, however, expect growth of
only 2 to 2.5 percent. Consequently, they believe the government
will collect less tax revenue. They also project higher interest
rates than the government, making it more costly to finance the $2.6
trillion national debt.
   ``We may have a few months that look better than last year, but I
don't think that can last,'' said Bruce Steinberg, an economist with
Merrill Lynch. ``I suspect we'll see a deficit similar to last
year's; $150 billion to $160 billion is quite likely.''
   Government revenue in October totaled $63.6 billion, up 2.1
percent from the same month a year ago. Spending totaled $91.1
billion, down 2.2 percent.
   The largest spending categories in October were the military
followed by Social Security, interest on the national debt and
programs in the Department of Health and Human Services other than
Social Security.
   Military spending totaled $25.2 billion last month, down 0.3
percent from the same month a year ago.
   Spending for Social Security totaled $17.5 billion last month, up
5.4 percent. The other programs in the Department of Health and
Human Services, including Medicare and Medicaid, cost $11.7 billion
in October, a 16.8 percent decline over fiscal 1988.
   Interest on the national debt totaled $15.2 billion last month,
an increase of 7.4 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
