<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 0128EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     11-23 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christopher Walken Stars in `Coriolanus'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A presentation of Shakespeare's political tragedy
``Coriolanus'' so soon after Election Day may seem apt, but the New
York Shakespeare Festival production evokes the world of rock stars
more than that of presidential candidates.
   Christopher Walken, in the title role, is known primarily from
films but has acted other classical roles at the off-Broadway Public
Theater, where ``Coriolanus'' opened Tuesday night.
   He makes the part funnier than one might expect and the play less
tragic. Coriolanus is the equivalent of a Roman five-star general.
He comes back, victorious, and is expected to put on a cloak of
poverty and display wounds, after which the people will acclaim him
a Consul. He thinks that's dishonest; he is what he is, a successful
soldier, not given to pretending poverty or anything else to seek
favor.
   His two enemies say he's proud. He acts humble. The necktieless
Walken shows humility in a perfect imitation of some top rock stars'
self-deprecating humor. Ask Phil Collins if he's special and he'd
probably reply he's an ordinary bloke. The Beatles used to deflect
adulation with wit.
   What Walken doesn't do is address whether, underneath, Coriolanus
is proud or not. His characterization is understandable in
contemporary terms and rock stars are often more interesting than
politicos. But it's more simple than the play and therefore doesn't
allow his eventual destruction to fulfill the title, ``The Tragedy
of Coriolanus.''
   Irene Worth plays the silver-tongued, dominating mother who has
instilled warlike qualities in her son and glories in them. However,
she can't bring him up to her equal in brains or cunning. She calls
herself Juno-like in the play and Miss Worth certainly lives up to
the larger-than-life passions of that goddess.
   Broadway veteran Paul Hecht displays a statesmanlike demeanor and
authoritative voice as Menenius, who is pro-Coriolanus. Keith David
is stalwart, while knowing he is jealous of Coriolanus' popularity,
as Aufidius, general opposing Coriolanus in war.
   Moses Gunn and Thomas Kopache speak well and appropriately as
Roman generals.
   The two tribunes who inflame the people against Coriolanus are
more one-dimensionally self-interested than sometimes played.
Sharp-featured Larry Bryggman, cast as a villain on TV, and Andre
Braugher were directed by Steven Berkoff to walk in lockstep and
dress like Mafia henchmen. They could be played to show some concern
for the people or the state.
   Battles are choreographed motions, without prop swords. Since the
same actors make up both armies, a battle scene takes place with
whichever army is on stage, individuals ``fighting'' unseen
opponents.
   Some speeches are cut, mostly by peripheral people. Coriolanus'
son doesn't appear. The scene in which a Roman tells one of
Aufidius' men that Coriolanus is banished from Rome is gone but the
play isn't damaged by making his arrival before Aufidius a surprise.
   ``Coriolanus,'' in the Public Theater's Anspacher Theater, is the
sixth in the festival's ``Shakespeare Marathon'' which will present
all 36 plays. It's the first obscure one but, thus far, among the
more successful presentations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881123-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 0040EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Onassis     11-23 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Onassis,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Approve Transfer Of Greek Heiress' Body</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judges granted approval early
Wednesday to take the body of Greek heiress Christina Onassis out of
the country for burial on a Greek island.
   Family and friends were expected to pick up the casket at 8:30
a.m. at the archbishopric of the Greek Orthodox Church, where it has
lain since Saturday, the private news agency Diarios y Noticias said.
   The agency quoted unidentified government sources as saying
Federal Judge Alberto Piotti and other judges who had jurisdiction
in the case accepted Interior Minister Enrique Nosiglia's request
that the proceeding be expedited to avoid diplomatic problems.
   Ms. Onassis, 37, died suddenly on Saturday morning.
   A preliminary coroner's report on Monday said the cause of death
was acute pulmonary edema, or an accumulation of fluid in her lungs.
It did not say what caused the accumulation.
   Determination of the cause of death has held up delivery of Ms.
Onassis' body to family members, who intend to take it for burial in
a mausoleum on the family-owned island of Skorpios in the Ionian Sea.
   Ms. Onassis inherited a fortune estimated at $500 million from
her father Aristotle, who died in 1975.
</TEXT>
