<2ND_LINE>AM-Cooper-Parachute, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0784,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Divers Say They Found Piece Of Cooper Parachute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 7-8 bgng `Rainey plans' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
comment from doubting chute packer; picks up 9th graf pvs, `The
FBI....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB BAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A diver seeking clues to the fate of D.B.
Cooper, the legendary hijacker who disappeared 17 years ago, says he
found a small parachute in the Columbia River about a mile upstream
from where $5,800 of Cooper's ransom washed up in 1980.
   The diver, 33-year-old Curtis Rainey of Portland, Ore., was
working for Richard Tosaw, a lawyer from Ceres, Calif., who has
spent each Thanksgiving season for seven years searching for
Cooper's remains.
   The nylon ``pilot'' parachute, used for deploying the main canopy
of a parachute such as the one Cooper had, was found Monday about 5
miles west of Vancouver on the Washington side of the river, Rainey
and Tosaw said.
   Cooper parachuted out of a Northwest Air Lines 727 with $200,000
in ransom money on Thanksgiving Eve, 1971. Except for the
waterlogged bills that washed up on the banks of the Columbia nine
years later, no trace of him has ever turned up.
   Tosaw admitted there could be many explanations for the
discovery, but he noted it was the most interesting piece of
evidence he's found since he made the Cooper search his hobby.
   ``The interesting thing is it was found in a place where he
pretty much has to be, give or take a mile or so,'' Tosaw said.
   Rainey planned to take the parachute on Thanksgiving to
Woodinville to be examined by Earl Cossey, who packed Cooper's
parachute.
   However, Cossey said late Tuesday that he had been given a
description of the pilot chute by telephone, and it sounded like it
was from an earlier design than the one Cooper used.
   ``There are probably a million of those in the world,'' Cossey
said. While the main parachute would be identifiable by stitching or
possibly a registration number, the pilot chute would bear no
identifying marks, he said.
   The FBI said Tosaw hadn't informed the agency of the discovery.
   ``We would be able to identify these parachutes but the process
would be part of our investigation and therefore something we
wouldn't comment on,'' said John Eyer of the Seattle FBI office.
   Tosaw, who has written a book titled ``D.B. Cooper, Dead or
Alive,'' said he has decided Cooper drowned and his remains became
hung up on one of the rows of pilings that extend into the river
about every half-mile to prevent erosion.
   The parachute was found snagged among such pilings about a mile
upstream from the beach where 8-year-old Brian Ingram found $5,800
of Cooper's loot in 1980, Tosaw said.
   Rainey, who along with diving partner Jamie Winkle of Portland
has worked for Tosaw on the Cooper search for three years, found the
parachute mostly intact and barely sticking out of the sand under
about 20 feet of water, the divers said.
   Cooper got his ransom and parachutes during a Seattle stopover
after hijacking a flight by displaying what appeared to be dynamite.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
