<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     11-23 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Noah the Boa is a free snake again
after nearly four days of captivity in the dashboard of a car
belonging to one of his red-faced handlers.
   Judy Booth of the J.L. Johnson Nature Center said she drove the
6-pound, 5-foot-long boa constrictor to a preschool for a Friday
morning presentation.
   ``I put him back in the car and went to lunch for about an
hour,'' Booth said. ``That was a big mistake.''
   Noah, probably spooked by unfamiliar surroundings, slithered out
of his pillowcase carrier and under the dashboard, she said.
   After failing to lure the serpent out with morsels of his
favorite foods, she was forced to spend the weekend keeping Noah
warm with a heat lamp.
   Booth took the car to a auto dealership Monday, where Rick
Hetchler and another mechanic freed the snake as about two dozen
people watched.
   ``I don't see any puncture wounds,'' Booth said after inspecting
Noah. ``I think he's OK.''
   ``It was no big deal,'' Hetchler said. ``It's just a snake. The
fun part will be putting the dashboard back together.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zeke Zzyzus has done it again, but he's had to
add another Z to his name.
   Now he's Zeke Zzzyzus, with three initial Zs instead of two, and
once again he's last in the latest Montreal telephone book.
   It was a close race for last, but he's been in training for the
past two books.
   In the previous phone book, he edged out Sunta Zzymox, who's
disappeared without a trace.
   Newcomers this time are Zzyzyx without a first name, Pol Zzyzzo
and Zzzap Distribution.
   Zzzyzus first became last two years ago, when he was a student at
Concordia University. At the time, he said he was determined to stay
last no matter how many Zs it takes.
</TEXT>
