<1ST_LINE>r w PM-KreegerCollection     11-23 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kreeger Collection,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Art Collector Will Leaves Home, Collection as Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Lloyd Kreeger, one of Washington's most
noted art collectors, says he and his wife intend to have the public
one day browse through their modernistic home and enjoy their
massive collection of 19th and 20th Century art.
   The Kreegers disclosed Wednesday that they will leave their
Foxhall Road home, designed by architect Philip Johnson, to a
foundation, which they will establish, so that the modernistic home
can be turned into a museum where the collection will be on display.
   The value of the Kreeger collection is not known. Four years ago,
well before the dramatic escalation of art prices, it was valued at
an estimated $30 million. Their home has been assessed at $3.3
million, but is worth much more than that on the market.
   Kreeger, 79, is a former president of Government Employees
Insurance Co., and has a net worth believed to be between $50
million and $75 million.
   The gift established by the Kreegers will include an endowment in
the millions of dollars to operate the museum. The Kreegers' two
children will be trustees of the art collection which includes many
impressionist and post-impressionist pieces.
   The Kreegers began buying paintings in l952. Their collection
includes the pre-blue-period Picasso `Cafe La Rotonde' and a late
Claude Monet, ``Misty River Scene''.
   There are paintings by more than 100 artists such as van Gogh,
Degas, Renoir, Bonnard, Kandinsky, Sisley, Corot, Rouault, Dufy,
Pissarro, Utrillo, Courbet, Braque, Avery, and Dubuffet.
   Sculptures by Arp, Picasso, Lipschitz, Noguchi and Moore, among
others, are in a courtyard that surrounds a swimming pool.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881123-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 0201EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BreastImplants     11-23 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Breast Implants,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Advisory Panel Urges Indepth Study Of Breast Implants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal advisory panel is calling for a
long-term study of the safety of silicone breast implants but says
there is not enough evidence of health risk now to ban the procedure.
   An estimated 2 million U.S. women have received implants over the
past two decades even though the Food and Drug Administration has
never fully reviewed how safe they are.
   A seven-member panel of outside experts convened by the agency
concluded Tuesday that the FDA should work with physicians, patients
and silicone implant manufacturers to design a series of studies
that will fully address the question over the next few years.
   Meanwhile, the committee agreed unanimously that there is no
reason to call for a ban on new implants unless new and substantial
evidence of harm surfaces before the group meets again in two months.
   Dr. John H. Davis, chairman of surgery at the University of
Vermont medical school, told fellow panelists he had never done a
breast implant but could speak as a husband and father of three
daughters.
   He said the procedure has been ``a great boon to women'' and that
since no comparable substitute is available, ``I don't believe I can
throw it out the window and say no.''
   About 15 percent of breast implants are done for women who have
lost part or all of their breasts to cancer surgery and Davis said
denying them access to reconstructive surgery might influence some
to ``accept the wrong kind of threatment or retreat'' from seeking
early treatment at all.
   He acknowledged that it will take a long time _ perhaps decades _
to definitely determine the safety of breast implants.
   ``We will not answer this question for the women in this room,
unfortunately, but we can answer it for your children,'' said Davis.
   Dr. Geneviene M. Matanoski, an epidemologist at Johns Hopkins,
agreed with Davis' assessment of the difficulties in compiling
definitive data over a period of years.
   ``Certainly the answer is not to panic 2 million women,'' she
said in concurring with the panel's unanimous recommendation against
calling for a ban.
   Dr. Sidney Wolfe of Public Citizen Health Research Group has
called for a ban, based largely on recent studies that showed
silicone implants caused certain types of cancer in rats.
   However, there are substantial questions about whether human
tissue reacts the same way as rat tissue when confronted with
foreign tissue, particularly in developing the type of tumors caused
in the rats.
   Dr. John E. Martin, appearing on behalf of the American College
of Radiology, told the panel that of the thousands of women who have
sought treatment for breast cancer at the M.D. Anderson Cancer
Center in Texas over the past 40 years, only 35 had the type of
tumor the rat studies suggested might occur in humans subjected to
silicone transplants.
   Martin said no such breast cancers had been seen at M.D. Anderson
in the past 10 years and decried what he called ``unfortunate
publicity associated with this scare.''
   He compared the recent concern by women about breast implants
with earlier questions about whether the radiation associated with a
breast X-ray argued against using the procedure as a screening
device. By the time those questions had been resolved in the
negative, he said, ``The emotional damage to women had already been
done.''
   The advisory committee called for:
   _Establishment of a national registry of women who have breast
implants so long-range studies can be carried out to determine
whether there is a heightened risk of breast cancer or other health
problems.
   _Drafting of a mandatory, standardized consent form to be signed
by any prospective patient for a breast implant before the procedure
can be done.
   _An FDA policy to keep physicians and the public aware of any new
information as it develops from whatever long-range studies are
devised.
   Since silicone breast implants were already on the market in 1976
when Congress gave the FDA authority over medical devices, they were
given ``grandfather'' approval under the law.
   Now the FDA has invoked essentially the same procedure that would
be used to establish the safety of a new product, but has no
standing to remove breast implants from the market in the absence of
clear evidence that they are a definite health risk.
   The significance of the advisory panel's conclusion was that it
saw no evidence of such a clear risk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
