<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hospital-Smoking     11-23 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital-Smoking,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No-Smoking Policy Leaves Patients, Docs Out In Cold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUDAHY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital's anti-smoking policy has gone up
in smoke because it sent so many patients, doctors and nurses
outside to light up.
   Trinity Memorial Hospital was among the Milwaukee area hospitals
that became smoke-free as of July 4, with smoking either banned or
severely restricted.
   The edict at Trinity Memorial meant smokers had no alternative
but to go outside, ``and they persisted in doing so,'' said James
Streed, a hospital spokesman.
   The resulting problems, he said, included:
   _Patients began congregating outdoors in their hospital gowns,
even though many of them had to drag their intravenous equipment
with them.
   _Nurses sometimes had to accompany the patients, which took
personnel away from work stations.
   _Some nurses, physicians and other employees also went outdoors
to smoke, and while outside were unable to hear the paging system.
   After four months, it was decided that for the sake of patient
safety, smokers would be brought back indoors under a relaxed
policy, Streed said this week.
   Smoking now is allowed in designated areas of the coffee shop and
employee cafeteria, he said.
   Although ventilation in the two designated smoking areas has been
improved to keep smoke out of non-smoking areas, the new policy has
rekindled some of the past debate over the issue.
   ``It gets to be a bit like legislating morality,'' Streed said.
``The smokers feel it's about time that they're accommodated more
humanely.''
   On the other hand, he said, the non-smokers felt that it was
hypocritical for a hospital to allow people to pursue an unhealthy
habit on its premises.
   ``People are people, and they're all different,'' Streed said.
``To deal with stress, some people do unhealthy things.''
   ``We're not doing anything to encourage smoking,'' he said. ``We
don't sell tobacco.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
