<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 0242EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UraniumCleanup     11-23 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Uranium Cleanup,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement to Clean Up Nuclear Plant Seen as Model for Other Waste
Sites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CHALFANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landmark agreement under which the U.S.
government will conduct a $50 million cleanup of a
uranium-enrichment plant could become a model for dealing with other
toxic waste sites, officials said.
   The agreement covering the Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion Plant
near Piketon in southern Ohio was significant because the U.S.
Department of Energy would be bound by state law and regulation,
said Gov. Richard Celeste.
   ``The Department of Energy is now voluntarily, without court
action, declaring itself, in effect, free from sovereign immunity,''
Celeste told a news conference Tuesday. ``They're acknowledging that
they must be accountable under the environmental laws of the state
of Ohio. ...
   ``It's a good arrangement, and I would hope that it could become
a model for other tough cases that we're wrestling with, like that
at Fernald,'' Celeste said.
   The federally owned Fernald plant near Cincinnati has dumped
radioactive waste improperly, possibly contaminating ground water,
since it began processing uranium for nuclear weapons in 1951,
according to environmental officials.
   The Piketon plant, which processes uranium for fuel for nuclear
power reactors, generates toxic wastes such as polychlorinated
byphenyls or PCBs, solvents and metals, as well as radioactive
materials.
   The settlement provides for the Energy Department to be subject
to newly issued orders from the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency
requiring a comprehensive cleanup of the site under state
supervision.
   Details of the pact still must be incorporated into a federal
court consent decree.
   ``It's a very large step forward and a significant shift in their
own policies and their own attitudes,'' said state Attorney General
Anthony J. Celebrezze Jr.
   Increasing congressional and public scrutiny of the nuclear waste
problem helped change the Energy Department's stance, he added.
   ``Anytime somebody that has a say over your budget starts putting
heat on you, people tend to react,'' he said. ``The other thing I
think that was a factor is that very simply the Department of Energy
was perceiving that it had truly an image problem with the sort of
arrogant attitude that they were taking.''
   The Energy Department has disclosed problems at some of its
nuclear production plants and has wholly or partly closed down four
of its 17 major plants. Officials have estimated cleanup will cost
$110 billion.
   Celebrezze said the agreement didn't address the question of
fines for pollution violations, but talks are continuing between
state and federal officials.
   ``We're negotiating, and any time we start talking about
penalties and fines you get to very sensitive parts of the
negotiations,'' Celebrezze said. ``I just don't even want to
speculate on that.''
   Piketon site manager Gene Gillespie said the Department of Energy
had agreed to clean up roughly 6 million pounds of wastes after a
final negotiating session Nov. 7.
   ``There's a lot of things involved. We're cleaning up waste that
had been generated over the past 30 years, a lot of things that were
accepted practices in the past that aren't any more,'' Gillespie
said.
   The cleanup may cost more than $50 million during the next five
years, he said. The department's fiscal 1989 budget sets aside $10
million for the first phase.
   Robert E. Anderson, environmental coordinator for Martin Marietta
Energy Systems, the contractor that operates Piketon, said some
cleanup was started in 1987 and continued this year during
negotiations.
   He said the toxic solvent levels in ground water at the site are
``tens to hundreds of times'' the acceptable levels for drinking
water.
   Bedrock separates the ground water at the site from the Teays
Valley Aquifer that provides drinking water for the area, he said,
adding that it would take 10 to 15 years for contaminated water to
leave the site.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
