<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Press     11-23 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Press,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalists Protest Restrictions On Palestinian Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli journalists say government orders
restricting news coverage of the PLO and the Palestinian uprising
make Israel look like Arab nations whose news coverage is completely
under government control.
   ``There is a political consensus to stop information from coming
out,'' Elisha Shpiegelman, head of the Jerusalem Journalists
Association, told about 300 people at a rally Tuesday. Other
meetings were held in Tel Aviv and Haifa.
   The protests followed a government order to restrict coverage of
the Palestine National Council meeting in Algiers last week during
which a Palestinian state was proclaimed.
   The order banned coverage of speeches at the council session and
affected Israel's state-run television and radio. The council acts
as legislature for the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   ``Syria, Egypt and Jordan did not broadcast the conference. Are
we democracies like they are?'' said Gabi Brun, a union leader at
the newspaper Yediot Ahronot newspaper.
   Israel Broadcast Authority officials said they acted at the
request of Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who feared televised
excerpts of the council session would fuel the year-long Palestinian
uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``It's not a form of censorship, it's a form of exercising our
editorial function,'' said Ari Avneri, an aide to broadcast
authority chief Uri Porat.
   TV correspondent Moshe Raz said broadcast journalists must refer
to the occupied lands by their biblical names, a practice that
implies Israel has an ancient right to the areas, which it seized in
the 1967 Middle East war.
   ``One day they decided that there was no West Bank and Gaza
Strip, only Judea, Samaria and the Gaza District,'' Raz said.
   He said television news is required to call PLO members
``terrorists'' whether or not they belonged to a military wing of
the PLO.
   Shpiegelman said journalists who violate the unwritten guidelines
or complain are asked to resign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
