<DOCNO> AP881123-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 0258EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ArtError     11-23 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Art Error,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auction House Fined For Peddling Paintings For Peanuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ordered an auction house to pay a woman
$200,000 for failing to recognize a pair of paintings as possible
masterworks, and then selling them for just one-tenth of their worth.
   High Court Judge Simon Brown on Tuesday ordered Messenger May
Baverstock to pay damages to Penelope Luxmoore-May for botching the
1985 auction of two paintings that were in the style of 18th century
master George Stubbs.
   The paintings, renderings of foxhounds, were sold by the auction
house for $1,500.
   They were purchased by an art dealer, who subsequently sold them
through the Sotheby's auction house as the work of Stubbs for
$162,000. They were subsequently sold again for an undisclosed price
to American multi-millionaire Paul Mellon.
   Brown ruled that it wasn't necessary for the court to determine
whether the paintings were in fact Stubbs' work.
   ``Their error lay not in failing to make a positive Stubbs
attribution _ they did not themselves have the expertise to do that
any more than to the contrary _ but rather in their failure to spot
the potential in these paintings,'' he said.
   An art expert testified during the trial that she could not
verify the authenticity of the paintings, but said there was an 85
percent chance they were painted not by Stubbs, but by a 19th
century admirer.
   Mrs. Luxmoore-May said she was ``absolutely delighted'' with the
$200,000 judgement. She said she went to the auctioneers because her
husband was a former director.
   ``I would prefer to have the pictures on my wall knowing they
were by Stubbs than have the damages,'' she said.
   Mrs. Luxmoore-May, a magistrate, testified that she was given the
paintings in 1948 by a family friend. But she said she and her
husband never liked them.
   Paul Thomas, the expert at Messenger May Baverstock, said he
thought the paintings were badly drawn and without quality, so he
valued them at $54 to $90.
   Brown said the Luxmoore-Mays were ``mortified'' to read on the
front page of The Times of London some months later that the
pictures had been bought by Spinks, fine art dealers, for $162,000.
   Spinks later sold them to Mellon for an undisclosed sum.
   Mrs. Luxmoore-May, 66, sued for breach of contract and failure to
exercise reasonable skill and care in its valuation and sale in
October 1985 in Godalming, 35 miles southwest of London.
   Stubbs, who lived from 1724 to 1806, is regarded as England's
finest animal painter.
</TEXT>
