<DOCNO> AP881123-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 0306EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-JFK-Dallas Bjt   11-23 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-JFK-Dallas, Bjt,0694</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mourners Drop Flowers, Other Memorabilia At Assassination Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK GODICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands made a pilgrimage to Dealey Plaza to
honor John F. Kennedy with prayers and tears and by dropping
bouquets and Kennedy half-dollars in the street where the president
was assassinated 25 years ago.
   ``It's just something to remember him by,'' Alvin Marin of
suburban Farmers Branch said Tuesday as he laid down the crucifix he
said he had grasped upon hearing of Kennedy's assassination. ``This
is very emotional.''
   Howard Hartog of Edgerton, Minn., drove more than 900 miles for
the anniversary, then was among the first to drop flowers at the
approximate spot by a grassy knoll where the president was gunned
down.
   ``I found myself fighting back tears,'' said Hartog, moments
after leaving a red rose. ``That's where the uplift came, from the
spontaneity that occurred when that first flower was dropped.''
   Although Dallas held no official ceremony, about 2,500 people
gathered along Elm Street to pass the anniversary hour of Kennedy's
death as he rode by in a motorcade. At 12:29 p.m. _ the time of the
fatal shots _ mourners began dropping bouquets of flowers,
half-dollars and other memorabilia on the street.
   ``It was a show of camaraderie,'' Hartog said.
   The flowers remained on the street and passing motorists were
careful to avoid them, backing up traffic downtown. A note attached
to one bouquet said, ``After 25 years, we still love you, John.''
Another said, ``We still miss you _ Nov. 22.'' About 20 people
clapsed hands in a loose chain along the motorcade route.
   At the flower-draped stone memorial about 200 yards away, where
one card read, ``Dallas Loves JFK Too!'' a few people knelt in
prayer. Others snapped pictures of the memorial and the Texas School
Book Depository Building, where police found Lee Harvey Oswald's
rifle.
   The building's sixth floor, where authorities believe the shots
were fired, is being converted to a museum by the Dallas County
Historical Foundation and is expected to open Feb. 20, President's
Day.
   Elsewhere, members of the Kennedy family observed the anniversary
in mostly private services. Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis attended a
private Mass in New York City along with her son, John, and
daughter, Caroline. Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., placed a white
rose on a monument honoring his brother n Runnymede, England.
   Eunice Kennedy Shriver, the late president's sister, visited his
grave and that of her brother Robert, at Arlington National Cemetery
in Virginia and said she hopes people remember ``the high points of
his life, the laughter and the vision.''
   The lack of official ceremonies in Dallas and elsewhere were
mostly in deference to a request from the president's family his
birthday on May 29 be marked instead of the assassination.
   However, Jean Hill of Dallas said she had something important to
impart to her class of 50 third-grade students who visited the site.
   ``Although this was a traumatic event, I want them to feel they
are a part of America's history,'' she said. ``We're here because
this is an important place in Dallas, an important place in
history.''
   Ms. Hill said she had been waiting at Dealey Plaza on Nov. 22,
1963, to see the president's motorcade. She jumped from the curb and
hollered at Kennedy to turn her way for a picture, then the shots
rang out.
   ``I could have touched the car when I jumped out into the
street,'' she said. The anniversary ``is bringing all of those
anxiety feelings and traumatic feelings back to me. The nightmares
are coming back.''
   At Parkland Memorial Hospital, where the mortally wounded
president was taken, a panel of 11 employees recounted their
experiences from the tragic day with about 200 hospital staff
members.
   ``It was as hopeless as anything we ever worked on,'' said
Charles Baxter, assistant professor of surgery and director of the
emergency room at the time. ``The emotion in the room would have
said to try and do something, even though it was a hopeless
situation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881123-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 0325EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Peru     11-23 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Besieged Government Devalues Currency By 50 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an attempt to deal with a shrinking economy
and runaway inflation, the government has devalued Peru's currency
by 50 percent and imposed other severe austerity measures including
food price increases.
   Also Tuesday, leftist rebels launched a mortar attack on the Lima
headquarters of the national security police and raided an isolated
mountain town, capping a four-day wave of violence that has killed
41 people.
   Though the country's two main leftist insurgencies are a serious
problem for the government of President Alan Garcia, they do not
pose as daunting a threat as Peru's grave economic crisis.
   Announcing the devaluation of the inti, Economy Minister Abel
Salinas also said the government would eliminate subsidies for basic
food products in stages over the next six months because it lacks
the money to finance them.
   The first reduction will be implemented immediately and will
double the prices of some food staples, Salinas said in a nationwide
television address.
   Severe economic measures implemented by the government in early
September, including an 86 percent currency devaluation, did not
succeed in reducing the country's huge deficit, said Salinas.
   Independent economists estimate the deficit has since increased
from 16 percent to 18 percent of the gross national product.
Inflation is expected to reach an annual 1,500 percent this year.
   Salinas said the curency's official exchange rate was being
devalued from 250 intis per dollar to 500 intis per dollar to boost
exports and bring in badly needed dollars.
   The inti traded Tuesday on the parallel market _ a legal
free-market currency exchange _ for 625 to the dollar.
   To offset the measures' impact on the poor, the government
decreed an increase in the monthly minimum wage from 15,000 to
24,000 intis.
   Sporadic food rioting broke out after the September austerity
package was announced.
   At one point, Garcia offered to resign but was persuaded by
leaders of his populist Aprista Party to stay, according to senior
government officials.
   Garcia took office in 1985 and gained international attention
when he defiantly set a ceiling on the country's foreign debt
payments equal to 10 percent of export earnings.
   He used the money to generate record economic growth of 8.5
percent in 1986 and 6.7 percent in 1987. But Peru has exhausted its
hard currency reserves and the government has said the economy will
shrink by at least 6 percent this year.
   Authorities said one policeman was killed, three were wounded and
two were missing Tuesday in the raid on the mountain community of
Cotahuasi, 335 miles southeast of Lima. They said rebels of the
Maoist-inspired Shining Path guerrilla movement carried out the raid.
   No one was reported injured in the Lima attack by the pro-Cuba
Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
