<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SantaSchool Bjt   11-23 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Santa School, Bjt,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Santas Learn How-Tos of Ho-Ho-Ho-ing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If would-be Kris Kringles have a love for
children, a twinkle in their eye and a desire to spread holiday
cheer, Santa school teacher Dick Lewis can teach them the rest.
   ``Screaming kids, shin-kickers, hecklers,'' Lewis said. ``We
teach them to deal with everything.''
   Everything from the proper way to wear their Santa hats to how to
chortle like a pro, said Lewis, who trains Santas for Western
Temporary Services.
   Retirees, character actors and a 19-year-old college student
donned red velveteen suits and ersatz beards at the John Wanamaker
department store and got the how-tos of ho-ho-ho-ing from Lewis on
Tuesday, three days before the start of the Christmas shopping
season.
   A Santa himself before he joined Western, Lewis has an eye for
the compassion and demeanor that makes a good Claus.
   ``We want people with a sincere desire to make children happy at
Christmas time,'' he said.
   Despite the professional, almost production-line approach to
training Santas, and the commercialism of the department-store
Kringles, Lewis advised his 10 students to remember their
responsibility to uphold the spirit of the holiday.
   ``These days and times there are going to be a lot of children
who are not going to have a happy holiday,'' Lewis said. ``At that
point in time, we need to be that special moment.''
   The temporary help company trains and employs 2,500 to 3,000
Santas each year for department stores, promotional and community
events throughout the country.
   Tuesday's training program, which lasted less than an hour but
usually runs longer, gives the basics of being Santa:
   _How to dress the part. Cap tassle always in front, beard hooked
around the top of the head, so it doesn't slip, two pairs of white
gloves, to be washed each day.
   _How to laugh in Santa's deep voice without scaring the child. No
loud ho-ho-ho's, but a low chortle coming from the stomach.
   _How to deal with difficult questions. Little girls often ask for
a little brother, Lewis said, and ``some kids are going to ask for a
bed.'' One child in Pittsburgh asked ``for Daddy to stop beating
me,'' he said.
   _A reminder to protect the shins when kids come flying up to the
chair, but always say ``ouch!'' when they tug on the beard.
   _And one of the cardinal rules _ always stay in character. ``No
matter what happens, you, each one of you, are the real Santa.''
   There were also tips from St. Nicks like Larry Dowd, who after 30
years as a Santa no longer needs artificial padding to play the role.
   ``I think I fill the suit out more,'' he said when asked if he'd
become a better Claus over the years. ``I used to use a pillow.''
   The kids, however, haven't changed at all, which is why Dowd will
come in before his regular night job supervising a custodial crew
and work a six-hour shift, talking with as many as 200 children.
   ``The kids really light up your life,'' said Dowd, 50. ``That's
the part of Christmas I really like.''
   Dowd and another Claus, Ned Holbrook, agreed Santas are born, not
made.
   ``I just think that you either have the natural training to be
one or you don't,'' said Holbrook, a character actor from
Philadelphia.
   But Holbrook, who said he prepares for being Santa as he would
for a dramatic role, is sometimes caught off-guard, such as the time
a retarded woman sat on his lap and asked him to bring back her dead
father.
   She gave him a kiss after his best attempt to deal with her wish.
   ``Now that's faith,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
