<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HolidayTraffic     11-23 0111</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Holiday Traffic,0113</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Safety Council: 450-550 May Die in Weekend Traffic Accidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of Americans will take to the nation's
roads as families and friends meet to celebrate Thanksgiving.
   The National Safety Council said between 450 and 550 people may
die in traffic accidents during the period, which for counting
purposes extends from 6 p.m. Wednesday to midnight Sunday local time.
   Council statisticians said about 390 people could be expected to
be killed on the highways during a four-day non-holiday period this
time of year.
   Last year, there were 494 highway deaths during the four-day
Thanksgiving period. The deadliest was in 1968, when 764 people were
killed.
</TEXT>
