<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 0517EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WhoIsAJew     11-23 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Who Is A Jew,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Orthodox Rabbis Split with Israeli Orthodox Position</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main U.S. alliance of Orthodox rabbis
reportedly has split with the Orthodox religious parties in Israel
that have been calling for a change in the legal definition of who
is a Jew.
   In a telegram sent Tuesday to Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir, the Rabbinical Council of America said it ``supports removal
of this issue from the political agenda,'' The New York Times
reported today.
   The council, a moderate Orthodox group, said it was acting ``to
preserve the unity and support of the American Jewish community with
and for Israel.''
   The council says is represents about 1,000 Orthodox rabbis, or 90
percent of those with major congregations across the country. It is
the first Orthodox group to state that the attempt to legally define
Jewishness by Israel should be dropped.
   Israel's Orthodox parties hold the balance of power in the
formation of a government in the Knesset, Israel's parliament, and
have pressed for a change in the Law of Return. The law now grants
all Jews immediate Israeli citizenship.
   The religious parties want it changed to say that the only
converts to Judaism eligible for Israeli citizenship must be
converted according to Orthodox religious law.
   The telegram, signed by the council's president, Rabbi Max
Schreier, and its executive vice president, Rabbi Binyamin Walfish,
said that they support the primacy of Orthodox conversions, but that
standards for conversion belong ``in the hands of the rabbinate and
not in the secular Knesset.''
   The council's position puts it in conflict with the Lubavitcher
Hasidim of Brooklyn, whose grand rabbi, Menachem M. Schneerson, has
been a force behind the effort to change the Israeli law.
   A study last year by the Council of Jewish Federations found that
9 percent of America's 5 million to 6 million Jews identify
themselves as Orthodox, 34 percent as Conservative and 30 percent as
Reform. Twenty-seven percent expressed no affiliation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
