<DOCNO> AP881123-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 0536EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Politics     11-23 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Politics,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Proposes Anti-IRA Measures; Sale Of State-Owned
Utilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outlining its legislative program for the coming
year, the government announced new moves against the IRA that will
include making candidates in Northern Ireland sign an oath
renouncing violence.
   The program, comprising 16 proposed bills, was read out by Queen
Elizabeth II on Tuesday at the traditional opening of Parliament in
the House of Lords, the unelected upper chamber.
   The speech also spelled out government plans to sell off the
state-owned water and electricity utilities. Denounced by the
opposition Labor Party, the sales are the biggest and most
controversial of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's massive program
of selling off state-owned assets to private enterprise and will
raise an estimated $55 billion.
   The program detailed in the queen's speech is the tenth written
by Mrs. Thatcher's Conservative government.
   One proposed bill would give authorities wide powers to probe and
seize suspected Irish Republican Army funds.
   ``The government is determined never to give in to the
terrorist,'' Mrs. Thatcher declared in the House of Commons later
Tuesday, launching a six-day debate on the legislative program.
   Despite protests from the opposition and from pro-IRA or moderate
Catholic groups in Northern Ireland, most of the new measures are
virtually certain of passage by the 650-member lower chamber, where
Mrs. Thatcher has a 101-seat margin over all the other parties
combined.
   Under the proposed measures, state investigators will be able to
demand from banks details of accounts through which the IRA is
suspected of moving cash from legitimate businesses or racketeering.
   Under the proposed measures, all Northern Ireland election
candidates will have to sign an oath rejecting violence.
   Other politicians or members of the public will be able to sue
those who don't sign and get them banned from office.
   Officials said despite the law providing for the proposed
non-violence pledge _ which is aimed at members of the outlawed
IRA's legal political front, Sinn Fein _ candidates can say what
they like during election campaigns.
   ``Further repression, the increasing erosion of our few remaining
civil liberties and British efforts to marginalize Sinn Fein are not
the way to resolve the conflict,'' said Sinn Fein spokesman Danny
Morrison.
   The new measure follows a ban this fall on broadcast interviews
with members of the IRA and 10 other militant Catholic and
Protestant groups in Northern Ireland.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA wants to end British rule in
predominantly Protestant Northern Ireland and unite it with the 95
percent Catholic Republic of Ireland under socialist rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
