<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MyersonTrial     11-23 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Myerson Trial,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Myerson Trial: What the Mayor Was Told</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch barely looked at former Miss
America Bess Myerson, his former close political ally, and said
almost as little during his testimony at her divorce-fixing
conspiracy trial.
   Miss Myerson's attorney got Koch to concede, however, that a
previous sworn statement he made was ``inaccurate'' because he had
forgotten about one conversation with an aide.
   Koch was unusually subdued and smiled little during most of his
testimony Tuesday in a packed federal courtroom.
   Koch appointed Miss Myerson as city cultural affairs commissioner
in 1983. She resigned in 1987 after a report commissioned by Koch
accused her of ``serious misconduct'' in the hiring of a judge's
daughter as her personal assistant.
   Miss Myerson, 64; her lover, Carl ``Andy'' Capasso, 43; and
former state Supreme Court Justice Hortense Gabel, 75, are on trial
for an alleged scheme to fix support payments in Capasso's divorce.
   Miss Myerson, is accused of giving a city job to the judge's
daughter, Sukhreet Gabel, to influence Mrs. Gabel, who later slashed
Capasso's temporary alimony and child support payments.
   Koch barely glanced at Miss Myerson as he testified for the
prosecution, but Miss Myerson stared intently at her former boss
from the defense table.
   Koch's testimony centered on a letter he received from Miss
Myerson on Oct. 19, 1983, explaining the hiring of Sukhreet Gabel.
   In the letter, written the day after a New York Post report about
Ms. Gabel's hiring, Miss Myerson contended that nothing improper was
done and that most of the decisions in the divorce case were already
made when Miss Gabel was hired.
   ``The only information that I had (about Ms. Gabel's hiring) was
the (Post) article and the letter,'' said Koch.
   Myerson lawyer Frederick Hafetz grilled the mayor about when a
top aide, Herbert Rickman, told him about Miss Gabel's hiring.
   Koch testified that his first recollection of discussing the
subject with Rickman was in 1986.
   But Hafetz pointed out that in a sworn statement to prosecutors
in September 1987, Koch said he had not discussed the Gabel hiring
with Rickman before June 1987.
   When Hafetz asked Koch if his statements last year were ``false,
incorrect, inaccurate or misleading,'' Koch replied: ``I am saying
they were inaccurate.''
   ``To the best of my recollection,'' Koch said later, ``now or at
any time, I had two conversations with Herb Rickman on this matter.''
   The first was in 1986, he said. The second in 1987, when the
mayor's commission made its report on Miss Myerson. He said he had
forgotten about the 1986 conversation when he made the statement to
prosecutors in 1987.
   Rickman testified earlier in the trial that he had gone to see
Koch in 1983 to angrily denounce the Post article, which quoted a
Myerson aide as saying Rickman had recommended Ms. Gabel as a job
candidate.
   The Myerson aide has admitted misleading the Post reporter.
   Koch, however, said he did not recall the 1983 conversation with
Rickman although he added: ``It could've occurred. I just have no
recollection.''
   Last year, Koch said he no longer considers Miss Myerson a
friend, but under questioning by Assistant U.S. Attorney David
Lawrence, the mayor said he ``had and has a high regard'' for Miss
Myerson, whom he described as ``very important in the (mayoral) race
I won in 1977.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
