<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FireDeaths     11-23 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fire Deaths,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retired Firefighter Unable to Save Own Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEANNE WAXMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETHTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired Navy firefighter says he was
unable to break through an intense fire that shot up his house's
only staircase, killing his two children, a niece and two nephews.
   Samuel Todaro and his wife, Eleanor, fled the fire unharmed
Tuesday, but said they had no chance of saving the five children
from the fatal inferno that trapped them in upstairs bedrooms of the
wooden, frame house.
   ``We heard a big pop and then we saw it. We looked over and we
saw this glow through our bedroom door,'' said Todaro, who was
asleep with his wife in a downstairs room. ``We ran out and started
yelling at the kids.''
   ``It doesn't seem like it happened. It seems like they're still
here but they're not,'' Mrs. Todaro said.
   The children were trapped by smoke and flames that shot up the
home's only staircase from the living room, said Fire Chief Bill
Carter. The staircase was the only exit for the children, who ranged
in age from 3-year-old twins to 15, he said.
   Todaro said he attempted to get to the sleeping children through
a second-floor balcony door, but he was driven back by intense heat.
   ``I'm a retired Navy firefighter,'' he said. ``I knew how far I
could get. I'd have died if I could have saved them.''
   A firefighter tried to reach the youngsters by ladder but also
was unsuccessful, Carter said.
   Investigators checked electrical wiring and the living room
fireplace as possible causes. Arson isn't suspected, Carter said.
The 11-room house, built at least 60 years ago, was gutted and not
equipped with smoke detectors.
   The house's gas furnace wasn't turned on, the fire chief said.
The couple had built a fire in the living room fireplace that night,
but Mrs. Todaro said they made sure flames were out when they went
to bed.
   Killed were twins Stephen and Stephanie Baumgartner, their
15-year-old brother Christopher Baumgartner, 12-year-old Amy Todaro
and her 7-year-old brother Guy Todaro, Carter said.
   All five died of smoke inhalation, but the twins also were
burned, the fire chief said.
   The Todaros said they were legal guardians of the Baumgartner
youngsters. Their mother is Todaro's sister, Barbara Gardner, who
also lives in Elizabethton.
   A funeral for the children was scheduled for Saturday at
Hathaway-Percy Funeral Home, across the street from the gutted house.
</TEXT>
