<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TurkeyRecall     11-23 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turkey Recall,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Distributor Tracks Down Spoiled Turkeys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's fifth-largest turkey
processor and distributor is recalling thousands of its ``Family
Tradition'' turkeys from seven Northeast states after three grocers
discovered spoiled giblets and necks in some birds.
   No illnesses have been reported and the U.S. Agriculture
Department has been notified, Norbest Inc. spokesman Mike Korologos
said by telephone from the company's Salt Lake City headquarters
Tuesday.
   The turkeys, which carry the number P-2487 on the metal package
closures, were processed under a packaging agreement with a Columbia
City, Ind., plant, Korologos said. They were distributed to stores
in Rhode Island, Massachusetts, Vermont, Maine, Connecticut, New
Hampshire and in Pittsburgh in Pennsylvania, he said.
   Bennett S. Berman, executive vice president of the meat division
of Roger Williams Foods in Cranston, a Norbest distributor, said he
had distributed about 900 boxes of turkeys, each containing two to
four birds, to ``mostly small stores where we could put our fingers
right on it.''
   ``I have recovered ... 90 percent of them,'' he said, estimating
the rest would be recovered today.
   He said one store apparently had sold several boxes of birds to
someone for a raffle or similar event and those were being tracked
down.
   Berman said a grocer complained about a bad bird Saturday but he
did not become concerned immediately because ``we get these calls
every year at Thanksgiving and Christmas'' when the birds jam
grocery shelves and often are improperly refrigerated.
   When a grocer found a bad box of turkeys, however, Berman said he
immediately notified Norbest on Monday and began recalling the
birds, which are being shipped to a Boston-area cold storage
warehouse for federal inspection.
   Korologos said the turkeys being recalled, which weigh from 6 to
20 pounds each, amount to less than 0.2 percent of Norbest's total
production.
   ``Norbest does not forsee any serious health problems, but
ordered the removal to avoid the remote possibility of illness to
consumers,'' he said. Consumers who purchased the turkeys should
return them to the place of purchase for a refund, Korologos said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
