<2ND_LINE>PM-Car-Train Wreck,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car, Train Collide At Railroad Crossing, Killing Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLEY CITY, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A train smashed into a car at a
fog-shrouded railroad crossing, killing a couple and three of their
six young children and injuring the other three, authorities said.
   No one on the freight train was injured in Tuesday's crash on a
rural gravel road about five miles west of this southeast North
Dakota city, the state Highway Patrol said.
   The engineer of the westbound Burlington Northern train blew the
engine's whistle before crossing the intersection, said Highway
Patrolman Roger Haga. But fog covered the area, and the driver of
the northbound car apparently did not see or hear the freight, Haga
said.
   The parents and three of the children, all of whom were less than
9 years old, were pronounced dead at the scene, authorities said.
Two of the surviving children were taken to Mercy Hospital in Valley
City.
   Another who wandered away from the wreck was found about an hour
later, and was taken to the hospital, Haga said.
   A 5-year-old girl was transfereed to a Fargo hospital, where she
was in critical condition Tuesday night, said Mercy Hospital
spokeswoman Connie Reed. Two boys, ages 4 and 6, were in stable
condition at Mercy.
   The victims' identities were not released. No other details were
available.
</TEXT>
