<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     11-23 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Keith Hits Florida As Pacific Storm Drifts Toward the Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm Keith blustered ashore in Florida today, spawning
tornadoes and bringing torrential rains, as a Pacific storm edged
toward the Rockies after hitting Oregon with 75 mph winds and
dumping nearly 4 inches of rain.
   In Florida, Keith's center made landfall shortly after 1 a.m.
today near Sarasota, about 50 miles south of Tampa. Later this
morning, the storm was moving east-northeast at 15-20 mph. It was
expected to move offshore in the Cape Canaveral area on the Atlantic
Coast.
   The storm was expected to dump up to 5 inches of rain and bring
tides 4 to 6 feet above normal. Early this morning, almost 2{ inches
were recorded at Tampa; more than 1{ inches at Daytona Beach, and
more than 1 inch at Gainesville.
   But a cold front from the North was mingling with Keith in the
Gulf of Mexico and was expected to sap its strength.
   At least two tornadoes were spotted near St. Petersburg early
today, but there were no immediate reports of injury or damage,
authorities said.
   In Lake County, a tornado struck a mobile home park south of
Leesburg, then skipped across a field and hit another park Tuesday
morning, officials said.
   If Keith's winds reach over 74 mph, it would become the sixth
hurricane of the Atlantic storm season, which runs from June through
Nov. 30. Keith is the 11th named storm of the season.
   In the Pacific Northwest, snow began to fall Tuesday night in
Oregon's higher elevations, with up to 2 feet in mountain passes
expected by today.
   The Pacific storm, moving toward the Rockies, also knocked down
power lines with winds up to 75 mph in Clackamas County southeast of
Portland, Ore., and unleashed nearly 4 inches of rain in less than
24 hours Tuesday.
   Today's forecast called for rain and thunderstorms from Florida
through the Carolinas; rain through the northern Pacific coastal
areas to Nevada and the Rockies, with rain turning to snow in higher
elevations; and strong, gusty winds from the northern and central
Pacific Coast to the Rockies.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 30s and 40s from New
England to the northern Appalachians, the Great Lakes, the upper
Mississippi Valley, North Dakota, the upper Missouri Valley, the
northern Rockies, the northern half of the Pacific Coast; the 70s
from the desert Southwest to southern Texas; near 70 over northern
Florida to the low and mid-80s across southern Florida; and in the
50s and 60s in the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 17
degrees at Montpelier, Vt., to 81 at Homestead, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 47 cloudy; Boston 32 partly cloudy; Buffalo 30
snow; Charleston, S.C. 53 rain; Cincinnati 29 fair; Cleveland 28
fair; Detroit 28 fair; Miami 79 windy; New York 38 fair;
Philadelphia 32 fair; Pittsburgh 27 fair; Portland, Maine 24 fair;
Washington 35 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 24 fair; Chicago 35 partly cloudy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 38 fair; Denver 40 fair; Des Moines 37 fair; Indianapolis 30
fair; Kansas City 38 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 34 cloudy; Nashville
34 fair; New Orleans 50 fair; St. Louis 36 foggy.
   _West: Albuquerque 33 fair; Anchorage 07 partly cloudy; Las Vegas
45 cloudy; Los Angeles 56 partly cloudy; Phoenix 53 fair; Salt Lake
City 50 cloudy; San Diego 51 foggy; San Francisco 60 drizzle;
Seattle 42 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 21 fair; Toronto 34 cloudy.
</TEXT>
