<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Censorship     11-23 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Censorship,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Bars Distribution Of Harper's Over Intelligence Excerpts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has barred distribution of the
December issue of Harper's magazine because it contains sensitive
excerpts from a book by former intelligence agent Anthony Cavendish,
the distributors said today.
   The government warned the distributors, COMAG, that issue of the
U.S.-published magazine would breach a High Court order barring two
London newspapers from publishing material about Cavendish's work in
East bloc countries in the late 1950s and early 1960s.
   ``At this time, we have agreed not to distribute'' the December
issue, a spokeswoman said on condition of anonymity.
   Cavendish, a 61-year-old merchant banker, worked for Britain's
MI6 agency, which gathers foreign intelligence.
   He abandoned a two-year battle to publish his memoirs, ``Inside
Intelligence,'' after the government threatened legal action, but he
sent 500 privately printed copies to friends as Christmas presents
last year.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government obtained an interim
injunction Jan. 2 against The Observer and The Sunday Times
newspapers after arguing that Cavendish broke a formal vow never to
reveal details of his intelligence work and that publication would
damage national security.
   Cavendish wrote that Harold Wilson may have abruptly resigned as
Labor Party prime minister in March 1976 because the Soviet KGB had
acquired embarrassing information about him.
   Wilson stepped down less than midway through his government's
normal five-year term of office. The 72-year-old politician, now
Lord Wilson, was twice prime minister, from 1964 to 1970 and from
1974 to 1976.
</TEXT>
