<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nazi-Citizenship     11-23 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nazi-Citizenship,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Accused Of Assisting Nazi Slaughter Loses U.S. Citizenship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of helping Nazis exterminate
more than 20,000 Jews in Lithuania during World War II was stripped
of U.S. citizenship but will not be deported, the Justice Department
says.
   Juoza Kungys, 73, of Clifton in northern New Jersey will be
allowed to remain in the United States as a permanent resident alien
as part of an agreement in which he admitted to authorities that he
lied to U.S. officials when he entered the country after World War
II, the department said.
   U.S. District Judge Dickinson R. Debevoise signed the consent
order here last week, and the Justice Department made it public
Tuesday.
   Government lawyers have said that in 1941, Kungys, as a member of
a military organization known as the Sauliai, helped force more than
2,000 Jewish men, women and children to undress and enter a ditch,
where they were shot.
   The government permitted Kungys to stay because he would probably
have been allowed to remain due to future litigation, said Neal
Sher, director of the Justice Department's special investigations
office. Sher said Kungys would still be eligible for extradition to
stand trial abroad.
   The Justice Department moved to revoke Kungys citizenship in
1981. Throughout the case, left unresolved by the Supreme Court last
May, authorities have charged that Kungys lied about his place of
birth and residence during the war.
   Government lawyers have said that in 1941, Kungys, as a member of
a military organization known as the Sauliai, helped force more than
2,000 Jewish men, women and children to undress and enter a ditch,
where they were shot.
   Kungys entered the U.S. in 1948 an was granted citizenship in
1954.
</TEXT>
