<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BowlingTurkeys     11-23 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bowling Turkeys,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkey Bowlers Toss Fowl Balls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEARNEY, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   College students rolled 10-pound frozen
butterballs at plastic pins in a holiday tournament that gave new
meaning to the term bowling a turkey.
   More than 50 students at Kearney State College participated
Monday night in the bowling championship in a dormitory hallway.
Sponsors said foul fowls were more common than turkeys, a real
bowling term for three strikes in a row.
   ``There are no holes in the turkey to put your fingers,'' said
Melissa Fitch, a sophomore. Miss Fitch said she averages 150 on a
real bowling alley but managed to knock down only 16 pins in the
turkey competition.
   ``I think its hilarious,'' she said. ``I've never seen anything
like it.''
   The rules and scoring during the 52-person tourney established by
the dormitory's resident assistants were generally the same as those
used in real bowling.
   ``Turkey must stay within taped boundaries or it is considered a
gutter turkey,'' one sign said. The cry of ``gutter turkey'' was
heard throughout the night.
   Some bowlers grasped the turkey by the net cover or the plastic
handle to propel the bird toward the toy pins. Others used two hands
to push it down the lane. Gina Christensen, a freshman, hiked her
``ball'' football-style.
   Tom Upthagrove, a freshman, said students needed a break from
their studies.
   ``It gives us something to talk about. It cheers us up,'' he said.
   Resident assistant Brad Krutsinger said winners of the finals
scheduled later this week will have the option of keeping a turkey
as a prize.
   But he said the birds may be mangled by then and probably will be
donated to the local Humane Society for use as cat food.
</TEXT>
