<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VideoBurglary     11-23 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Video Burglary,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeowner Videotapes Burglars Along With Parrot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who trained his video camera on his
parrot to catch the bird talking while he was away instead caught
two teen-agers who burglarized his home and threatened to throttle
the squawking animal.
   Roy Ohse, 57, rigged the camera before he went to the store in
May and returned a half-hour later and turned on the videotape.
   ``Was I surprised,'' he recalled Monday.
   He didn't know he had been burglarized until he heard human
voices on the tape. The burglars could be heard rummaging through
things.
   One voice said, ``See anything worth taking?'' Another said,
``You take the bag and stuff and I'll take this.''
   Both burglars passed in front of the camera and their faces could
be clearly seen. At one point, a 13-year-old said to his older
accomplice, ``There's a video camera, you want to chance it with
that?''
   ``Nah,'' came the answer from the background.
   One teen-ager threatened to throttle the bird, which by this time
was squawking loudly. One even pulled a gun.
   ``Don't, don't, don't, don't, don't,'' the other boy said.
``It'll be too noisy and too bloody.''
   ``I'm going to strangle you, you (expletive) bird,'' the first
teen-ager said.
   ``Well, strangle it. Just don't shoot it.''
   The two left without harming the bird, called Turkey by its owner.
   When Ohse played the tape for police and family, a friend of his
son recognized one of the teen-agers. The two teen-agers later
pleaded guilty to burglary and a third pleaded guilty to dealing in
stolen property.
</TEXT>
