<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MallBan-Kidnap     11-23 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mall Ban-Kidnap,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posters Of Missing Girl Banned from Shopping Malls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAYWARD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Posters bearing the photo of a 9-year-old
kidnapping victim have been ordered removed from common areas at two
shopping malls by managers who cited policies against non-profit
displays.
   Managers of Hayward's Southland Shopping Center and Newark's
NewPark mall on Tuesday also told volunteers in the search for
Michaela Garecht not to pass out fliers on mall grounds.
   Michaela Garecht's grandmother, Audrey Nemeth, who works at a
department store at Southland, said the mall should make an
exception.
   ``I think it's pretty disgusting,'' she said. ``I understand the
issue of clutter, but a missing child is a lot different.''
   Michaela was last seen Saturday, when a man forced her into his
car in Hayward, authorities said.
   Southland Mall manager Elliott Riley said he told the mall's
security guards to remove the fliers, which he said were placed in a
haphazard fashion, in violation of the mall's rules and without the
consent of mall management.
   Riley said later he would work out a plan to post the fliers in
the mall if the people distributing them contact him. He said he
also would pay for an ad.
   Some stores refused to remove the flier from their windows.
   Jim Elliott, security manager for J.C. Penney Co., said a mall
security guard who asked that the flier be removed was told it would
stay up. No effort was made to remove it, Elliott said.
   At NewPark and Southland, merchants were allowed to display
posters inside the stores but could not put them in the windows
facing the shopping center.
   ``We have a policy that we cannot attach anything to the common
areas,'' said NewPark Mall marketing director Lisa Shepherd. ``A
store can do whatever they wish within their store area.''
   Bay Fair Mall in San Leandro was plastered with fliers also.
Manager Paul DeMarco said the posters will stay although they
violate mall rules.
   ``This is a local girl,'' he said. ``The chance is good that
someone might see her.''
</TEXT>
