<HEAD>Police, Fire Dispatchers Overcome By Gas; No One Hurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oxygen-eating gas designed to put out
fires accidentally discharged in the City-County Building, and eight
police and fire dispatchers were overcome, authorities said.
   The dispatchers were given oxygen Tuesday night and none required
hospital treatment.
   Fire Capt. Gary Campbell said a malfunction system caused the
building fire alarm to go off and the gas Halon to be released.
Dispatchers were forced to crawl out because there was more oxygen
near the floor, Campbell said.
   Firefighters used fans to blow the gas from the rooms, and
dispatchers returned after about an hour. Communications were not
disrupted because dispatchers who were not affected used hand-held
radios to monitor calls.
</TEXT>
