<1ST_LINE>u i PM-QuebecQuake 1stLd-Writethru a0521 11-23 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quebec Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0521,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mild Quake Shakes Southern Quebec</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUEBEC CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake shook southern Quebec early
today, causing slight damage but no injuries, officials said.
   The epicenter of the quake, which measured 4.9 on the Richter
scale, was 90 miles north of Quebec City, John Adams of the
Geological Survey of Canada said. Preliminary measurements by the
U.S. Geological Survey in Golden, Colo., put the magnitude of the
quake at 4.5 on the Richter scale.
   The 4:11 a.m. jolt was felt in Quebec City and over a broad area
including Bagotville, Trois-Rivieres, Chicoutimi and Lac St-Jean,
Adams said.
   ``Some unconfirmed damage has been reported in Lac St-Jean,''
Adams said. ``But it would be slight _ in the nature of cracks
showing in walls, glasses or china falling off shelves, that sort of
thing.''
   There were some reports of people thinking a snowblower had been
turned on outside their home or their furnace had blown up. But most
residents between Quebec City and Chicoutimi slept through the
unexpected quake.
   Earthquakes are very rare in the region, which is considered
relatively stable, Adams said. ``This one really caught us by
surprise,'' he said.
   The Richter scale is an open-ended gauge of energy released by an
earthquake as measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph.
Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight damage
in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage.
</TEXT>
