<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ConanOwen     11-23 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Conan Owen,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Photographer Home After 20-Month Ordeal That Began With Spanish
Drug Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNANDALE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Photographer Conan Owen is home with his
parents today, savoring his freedom after a 20-month ordeal that
began with his arrest in Spain for a drug trafficking crime U.S.
officials said he didn't commit.
   Owen, 24, arrived home Tuesday night, his parents' 27th wedding
anniversary, to a jubilant welcome and said his first order of
business was to ``sleep in'' and then spend today talking on the
phone to friends.
   Federal prison officials in Pennsylvania on Tuesday released Owen
for a holiday furlough. Under a plan approved by a federal parole
commission, Owen will be able to serve remaining months of his
sentence at home with his parents Ernest and Raquel Owens.
   On Monday, Owen will report to the Fairfax County Home Detention
Program in Fairfax to be fitted with an electronic device that will
monitor him during his period of house arrest.
   Owen, a 1986 honors graduate of Syracuse University, was
sentenced last April to six years in prison by a Spanish court for
carrying four pounds of 80 percent pure cocaine in a suitcase to an
airport in Barcelona in March 1987.
   U.S. investigators later collected evidence that he had been
duped into becoming a drug courier without his knowledge, and
then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III pleaded Owen's case with
Spanish authorities.
   Owen's former boss, George Barahona, confessed in a U.S. court
that he and colleagues had hidden the cocaine in the suitcase which
they asked Owen to carry to Barcelona. Spanish officials refused to
admit Barahona's deposition as evidence.
   Owen was transferred to New York on Nov. 8 under terms of a 1983
treaty that provides for the transfer of prisoners between the
United States and Spain when a citizen of one country is convicted
of a crime in another.
   Owen worked as a 1984 summer intern in Vice President George
Bush's office and had been admitted to the U.S. Army Intelligence
School in Fort Huachuca, Ariz.
   Owen was furloughed after a hearing Tuesday at the federal
Correctional Institution in Loretto, Pa., where he has been
incarcerated since his return to the United States.
   The U.S. Parole Commission said Tuesday that Owen's role in
bringing cocaine into Spain was ``peripheral'' _ a courier with ``no
managerial or proprietary interest'' _ and reduced his minimum
prison sentence from 40 months to 24 months. A parole hearing is
scheduled for March 12.
</TEXT>
