<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Portugal-Shooting     11-23 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Portugal-Shooting,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guardsman Fires on Parade, Kills Four</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national guardsman fired wildly into a
parade at his barracks today, killing four guardsmen and injuring at
least 12 before committing suicide, officials and news reports said.
   Gen. Lemos Couto, commander of Ajuda barracks of the Portuguese
National Republican Guardsmen, said the shots were fired into a
troop of cadets by a Cpl. Antonio Saraiva Antunes. Couto said
Antunes, 28, fired his own hunting rifle, rather than a military
weapon.
   Following the attack Antunes shot himself with a pistol and died
later in Lisbon's Sao Fransisco Xavier hospital, Couto said.
   ``(The corporal) went mad and fired indiscriminately with what
seemed to be his own hunting rifle into the guards from the terrace
above the parade ground,'' Couto said.
   A barracks official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
some cadets shot back at Antunes. Two of the four guards who died
were officers. One officer killed was Lieutenant-Colonel Jorge
Duarte de Almeida, the barracks second-in-command, said the
official. Antunes' death left 12 guardsmen hospitalized, including
one in critical condition, doctors said.
   Antunes, who received a commendation from his division commander
in 1987, was apparently popular with his colleagues and had no
record of disciplinary measures or mental illness, Portuguese media
reports said.
   He joined the National Guard in 1982.
</TEXT>
