<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 0937EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Trotsky     11-23 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Trotsky,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trotsky's Son Posthumously Rehabilitated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Supreme Court has rehabilitated Leon
Trotsky's son, Sergei Sedov, who was killed in Josef Stalin's purges
even though he rejected his father's beliefs.
   The court's action came after Sedov's daughter, Yulia Akselrod,
who immigrated to the United States in 1979, wrote President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev seeking to clear her father's name.
   The government newspaper Izvestia reported Monday that ``charges
are dropped'' against Sedov, who it said was shot to death in 1937.
   The terse, two-sentence reference to Sedov partially answered
Mrs. Akselrod's questions about the circumstances of her father's
death. She said in September that she did not know when or how her
father died.
   Izvestia said Sedov was sentenced in 1935, but was killed two
years later.
   Trotsky, once a leader of the revolution, was expelled from the
Soviet Union by Stalin in 1929 after losing a power struggle
following the death of Soviet founder Vladimir I. Lenin in 1924.
   Stalin advocated ``communism in one country,'' while Trotsky
believed in worldwide revolution. Later, in the purges of the 1930s
Stalin hunted down real and imagined followers of Trotsky and had
them imprisoned or killed.
   Mrs. Akselrod said she and her family were still being punished
for their lineage. She said her father had been politically and
personally estranged from Trotsky.
   Until Gorbachev mentioned Trotsky in a speech last year, his name
had been taboo.
   Mrs. Akselrod said the Soviet government should fully clear
Trotsky's name and document his true role in the revolution.
   But despite Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or more openness on
some issues, officials have so far taken the stance that Trotsky's
views were wrong and his full rehabilitation soon is unlikely.
   After being branded a traitor, Trotsky left the country with his
wife, Natalia Sedova, and their oldest son Lyova, who avidly backed
his father. He was assassinated in Mexico in 1940, allegedly by a
Mexican Communist Party member loyal to Stalin.
   Sedov, who stayed behind in the Soviet Union, took his mother's
name to avoid persecution and thought he was safe. Mrs. Akselrod
said her father was sent to Siberia about three months before she
was born.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
