<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EmployerSanctions     11-23 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Employer Sanctions,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quakers Disobey Immigration Law, Seek Religious Exemption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Quaker organization is seeking a religious
exemption from a law requiring employers to fire undocumented aliens.
   Provisions in the 1986 immigration reform act ``require us to act
in ways that violate our fundamental religious beliefs,'' said
Stephen G. Cary, chairman of the board of directors of the American
Friends Service Committee.
   The lawsuit filed in federal court Tuesday seeks to exempt the
Quakers from the threat of fines of up to $10,000 against employers
who fail to verify documents or fail to fire employees who don't
produce documentation.
   The Quakers, who employ 450 people, have disobeyed the
documentation provision while deciding on a legal course, Cary said.
   ``We find ourselves ordered by the government to cast out those
we have tried for so long to help,'' he said. ``The effort of a
parent to feed his or her children is criminalized. The demand that
we fire those we cannot document is repugnant to us.''
   A spokesman for the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service
declined to comment on the lawsuit.
</TEXT>
