<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0442 11-23 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge To Hold Closed Hearings On Whether To Delete Some Sensitive
Items</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds last 4 grafs on White House role.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra case will hold
closed hearings on Oliver L. North's objections to deleting
sensitive references from secret documents that prosecutors want to
use as evidence against him.
   North, a former White House aide, is charged with conspiring to
illegally divert U.S.-Iran arms sales profits to the Nicaraguan
anti-government Contra rebels.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell on Tuesday ordered closed
hearings to begin Nov. 30 and continue ``thereafter day-to-day as
long as necessary'' to review the deletions from 350 classified
documents proposed by independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh.
   Walsh wants to delete the names of countries, foreign officials
and U.S. agents stationed abroad to protect secret diplomatic and
intelligence initiatives.
   The government has agreed to allow Walsh to use the documents as
evidence in a public trial provided the sensitive information is
deleted.
   The judge said North ``should be prepared to explain why a
proposed redaction (deletion) is relevant and material for his
defense.''
   Gesell made no mention in his brief order of North's proposal to
introduce into evidence 40,000 pages of classified material. At a
hearing on Monday, the judge seemed to indicate he would grant
Walsh's motion to bar North from using any of the material, saying
he had no intention of scheduling hearings on North's proposals.
   The independent prosecutor argued in court papers that North's
list of documents should be rejected as legally insufficient.
   He contended that the former National Security Council aide
listed many of the documents simply to frighten the government to
drop the charges to prevent disclosing some of the nation's most
well-kept intelligence and foreign-policy secrets.
   In his order scheduling the hearings on the prosecution's
documents, Gesell said he had reviewed many of the papers.
   ``Numerous redactions appear designed to excise the identity of
countries mentioned and communications with named individuals,
including officials of such countries and United States agents in
the field,'' the judge said.
   ``Almost without exception North objects to these categories of
redactions.''
   The prosecution exhibits include between 1,000 and 2,000 pages of
classified material.
   The Classified Information Procedures Act provides for
substitution of information with a written statement of facts if
North convinces the judge that some of the material Walsh wants to
delete from the exhibits is necessary for his defense.
   Gesell directed Walsh to devise an alternative system to denoting
countries and officials with numbers and letters, saying ``this
masking technique appears unduly cumbersome and likely to prevent
easy reading of the text.''
   No date has been set for North's trial. Separate trials have been
ordered for former national security adviser John M. Poindexter and
arms dealers Albert Hakim and retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V.
Secord.
   Marlin Fitzwater, President Reagan's spokesman, said Tuesday the
White House role currently is ``to review classified information
that has been designated by the prosecution and by the defense'' for
possible use in the trial.
   Asked to comment on suggestions by Gesell that Reagan should
consider exercising his constitutional authority to thwart North's
trial if the president feels national security would be compromised,
Fitzwater replied, ``We don't have any direct role.''
   Reagan for months has said he would not discuss with reporters
the option of granting a pardon to North. On Monday, when asked
whether he was drawing near a decision on a possible pardon, he
replied, ``No, no. And I don't think it would be any time to make
such a decision while it's still before the courts.''
   When pressed during a news briefing to say whether a pardon was
being considered, Fitzwater said repeatedly, ``We aren't discussing
pardons.''
</TEXT>
