<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Fried,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Erich Fried, Austrian Poet, Dead At 67</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Erich Fried, a poet who translated Shakespeare's
works into modern German, died of cancer at age 67, his publisher
said today.
   He died Tuesday at a hospital in Baden-Baden, said Klaus
Wagenbach, his close friend and publisher in West Berlin.
   Fried, an Austrian Jew, was born in Vienna on May 6, 1921, but
fled his Nazi-ruled homeland in 1938. He spent most of the rest of
his life in Britain.
   He was known primarily for his political poems but also worked as
a journalist and translator.
   Over the past 20 years, he translated 27 of Shakespeare's works
into modern German as well as works by T.S. Eliot and Dylan Thomas.
   In some of his poems, Fried harshly criticized the Vietnam War
and the handling of student protests in Western countries.
   Among his best-known works are ``Und Vietnam Und'' (And Vietnam
And), ``Liebesgedichte'' (Love Poems), and ``Die Freiheit den Mund
aufzumachen'' (Freedom To Speak Openly).
   Fried is survived by his wife, Catherine.
</TEXT>
