<2ND_LINE>PM-Scowcroft Thumbnail,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Selection for National Security Adviser Known for Moderate
Views</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brent Scowcroft, selected by President-elect
George Bush to be his national security adviser, is a retired
three-star Air Force general known for his moderate views and
professionalism.
   Scowcroft, 63, rose to prominence as national security adviser to
President Gerald Ford 1975-77. Earlier, he had served as military
assistant to the president 1972-73 and deputy national security
adviser 1973-75.
   Scowcroft, born in Ogden, Utah, graduated from the U.S. Military
Academy in 1947, and advanced through the Air Force ranks to
lieutenant general. Along the way, he picked up masters and
doctorate degrees from Georgetown University.
   After the Ford administration, Scowcroft served as an arms
control adviser to President Carter, and on a number of blue ribbon
commissions, including one appointed by President Reagan to study
basing possibilities for the MX missile.
   Scowcroft is married and has one daughter.
</TEXT>
