<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1039EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland     11-23 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Charges Police With Beating Demonstrators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Solidarity human rights commission today
charged that police severely beat 108 demonstrators since Oct. 7 in
a ``wave of police violence,'' and it appealed to the Roman Catholic
Church for help.
   The Commission of Intervention and Lawfulness, appointed by
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, said police beat 51 people during the
Nov. 11 protests marking the 70th anniversary of Polish independence
after World War I.
   The commission monitors human rights abuses for Solidarity, the
independent trade union federation crushed by security forces in
1981 and outlawed in 1982.
   The panel today released a report naming the 108 people it said
were beaten and describing their injuries.
   In the report signed by its chairman, Zbigniew Romaszewski, the
panel said remarks by government spokesman Jerzy Urban that only two
people had been injured during the protests were ``notorious
disinformation.''
   At a Nov. 15 news conference, Urban said eight people were
detained and 39 people were questioned by police in the nationwide
demonstrations. He said the only injuries were in the southern city
of Katowice, where he said one person suffered a bruised knee and
another person a bruised shoulder.
   But the report said the anniversary was ``a day of peak intensity
of a ... wave of police violence.
   ``Are only death casualities ... capable of alarming society and
authorities of the existing danger?''
   The panel questioned government statements that demonstrators
started the violence by throwing stones at police.
   It cited statements from protesters in Poznan that the
rock-throwing was started by police in civilian clothes who mixed
with the crowd. The beatings seemed directed especially at
university and high school students, the commission said. Every
third high school student detained was beaten, it said.
   Other beatings listed in the report allegedly occurred between
Oct. 7 and Nov. 11 at various demonstrations.
   On Oct. 7, a day honoring Polish police, demonstrations mocking
the police force were staged across the country.
   The first victim listed in the report was allegedly beaten on
Oct. 7 for holding up a pro-Solidarity sign at the train station in
the northern port of Gdansk, where the federation was started in
1980.
   On the same day in Warsaw, a university student said he was held
down while police banged his head, hit him in the face and kicked
him in the stomach.
   Another student in Warsaw told the panel he was severely beaten,
and a third student said he was hit in the face with a baton and
kicked in the stomach.
   The panel reported similar incidents throughout Poland between
Oct. 9 and Nov. 11. It said some beatings involved miners attending
Solidarity meetings and rallies, and people attending Mass honoring
the Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko, a priest slain by police.
   The Solidarity panel appealed to the church, to a parliamentary
human rights committee and to ``all of society'' to exert pressure
to end such beatings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
