<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SelmaElection     11-23 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Selma Election,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blacks Move Closer To Gaining First County Commission Seats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four blacks moved into primary runoffs in a
campaign to elect the first black member of the Dallas County
Commission in more than a century.
   A federal court ordered Tuesday's election in a legal dispute
that began in 1978, when the U.S. Justice Department said the
countywide election process diluted black voter strength in the
county, which is about 55 percent black.
   The change from at-large voting to five districts gave black
voters a majority in at least two of the districts in this county,
the site of one of the most famous voter registration struggles of
the civil rights movement.
   A black has not served on the commission since Reconstruction.
   ``We've been trying for 20 years to get a county commission that
represents everyone and Tuesday seems to be that day,'' said civil
rights activist J.L. Chestnut.
   As a result of Tuesday's balloting, two blacks will be in a
runoff for one district and will face white Republican opposition in
the general election.
   Two whites made it into runoffs with black candidates in black
districts. Whites will advance to the general election in two other
districts.
   Runoffs are set for Dec. 13 and the general election is scheduled
for Dec. 27.
   More than 30 federal observers monitored the voting, while in
Washington, U.S. Supreme Court Justice Anthony Kennedy rejected a
bid by the county school board for a review of the district plan.
   The number of black registered voters in the county has swelled
from 300 to more than 20,000 since enactment of the Voting Rights
Act in 1965, the Selma-to-Montgomery voting rights march that year
and the other bitter civil rights struggles in Selma in the 1960s.
</TEXT>
