<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0426 11-23 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0426,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation Up, Dollar Down, Wild Day in the Oil Pits</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with durable goods report, early
dollar, market activity; Picks up 2nd graf, `The Labor ...'; A
version moved on the financial wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   American factory orders surged 2.4 percent last month for large
manufactured items, the government reported today, but the increase
came from a 41.1 percent jump in demand for military equipment,
mostly new warships.
   The Commerce Department said that excluding the military order
category, orders for durable goods fell 0.2 percent, the second
consecutive monthly drop.
   The key category of non-defense capital goods, a measure of
business expansion plans, also fell for the second straight month.
It was down 2.6 percent to $34 billion, following a 10.2 percent
drop in September, the largest since January 1986.
   Durable goods are defined as big items ranging from refrigerators
to tanks and aircraft that are expected to last at least three
years. Orders are an important barometer of manufacturing strength,
but economists discount the military and transportation categories
because they fluctuate sharply from month to month.
   The weak dollar fell further in New York in morning trading in
reaction to the durable goods report, evidently reflecting pessimism
about the ability of U.S. manufacturers to compete well in world
markets without a cheaper currency.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up
about 4 points to the 2,082 level, and in the bond market prices
were little changed.
   Other unsettling economic news dominated the attention of
financial markets Tuesday, leaving the United States facing higher
consumer prices, a weaker dollar, more expensive oil and its biggest
budget deficit since March.
   The Labor Department said Tuesday that sharp increases for fall
and winter clothing last month put consumer price inflation back
around 5 percent annually, despite the smallest monthly increase in
food costs since February.
   Consumer prices rose 0.4 percent in October _ or at an annual
rate of 5.1 percent vs. 4.1 percent in September _ with more than
half the gain coming from a 1.8 percent boost in apparel prices and
sharp increases in auto insurance and financing charges.
   Other inflation news came from the conference of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries in Vienna, Austria, where Iran gave
conflicting signals on whether a price-boosting pact was possible.
   The Iranians incited trading frenzies in the oil pits at the New
York Mercantile Exchange, where prices zoomed, collapsed and jumped
back up again in one of the wildest days in months. West Texas
Intermediate, the benchmark crude oil, ended up 88 cents per barrel
to $13.86.
   None of these events helped the dollar, which continued declining
in value against foreign currencies, not only because they raised
inflation fears but also because of increasing anxiety that the Bush
administration will do little to stem staggering budget and trade
deficits.
   The dollar fell in New York trading from 122.03 yen to 121.31 yen
and from 1.728 West German marks to 1.718. In other markets, stocks
were slightly higher and bond prices slipped.
   Heightening concern about budget deficit was a Treasury
Department report showing the federal government spent $27.4 billion
more than it took in last month, the largest deficit since March.
   That level was down 10.9 percent from a year earlier, but the
decline was more than accounted for by temporary factors or one-time
accounting adjustments.
   The Reagan administration is projecting the budget deficit in
fiscal 1989 will shrink to $145.5 billion, down from $155.1 billion
in the year ended Sept. 30. The Congressional Budget Office projects
a $148 billion deficit.
   But most private economists are projecting a 1989 deficit little
improved and perhaps worse than 1988.
</TEXT>
