<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DowalibySlaying     11-23 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dowaliby Slaying,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emotional Police Effort Results in Charges in Dowaliby Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Hearing scheduled for 1 p.m. EST; Lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDLOTHIAN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police investigating the strangling of a
7-year-old taped her picture to the wall and carried copies in their
wallets for nine weeks until they arrested her parents, who claimed
the child was stolen from her bed.
   ``We had an obligation to our profession to do this right and to
allay fears in these communities,'' said State Police Capt. Dan
McDevitt, who headed the investigation.
   ``But above all,'' he added, pointing to a picture of Jaclyn
Dowaliby on a bulletin board at the police station, ``we had an
obligation to her.''
   David and Cynthia Dowaliby were arrested Tuesday and charged with
murder. They were scheduled for a preliminary hearing today and were
held without bail.
   Dowaliby, 31, reported his daughter had been stolen from her bed
while he and his 26-year-old wife slept Sept. 10. Her body was found
four days later next to an apartment building in Blue Island.
   The investigation slowed when the Dowalibys refused to answer
further questions. Their attorney maintained they were being
harassed and had told police all they knew.
   Blue Island Police Chief Paul Greves declined to comment on the
findings of the investigation.
   Lawrence Hyman, attorney for Mrs. Dowaliby, said police had made
them ``scapegoats.''
   The investigation involved about 40 federal, state and local law
enforcement officers.
   ``There was no one key suspect from Day One. We followed
thousands of leads,'' Greves said. ``A lot of the investigators
carried her picture in their wallet while this went on.''
   Pulling a small photo of Jaclyn from his wallet, Greves added,
``I guess I can put this away now.''
   The couple's 4-year-old son, David, was taken into state custody,
McDevitt said. He was distraught about the arrests and was
hospitalized.
</TEXT>
