<DOCNO> AP881123-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1105EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Bush-TransitionChoices 4thLd-Writethru a0544 11-23 0974</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Transition Choices, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0544,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Quit Speculating in Print, Names Scowcroft as Adviser</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Scowcroft appointment, Bush quotes on Tower in
top 12 grafs, picking up in 10th graf pvs, Bush has already; deletes
17th graf pvs, National Security</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush asked today for an
end to news reports that he is about to name former Sen. John Tower
of Texas as defense secretary. Meanwhile, he did fill one post,
picking Brent Scowcroft as his national security adviser.
   ``I will put together a strong national security team. Now with
Brent Scowcroft at my side in the White House, we have taken a large
step in that direction,'' Bush said today.
   Asked about Tower, he replied that he was not yet ready to name
his Pentagon chief. And he added that he didn't like news stories
speculating on choices for various jobs.
   Such reports, he said, raise potential appointees' hopes, which
then can be dashed if ``it doesn't work out.''
   When asked if he would soon put Tower ``out of his misery, one
way or the other,'' he replied, ``I'm asking you to do that.''
   Tower's spokeswoman, Kim Garvin, said Tuesday, ``He's on hold. He
at present has not been asked.''
   Bush said the same thing Tuesday. ``No decision has been made,''
he told reporters traveling to Houston with him. The president-elect
indicated he would wait until after the Thanksgiving holiday to
announce his new Pentagon chief.
   Tower, 63, a former chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee from Texas, would be expected to deal effectively with
Congress, but some people have expressed qualms about his ability to
manage the multibillion-dollar a year agency.
   One scenario calls for a top manager, perhaps Paul O'Neill, the
chief executive officer of Alcoa, to serve as Tower's No. 2,
effectively running the Pentagon bureaucracy.
   O'Neill also has been mentioned as a possible defense secretary,
as have Donald Rumsfeld, a former Pentagon chief, Rep. Jack Kemp of
New York, procurement expert Norman Augustine and even Sen. Sam
Nunn, a Georgia Democrat.
   Whatever choice is made for Pentagon chief, Tower is expected to
land some kind of plum in the Bush administration in part because he
campaigned tirelessly for Bush's victory.
   Bush has said he will move expeditiously on appointments, but he
won't be rushed.
   Bush has already filled a number of jobs: Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh, Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos and Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady will remain in their posts.
   Richard Darman, a former Treasury official, will head the Office
of Management and Budget, former Treasury Secretary James A. Baker
III will become secretary of state, and New Hampshire Gov. John
Sununu has been selected as White House chief of staff.
   Here's the latest thinking on some other top agency and executive
posts.
   _ Agriculture. No new names surfaced Tuesday. Still in the
running are Robert Delano, former president of the American Farm
Bureau Federation; Clayton Yeutter, the U.S. trade representative;
Sen. Dan Evans, R-Wash.; and Rep. Thomas Coleman of Missouri.
   _ Energy. Former Rep. Thomas Loeffler, who ran Bush's campaign in
Texas, is a strong contender. Also talked about are former White
House aide Fred Khedouri, former deputy secretary William Martin and
Evans.
   _ Interior. This is one of the many jobs for which Evans' name
has been floated. Others on the list include Nathaniel Reed, a
former assistant secretary, Rep. Dick Cheney of Wyoming, former EPA
director William Ruckelshaus and former Tennessee Gov. Lamar
Alexander.
   _ CIA. The list has been pretty stable on who might succeed CIA
Director William Webster, but no decision has been made. Those on it
include James Lilley, the ambassador to Korea; Scowcroft; national
security adviser Colin Powell; Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and
William Hyland, editor of Foreign Affairs magazine. Webster, who
could be offered an interim appointment, has said little on the
issue.
   _ U.N. Ambassador. Alan Keyes, a former State Department
official, is a contender along with Maureen Reagan, President
Reagan's daughter; former Rep. Ed Derwinski and former national
security adviser Zbigniew Brzezinski.
   _ Health and Human Services. The same names keep cropping up for
this huge agency. They include Dorcas Hardy, the Social Security
commissioner; Rep. Willis Gradison of Ohio; Sen. Lowell Weicker of
Connecticut and Deborah Steelman, a campaign aide to Bush. Rep.
Trent Lott, a Mississippi Republican who will move to the Senate in
January, said Tuesday that he had written a letter to the Bush
transition team recommending former Rep. Bobbi Fiedler, R-Calif.,
for the job.
   _ Transportation. Matthew Scocozza, a private lawyer who worked
as an assistant secretary, has emerged as a candidate. Other
possibles are Sam Skinner, chairman of Chicago's Regional Transit
Authority; Rep. Guy Molinari of New York; Peter Schabarum, an urban
transportation expert; James Burnett, former head of the National
Transportation Safety Board; Rep. Lynn Martin of Illinois and Allan
McArtor, the administrator at the Federal Aviation Administration.
   _ Labor. Rep. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania is a leading contender,
as is William Kilberg, a Washington lawyer who worked in the
department in the Nixon administration. Ann Dore McLaughlin, the
current secretary, could keep the job, but she'll have stiff
competition from Ridge, Kilberg and former Rep. John Ehrlenborn of
Illinois.
   _ Housing and Urban Development. Possibilities are Cleveland
Mayor George Voinovich, Indianapolis Mayor William Hudnut,
businessman Robert Woodson and campaign official Thaddeus Garrett.
   _ Commerce. Houston oilman Robert Mosbacher, a longtime friend of
Bush, is believed to have the job nailed down if he wants it. Others
on the list are former Delaware Gov. Pete du Pont, baseball
commissioner Peter Ueberroth and James Robinson, head of American
Express Co.
   _ Veterans. Ridge has been mentioned, as has Everett Alvarez, a
former deputy administrator of the Veterans Administration, retired
Gen. Pete Dawkins and former Sen. Jeremiah Denton.
</TEXT>
