<1ST_LINE>u i PM-France-Dolphins     11-23 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Dolphins,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dolphins Who Were Stranded In Cairo Pool Arrive In France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two peforming dolphins who were stranded for months
in a classy Cairo swimming pool arrived in France today after being
spirited out of Egypt to avoid a legal battle that could have kept
them there.
   Leo and Nemo, flown to France in a ZAS Boeing 707, were placed in
a hospital pool at Marineland Cote d'Azur, according to Dr. David
Taylor, a veterinarian caring for the animals. They immediately
began to eat.
   ``They're in very, very good spirits. They're eating extremely
well, eating high quality herring,'' Taylor said in a telephone
interview.
   He was hopeful about Nemo, who is suffering from pneumonia in one
lung, liver trouble and skin problems. Both animals had grown
lethargic after a year of swimming in circles in the pool of Cairo's
Meridien hotel.
   The dolphins were brought to the Meridien last November to
perform in the main pool for guests during the winter season. But
they were stranded there after the contract allegedly expired May
31, with the owners, the International Dolphin Show Co., saying it
had nowhere to take them.
   Edouard Speck, the Meridien hotel general manager, has said the
hotel is taking Leo's and Nemo's owners to court to decide the
animals' eventual fate.
   A hearing is scheduled for Nov. 27.
   Bruno Lienhardt of Switzerland, the owner of the
Liechtenstein-based company which owns the dolphins, said the
contract was not due to expire until May 1989, but in April the
hotel decided it wanted to use its pool for guests.
   ``I traveled everywhere to find a suitable pool for the
dolphins,'' he told The Associated Press in Cairo. ``I couldn't find
anything in one month.''
   Taylor said Lienhardt, learning of the dolphins planned
departure, began obtaining court injunctions to freeze their
movement.
   Taylor said travel plans on Air France were changed and the
dolphins were spirited from the Meridien pool in the dark of night
onto another carrier. ``It was a very smooth, fast operation.''
   ``What counts at the bottom of the pile is the animals'
welfare,'' said Taylor who is a specialist on exotic animals. He is
part of the International Zoo Veterinary Group based in Lightwater,
outside London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
