<2ND_LINE>PM-Young Refugee, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0492,0716</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Orphan Greeted Amid Laughter, Tears</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to ADD details on cannibalism aboard ship,
boy refusing to talk about events aboard ship; Picks up 10th graf,
`We worried ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crowd greeted a young Vietnamese boat
refugee who made it to the United States alone after watching his
parents and brother die at sea while starving shipmates resorted to
cannibalism.
   As Hung Quoc Tran's grandmother fell sobbing to her knees on an
airport concourse Tuesday night, the 10-year-old boy quietly shed a
single tear that streaked the blue union of a .
   The flag, presented to Hung by Rep. Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., had
flown over the U.S. Capitol.
   ``I think he'll feel right at home. It's a beautiful ending, a
happy ending,'' Anthony said.
   The folded U.S. flagboy was aboard a crowded boat found drifting without
food or
water in the South China Sea June 9 by a U.S. Navy ship, the USS
Dubuque, which gave them some supplies but left without taking any
of the 100 refugees aboard.
   The Dubuque's commander, Capt. Alexander G. Balian, was relieved
of duty after the incident. He was charged with failing to render
assistance.
   Survivors said a 12-year-old boy and a 15-year-old boy were
murdered and eaten aboard the 35-foot cra the
boy's family left Vietnam illegally by boat after their efforts for
official emigration clearance failed. They set out in May hoping to
reach the Arkansas town of El Dorado, where Tong had settled and
raised a family after fleeing Saigon in 1975.
   ``We worried. We knew my brother was coming. But no word, no
word,'' said Tong.
   In June, Tong got word from the Philippines that her brother,
sister-in-law and nephew were dead. But she learned that Hung was
alive, plucked from the boat in June by Filipino fishermen and
detained in a United Nations camp at Puerto Princesa in the
Philippines.
   ``I was so worried _ he's only 10 years old and all alone,'' she
said. Tong began sending letters to officials, aiming to bring the
orphan to El Dorado.
   With urging from Arkansas' congressional delegation and the U.S.
Catholic Conference, the Immigration and Naturalization Service
granted Hung refugee status, and the Catholic organization
coordinated his trip from the Philippines.
   As Hung stepped from a jet at Little Rock Regional Airport,
onlookers applauded and his family surged forward to meet him.
   The boy leaned into his aunt's arms, awed by the attention he was
receiving. He whispered to her.
   ``He says thank you. He's happy to see Grandma,'' Tong said.
   Anthony said he hoped Hung's story would publicize the plight of
Vietnamese refugees who are stalled in camps like the one at Puerto
Princesa, where the 4,000 detainees include about 300 minors.
   ``The shame of it is you have a lot of young boys just like this
whose parents die or they try to come over here with friends or
relatives,'' the congressman said. ``It takes two or three years,
sometimes, to process them.''
   Hung also got a letter of greeting from Gov. Bill Clinton, along
with an invitation relayed by an aide to visit Clinton at the state
Capitol.
</TEXT>
