<1ST_LINE>r i PM-USSoldiersKilled     11-23 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US Soldiers Killed,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three U.S. Soldiers Killed in Training Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three U.S. soldiers were killed in
a nighttime training operation in Bavaria when their tank fell into
a pit and overturned, the U.S. Army reported today.
   The accident Sunday night at the Hohenfels military training
grounds also injured another soldier, Army spokesman 1st Lt. Patrick
Sawyer said in a telephone interview from 3rd Infantry Division
headquarters in Wuerzburg.
   Sawyer identified the dead soldiers as: Capt. Donald M. Kessler,
31, of Canton, Ga.; Staff Sgt. James Frear, 30, of Deridder, La.;
and Spec. Anthony T. Tallos, 20, of Philadelphia. Pvt. Dean C. Brown
was released after being treated for minor injuries, Sawyer said.
   The accident occurred when the men inadvertently drove the tank
into a pit normally used as a fighting position for military
vehicles during combat maneuvers, Sawyer said.
   Army authorities are investigating the accident.
   The Hohenfels military training area is 75 miles northwest of
Munich.
