<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia     11-23 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kosovo Bans All Mass Assemblies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in the southern province of
Kosovo today banned all mass gatherings after five days of the
region's biggest rallies in more than four decades of Communist rule.
   In the neighboring southern republic of Macedonia, meanwhile,
15,000 people protested what they said was discrimination against
the ethnic Macedonian minority in northern Greece.
   The indefinite ban on mass gatherings in Kosovo was announced by
the state-run news agency Tanjug. It quoted Rahman Morina, Kosovo's
chief of interior affairs, as saying ``extraordinary circumstances
have taken place which threaten public order.
   ``All those failing to comply (with the decree) will be subject
to all legal and other measures.'' Tanjug did not elaborated.
   The decree said the ban on mass gatherings ``should not affect
normal development of public and cultural life of citizens.''
   The protests in Kosovo were triggered by the forced resignations
Nov. 17 of two ethnic Albanian leaders, Kacusa Jasari and Azem
Vlasi, under pressure from the Communist Party leadership in the
republic of Serbia.
   The move sparked the largest demonstrations ever in the province,
with up to 100,000 people noisily demanding the reinstatement of
Jasari and Vlasi.
   Provincial party leaders have promised to review Jasari's and
Vlasi's resignations at a meeting tentatively scheduled later this
week.
   No demonstrations were reported Tuesday or early today from
Kosovo's capital of Pristina, 240 miles south of Belgrade.
   But the ban _ and a provision forbidding marchers from entering
Pristina _ indicated officials feared further demonstrations.
   Observers believe there might be renewed protests if the two
ethnic Albanian leaders' resignations are not reversed.
   Slobodan Milosevic, the Serbian Communist Party leader, pushed
hard for the resignations as part of his drive to gain more control
of Kosovo.
   Kosovo won broad autonomy under the 1974 constitution. Milosevic
wants the situation changed to protect the Serb and Montenegrin
minorities in Kosovo from alleged ethnic Albanian harassment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
