<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NIU-Racism     11-23 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIU-Racism,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northern Illinois Suspends Fraternity after Skit Labeled Racist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DE KALB, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northern Illinois University has suspended a
fraternity for performing a skit in blackface and Afro wigs.
   Administrators were considering whether to take further action
against Sigma Chi, which was suspended Monday, said Jon Dalton, NIU
vice president for student affairs.
   ``This conduct is of a most serious nature and I believe tht very
serious sanctions are necessary,'' he said.
   Five Sigma Chi members performed a parody of The Temptations, the
black singing group, at a charity fund-raiser Sunday. Students and
others in the audience complained that the skit was racist, Dalton
said.
   ``We are making sure that the chapter has publicly and in writing
apologized to other Greek organizations as well as to the black
student organizations,'' said Fred Yoder, spokesman for the
fraternity's international headquarters.
   Under the suspension, Sigma Chi cannot meet as a campus
organization, have parties or participate in intramural sports,
Yoder said.
   The university could ban the fraternity, continue the suspension,
replace its officers or otherwise restrict its activities.
   Yoder said he did not know if there were any blacks among the 85
members of the chapter.
   In 1987, students in a van shouted slurs at people attending a
speech by the Rev. Jesse Jackson. Three days later, flyers bearing
racial insults and swastikas appeared on campus buses.
   Later in the year, a race-baiting publication called ``Stump''
was distributed on campus.
</TEXT>
