<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   11-23 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0523,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Strike; Charges Reportedly Recommended For Jewish
Settler</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with 3 Palestinians wounded.
Pickup 3rd graf pvs, ``Israel radio...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians shut down the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip with a general strike today to protest the
deportation of dozens of Palestinians in the yearlong uprising.
   Police recommended that prominent Jewish settler Rabbi Moshe
Levinger be tried in the shooting death of a Palestinian, a
Parliament member said.
   Also today, two Palestinian teen-agers and a 5-year-old boy were
shot and wounded in stone-throwing clashes with troops during the
general strike, called by PLO underground leaders of the uprising,
hospital officials said.
   Israel radio said an army officer was sentenced to two weeks in
prison for failing to stop a rampage in which troops smashed houses
and overturned cars after the soldiers were stoned in a refugee camp
in the West Bank.
   The officer, a second lieutenant, was sentenced Tuesday in a
quick trial after the incident in the Kalandia camp a day earlier,
the radio said. The army said it was checking the report.
   The left-wing Peace Now movement became the first Israeli group
to respond positively to the PLO's implicit recognition of Israel.
   The PLO did so when its parliament-in-exile met in Algiers and
declared an independent state in the occupied lands.
   ``In Algiers the PLO abandoned the path of rejection ... and
adopted the path of political compromise,'' said a Peace Now
advertisement in the Jerusalem Post. ``The government of Israel must
call for direct negotiations with the PLO on the basis of mutual
recognition and cessation of violence,'' said the ad by Peace Now,
which was founded during peace negotiations with Egypt in 1978.
   The Israeli government has rejected the PLO's acceptance of U.N.
Security Council Resolution 242, which implicitly recognizes Israel.
   A 13-year-old Palestinian boy died today of a bullet wound to the
head suffered during a clash with troops on Saturday in the village
of Beita near Nablus, the army said. Arab reports identified him as
Amar Muhib Hamayel.
   He was the 315th Palestinian to be killed since the uprising
against Israeli rule began Dec. 8. Eleven Israelis also have died.
   Ran Cohen, a member of Parliament from the left-wing Citizens
Rights Movement, said police recommended charges against Levinger, a
settler leader in Hebron who allegedly opened fire during a
rock-throwing attack in the West Bank city. Kayed Hassan Salah, 42,
was killed outside his store and another Palestinian was wounded in
the shooting Sept. 30.
   Cohen quoted a letter from District Police Superintendent Eitan
Katz saying investigators recommended on Oct. 26 ``to put Rabbi
Levinger on trial for causing death and wounding another person
while using firearms.''
   Asked about the police recommendation, Justice Ministry
spokeswoman Etty Eshed said: ``There's no decision yet. We are short
of people and every case is important. I assume they would decide in
the case soon ... a week to 10 days.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
