<DOCNO> AP881123-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1202EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaRouche 1stLd-Writethru a0447 11-23 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0447,640</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout to include today's
testimony.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former security aide to Lyndon H.
LaRouche Jr. told LaRouche's conspiracy trial today that the
political maverick lied to his employees, gave orders while drunk
and let his lieutenants harass political figures.
   Charles Tate told jurors he quit the LaRouche organization in
disgust four years ago after he saw LaRouche staffers ``insulted and
humiliated'' by LaRouche and others.
   Tate came under sharp questioning from defense attorney William
Moffitt, who tried to show the jury that Tate harbored malice toward
his former employer.
   LaRouche and six associates are charged with conspiracy to
defraud those who loaned the political organization money, while
LaRouche alone is charged with conspiring to defraud the Internal
Revenue Service by failing to pay taxes.
   Under cross-examination, Tate admitted he went to a Halloween
party of former LaRouche staffers in 1986 where he did an imitation
of LaRouche giving orders while _ Tate said _ the leader was under
the influence of alcohol.
   Under direct examination from prosecutor John Markham, Tate said
he quit the LaRouche organization four years ago because the
movement had ``contempt for decent ordinary humanity.''
   ``I had witnessed Mr. LaRouche lie to the membership again and
again,'' Tate testified. ``I had seen revolting actions.''
   ``I had seen members of the organization insulted and
humiliated,'' he said.
   Tate said the organization harassed political figures, from
liberals to conservatives, and LaRouche followers assumed false
identities to gain information on their enemies.
   In earlier testimony, Tate said a 12-member security staff played
``maid and butler'' to LaRouche, catering to every personal need
during the years LaRouche declared no taxable income.
   According to a federal grand jury, LaRouche conspired to defraud
the IRS by not filing tax returns since 1979, and by failing to
declare the cost of personal services as income. The grand jury also
charged LaRouche and six co-defendants with conspiring to defraud
those who loaned the LaRouche movement money, by resolving not to
pay them back.
   Tate quoted chief LaRouche fund-raiser William Wertz as telling
staffers ``there was no such thing as a loan'' and money given as
loans should not be repaid barring a ``political downside'' or a
threatened lawsuit. Tate said those remarks caused him to quit
LaRouche's organization in 1984.
   Tate said the security staff had round-the-clock shifts, playing
``maid and butler'' to LaRouche and his wife, Helga, whether they
were at their residences in New York City, their 40-acre estate in
the horse country of Leesburg, Va., hotels or their home of Mainz,
West Germany.
   Chores included serving food, cleaning, walking Mrs. LaRouche's
dog, caring for her horses, maintaining LaRouche's fleet of
limousines, and grocery shopping, he said.
   Tate described Wertz as someone whose steel-tough discipline
brought internal dissension among LaRouche staffers. Wertz ordered a
military style daily roll call and exhorted the staff to ``take the
beachhead'' and ``capture the bridges,'' the witness said.
   Sometimes, Tate testified, Wertz quoted World War II hero Gen.
George Patton, and played the soundtrack of the movie ``Patton''
starring George C. Scott.
   But Tate said that LaRouche backed Wertz all the way, credited
him for the movement's fund-raising success, and told staffers,
``Wertz reports directly to me.''
   LaRouche and his associates are building their defense with two
cornerstones. They insist that they planned to repay the more than
$30 million in loans they received, but had to divert their money to
defend the movement against attacks from the government and news
media.
   And LaRouche contends he filed no tax returns because he had no
income.
   The co-defendants are Wertz, chief LaRouche legal adviser Edward
Spannaus and four fund-raisers: Michael Billington, Dennis Small,
Paul Greenberg and Joyce Rubinstein.
</TEXT>
