<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1206EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   11-23 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: it proposed.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 19
   Worthington (Minn.) Daily Globe on child care:
   One of the once-burning issues of the now-burned-out presidential
campaign was the need for affordable child care options for working
mothers.
   Democratic and Republican candidates proposed plans to help the
women of America return to the workforce after time off to have a
baby. But it appears a comprehensive federal child care act is far
from reality.
   Republicans claim Democratic proposals are too expensive.
Democrats claim Republican proposals reach too few.
   Of course, now that the election is over, the burning need for
child care has flamed out on Capitol Hill. With the increasing
concern over the burgeoning federal deficit, nearly everyone in
Washington agrees finding dollars to pay for any type of child care
program will be difficult.
   For 1.5 million women who stay home because they cannot find
adequate, affordable child care, the issue still burns like 1,000
points of light.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 20
   Los Angeles Herald Examiner on the Reagan-Thatcher meeting:
   They were the international odd couple. She the brilliant
workaholic who always seems to know more than any of the
``experts''; he a friendly, avuncular guy who often leads with his
heart instead of his head.
   Yet Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and President Ronald Reagan
were kindred spirits, both fighting the good fight for democracy and
prosperity.
   Last week, as the visiting prime minister said farewell to the
president before he leaves office, they couldn't seem to compliment
each other enough. ...
   But all this self-congratulation and warm talk is distorting
what's happening around the world.
   In the Soviet Union, for example, the man who we can do business
with, seems to be less eager to play at democratizing these days and
more interested in consolidating and fortifying his power. Likewise
the warm winds of change in China have turned a bit chilly this
season.
   Ron and Maggie certainly have had an influence on the world, but
this globe is far too complex a place to believe two Westerners
alone can change the face of it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 18
   The Register-Herald, Beckley, W.Va., on the collapse of one of
the nation's largest radiotelescopes at Green Bank, W.Va.:
   It may be weeks before the cause of the collapse (Nov. 15) of one
of the world's largest radiotelescopes at the National Radio
Astronomy Observatory in Green Bank (W.Va.) is known, but taxpayers
should pay heed to the immediate comments of one of the
observatory's officials.
   Surveying the vast crushed pile of metal plates and girders ...,
assistant observatory director George Seielstad criticized the
design and materials used to construct the 300-foot-diameter dish
some 26 years ago.
   Noting the dish was originally supposed to be 140 feet in
diameter, but was allegedly expanded without changes in its design
or materials, Seielstad told reporters the collapse ``was the price
you paid to do something fast and cheap.''
   It's comforting to know that even the ``experts'' can make
mistakes, but before these astronomers build a new radiotelescope,
we suggest they get their heads out of the clouds.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 19
   The Milwaukee Journal on education for workfare recipients:
   Across Wisconsin hundreds of women on welfare attend college,
generally the surest route to self-sufficiency in the nation.
   Yet, the state's workfare program in effect expects them to drop
out and either get a full-time job or enroll in a job-training
program. ...
   Just (recently) came news of a two-year study concluding that
young Americans who do not attend college have a high chance of
facing dead-end jobs with poverty level pay or no jobs at all.
   Yet, according to testimony before a state legislative committee,
welfare officials advised one single parent to quit the University
of Wisconsin-Parkside, where she is a freshman, and learn auto
mechanics. ...
   This rule is completely upside down. Workfare ought to encourage
college attendance. ...
   Sure, officials should monitor attendance closely to make sure
that welfare recipients are genuinely working toward degrees. But
punishing them for going to college is an inanity begging for a
legislative remedy.
</TEXT>
