<HEAD>Government Artillery Fire Kills Family of Six</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAGAYAN DE ORO, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops bombarding a suspected
communist rebel hideout in the southern Philippines accidentally
killed a family of six when an artillery shell hit a hut, a military
official said Wednesday.
   Col. Rogelio Villanueva, army regional commander, said the
incident occured Sunday in the village of Maritula, about 525 miles
southeast of Manila.
   Before the accident, government troops on patrol clashed with a
group of Communist New People's Army guerrillas near Maritula,
Villanueva said. After a 30-minute firefight, the rebels fled to
different directions with most of them running toward Maritula.
   The soldiers radioed for artillery fire after pinpointing where
the rebels had hidden, he said. One of five rounds from a 105mm
Howitzer cannon landed in the house, killing the family. The rebels
escaped, he added.
   Villanueva said he had ordered an investigation into the accident.
