<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-Hotel,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Famous Hotel Fined For Health, Safety Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dorchester, one of London's grandest hotels,
has been fined about $11,900 for violating health and safety
regulations.
   Prosecutor Geoffrey Stevenson told Bow Street Magistrates Court
on Tuesday that health officers in March found part of the hotel's
main kitchen infested with cockroaches.
   The Sultan of Brunei, one of the world's richest men, paid $55.9
million for the 280-bedroom hotel on swank Park Lane in 1985.
   The 57-year-old hotel was headquarters for Gen. Dwight D.
Eisenhower, the Allied Supreme Commander in World War II.
   On behalf of the hotel, lawyer Patrick Hamlin pleaded guilty to
17 counts of infringing food and hygiene regulations and one count
under safety regulations charging the kitchen floor was slippery
with grease and very dangerous.
   Stevenson said kitchen ceilings, walls, an open gully and cooking
equipment were covered in grease.
   Since the inspection, the hotel has spent $170,190 improving the
kitchen, Hamlin said.
   An average single room at the Dorchester costs $219 a night and
dinner for one about $54.
</TEXT>
