<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--EEC-Poverty     11-23 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--EEC-Poverty,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Poor People in European Community</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of poor people in the
European Economic Community has grown to 44 million, or 14 percent
of its population, the EEC Commission reported Wednesday.
   The people it considers poor earn less than half the average per
capita income of the 12 countries in which they live, it said in a
report.
   But it warns the figure of 44 million is imprecise, since poverty
is not just a matter of income. The commission said it lacks enough
data about other factors, such as housing and education, to make a
fair EEC-wide comparison.
   It attributed the increasing number of poor to ``growing
unemployment, under-employment and unstable and underpaid work as
well as the increase in single parent families.''
   In all, the elderly form the largest group among the poor, the
report said.
   In the 1985-89 period, the EEC contributes a modest $35 million
to 91 projects in all EEC nations aimed at alleviating conditions
for the unemployed, single parents, migrants and refugees and urban
poor.
</TEXT>
