<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Interpol     11-23 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Interpol,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Police Chief Elected Interpol President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France's national police chief Ivan
Barbot was elected president of Interpol on Wednesday, beating his
Thai counterpart after intense lobbying for leadership of the
international police organization.
   The vote was 72-50 for Barbot, said Interpol spokesman M.
Chamorro. A second vote went 72-48 with two abstentions.
   Barbot needed 80 votes for a two-thirds majority win. But Thai
Police Director-General Pow Sarasin withdrew his candidacy for the
unsalaried post after the second vote result was announced, Chamorro
said.
   At a news conference, Barbot said priorities for his four-year
term are improving international cooperation, telecommunications and
computerization of Interpol information.
   He succeeds John R. Simpson of the U.S. Secret Service.
   Police chiefs from 122 nations attended Interpol's 57th Annual
General Assembly in Bangkok that ended Wednesday. Interpol has 147
member nations.
   Interpol Secretary-General R. E. Kendall said there were
``considerable improvements'' in international cooperation against
illicit drug trafficking this year. But he said organized crime is
increasing, and ``We are fighting an uphill battle.''
</TEXT>
