<HEAD>Strike Ends at Latin America's Largest Steel Mill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of workers returned to
their jobs today at Latin America's largest steel mill, ending a
17-day strike marked by a clash with soldiers that left three
strikers dead and scores injured.
   The workers voted to accept a proposed wage increase and end
their walkout at the state-owned National Steel Co. in Volta Redonda
northwest of Rio, Jose Queiroz, a plant administrator said in a
telephone interview. Soldiers who occupied the plant for two weeks
began to withdraw, he said.
   The union agreed to an 8 percent raise and a bonus of about $50.
Workers also were to receive a 24 percent cost-of-living raise that
was suspended by the government in July, and the plant management
promised to reduce the shift from eight hours to six within 90 days.
   Earlier, the union had demanded a 26 percent wage increase and a
cost-of-living adjustment. Workers make an average salary of about
$40 a week.
   Inflation in Brazil is running at over 1,000 percent, and many
workers get monthly cost-of-living raises. But the government claims
the raises fuel inflation and has tried to restrict them for federal
employees.
   The strike at the National Steel Co. was the bloodiest in a
recent wave of labor protests acoss the country.
   On Nov. 9, 3,000 strikers armed with rocks, steel pipes and
firebombs battled 800 soldierm the Bridge,'' saved the
hand after the rest of the statue in Budapest was demolished on Oct.
23, 1956, MTI said.
   ``The monstrous piece that has since been decorating the actor's
garden, who died in 1972, was now sold by his widow,'' MTI said in
the English-language dispatch.
   The right hand from the Stalin statue will be part of an
exhibition next year on Stalinism in Hungary.
   In 1956, Soviet leader Nikita S. Khrushchev gave his ``secret
speech'' to a meeting of the Soviet Communist party Central
Committee, beginning a broad de-Stalinization campaign that led to
the destruction of thousands of Stalin statues and the renaming of
Stalin factories, streets and schools throughout the Soviet Union.
Stalin died in 1953.
</TEXT>
