<DOCNO> AP881123-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HospitalCare     11-23 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Care,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hip Fracture Patients More Likely To Be Confined to Nursing Homes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elderly people who break their hips are more likely
to be discharged from hospitals before they can walk and forced to
live in nursing homes since Medicare began paying flat fees for
their care, a study says.
   The report, based on the records of one hospital, shows that
hospitalization for hip fractures has been cut by 40 percent since
the start of the new payment system in 1984.
   The findings suggest ``the overall quality of care for these
patients may have deteriorated,'' the researchers wrote.
   Under the new system, Medicare pays flat fees to hospitals for
specific illnesses, no matter how long patients stay. This gives
hospitals an incentive to treat patients more efficiently. However,
critics say it also may pressure them to send patients home before
they are well.
   The new study found that the proportion of hip fracture patients
remaining in nursing homes one year after their hospitalization rose
from 9 percent to 33 percent since the start of the new program.
   This increase ``is alarming and represents the most important
finding of this study,'' wrote Dr. John F. Fitzgerald and colleagues
from Indiana University School of Medicine.
   They said this suggests that since the start of the new payment
system, patients are less likely to recover enough to live on their
own and instead become long-term residents of nursing homes.
   The study, published in Thursday's New England Journal of
Medicine, was based on a review of 331 people treated from 1981 to
1986 at a large community hospital in the Midwest. It was not
identified.
   They said that since the start of the new payment system:
   _Hospitalization for hip fractures decreased from 22 days to 13
days.
   _The proportion of patients who could walk at all when discharged
dropped from 56 percent to 40 percent.
   _The distance patients could walk when discharged fell from 93
feet to 38 feet.
   _The proportion discharged directly to nursing homes rose from 38
percent to 60 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
