<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FuelSpill     11-23 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fuel Spill,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inspector Never Examined Tank Before Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official of the county fire marshal's office
falsely claimed to have inspected an Ashland Oil Inc. diesel tank a
year and a half before it collapsed, fouling drinking water in
several states, police said.
   Charles E. Kelly wrote in a May 19, 1986, memo that ``this
inspector performed an on-site inspection'' that day but has since
admitted he did not visit the site, said Richard Winters, Allegheny
County assistant police superintendent.
   Kelly's office was responsible for inspecting the tank at
Ashland's Floreffe terminal that collapsed south of Pittsburgh on
Jan. 2, spilling more than 700,000 gallons of fuel into the
Monongahela River.
   The spill cut off drinking water in West Virginia, Pennsylvania
and Ohio.
   Ashland later admitted it did not obtain the required permit to
erect the tank.
   Former Fire Marshal Martin A. Jacobs on Tuesday admitted lying in
a sworn deposition when he said he didn't know about the existence
of the memo. Jacobs and Kelly resigned Friday at the request of
Police Superintendent Robert G. Kroner.
   The memo was revealed last month by Edward Babyak, deputy fire
marshal. County fire and police officials had previously denied such
a memo existed.
   Babyak also was asked to resign but refused, and was suspended
pending a review of dismissal procedures.
</TEXT>
