<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Charges,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Says AIDS Patient Being Persecuted Because of AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Family and friends of an AIDS patient charged
with endangering a nurse say he is being persecuted because of his
condition.
   Scott Fleming, 25, of Los Angeles, was experiencing a seizure,
not trying to hurt the nurse, when he struck out at her as she drew
blood from his arm, they said Tuesday. The nurse was stabbed in the
finger with the needle.
   ``We told them he had AIDS so they could take precautions,'' said
Ilsa Andress, who said she telephoned paramedics when Fleming
experienced a seizure at her home last week. ``Instead they're
trying to persecute him because of it.''
   Fleming has been jailed on $50,000 bail on charges of attempted
battery and endangering.
   The nurse at the Milwaukee County Medical Complex in Wauwatosa
was drawing a blood sample when Fleming jerked his arm away, called
her a name and swung at her, the Milwaukee County Sheriff's
Department said.
   Fleming's roommate, Patrick Leyba, said that it was not like
Fleming to be violent but that Fleming could act unusually if he had
one of the seizures he has experienced since childhood.
   ``I can understand the nurse's feelings. But my son has only four
months to live,'' said Ronald Fleming. ``We've already talked with a
funeral director about what we're going to do, and now this
happens.''
</TEXT>
