<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DurableGoods     11-23 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Durable Goods,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orders for Non-Military Durable Goods Drop for Second Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for durable goods,
excluding military equipment, slipped in October for the second
consecutive month, the government said Wednesday, but economists
weren't unduly concerned about the weakness.
   The Commerce Department said total orders, including the biggest
gain in military goods since June, rose 2.4 percent last month to a
seasonally adjusted $122.1 billion.
   However, excluding the defense category, which swings widely from
month to month, orders fell 0.2 percent in October and 2.5 percent
in September.
   Nevertheless, economists weren't overly worried, pointing to the
steady increase in the backlog of unfilled orders, which rose 0.8
percent to $435.7 billion in October after increasing 0.3 percent in
September and 1.2 percent in August.
   ``The backlogs will keep the (manufacturing) sector humming ...
well into next year,'' said Cynthia Latta, an economist with Data
Resources Inc., a forecasting firm in Lexington, Mass. ``The idea
that growth is slowing is correct ... but it certainly doesn't
portend a recession.''
   Other economic indicators, including employment, retail sales,
consumer prices and industrial production, portray a robust, if
somewhat inflationary, economy, in October.
   The report on orders for durable goods, ``big ticket'' items
ranging from bicycles to battleships, is the first hint of softness.
   ``From the point of view of (those worried that the economy is)
overheating, it's a favorable development,'' Ms. Latta said.
   The key category of non-defense capital goods, a barometer of
business expansion plans, also fell for the second month. It was
down 2.6 percent last month to $34.0 billion, following a 10.2
percent drop in September, the largest since January 1986.
   Capital spending has been one of the strongest sectors of the
economy this year because manufacturers spent heavily to increase
production for booming export markets.
   ``You can see some of the edge coming off the fast rates of
growth in capital spending, but it still remains healthy,'' said
Jerry Jasinowski, chief economist of the National Association of
Manufacturers. He said manufacturers in his organization expect
``reasonably good'' business through the first half of 1989.
   The 2.4 percent increase in October orders followed a decline of
2.9 percent in September and a rise of 5.2 percent in August.
   Defense orders totaled $10.4 billion, up 41.1 percent from
September. The department attributed much of the gain to orders for
new ships.
   Transportation equipment, boosted by gains at auto plants as well
as shipbuilding, rose 8.9 percent in October to $34.4 billion,
almost rebounding from a 9.1 percent drop in September.
   Excluding transportation, orders rose a scant 0.1 percent in
October and fell 0.4 percent in September.
   In other categories last month, orders for primary metals
including steel fell 0.6 percent following a 5.9 percent rise.
Orders in the machinery category that includes computers fell 3.6
percent. Electrical machinery was up 1.8 percent.
   Shipments of durable goods rose 0.5 percent last month to $118.7
billion, following a 0.2 percent rise in September.
</TEXT>
