<HEAD>Injured Shopowner Dies, Raising Rampage Death Toll to Seven</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SAfrica-Extremists, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shopowner wounded in a shooting
spree last week has died of his injuries, raising to seven the death
toll from a rampage by an ex-policeman who opened fire randomly at
blacks.
   Abdul Carrim, owner of a jewelry store in central Pretoria, died
Tuesday night, reportedly of heart failure caused by a blood clot.
He was shot in the leg Nov. 16 when he confronted the gunman during
the rampage.
   Six blacks were killed and 17 people injured, all of them black
except Carrim, 52, who was of Indian descent.
   The gunman has been identified as Barend Strydom, 23, who quit
the national police force in February while facing misconduct
charges. He is a member of the Afrikaner Resistance Movement, a
whites-only paramilitary group.
   The government responded to the rampage by threatening a
crackdown on extreme-right groups. But the leader of the resistance
movement, Eugene TerreBlanche, said at a rally Tuesday night near
Cape Town that his group was too powerful to be banned.
   Strydom is to undergo psychiatric testing pending his Dec. 19
court appearance.
