<DOCNO> AP881123-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1332EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ConanOwen     11-23 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Conan Owen,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pardon Sought For Photographer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five members of Congress asked President Reagan
on Wednesday to pardon Conan Owen, the Annandale, Va., photographer
freed from a Spanish prison after serving time for what U.S.
officials say was a wrongful drug trafficking conviction.
   Owen, 24, arrived at his suburban Washington home Tuesday night,
on his parents' 27th wedding anniversary, to a boisterous greeting
from neighbors and friends who had festooned the place with balloons
and welcoming signs. Technically, he must remain there under house
arrest until March, when he will be eligible for a U.S. parole.
   ``The tragedy of Conan Owen's story is finally coming to an
end,'' said Rep. Stan Parris, R-Va., who is Owen's congressman.
``This story, however, will not be concluded until Conan's name is
finally cleared _ and that requires a presidential pardon.''
   Parris and four congressional colleagues sent Reagan a letter
asking him to ``grant Mr. Owen a full presidential pardon and, in
accordance with the findings of the Justice Department, establish
his innocence. Your action will help to end a year- and a half-long
nightmare for Mr. Owen and his family.''
   Others signing the letter were Reps. Romano Mazzoli, D-Ky.,
Thomas Carper, D-Del., Bill Nichols, D-Ala., and Trent Lott, R-Miss,
a senator-elect.
   In Annandale, Owen said ``It was really great to see all those
familiar faces, all the familiar sights. It's a great relief.'' He
said he plans to write a book about his experiences.
   ``I'm going to give it a try, try to write it out,'' said the
congenial Owen. ``It can't be too hard _ after all, Donald Trump
wrote one.''
   Owen was convicted in Barcelona last April of carrying four
pounds of cocaine from Chile into Spain beneath the false bottom of
a suitcase. He was on a free-lance photo assignment for a travel
brochure.
   The young photographer steadfastly maintained that he was unaware
the drugs were there, and the man who arranged the assignment, Jorge
Barahona of Washington, later admitted in a U.S. court that he had
planted the drugs in the suitcase without Owen's knowledge.
Then-Attorney General Edwin Meese presented Barahona's confession to
Spanish authorities, as well as other evidence he said established
Owen's innocence, but to no avail.
   After spending 19 months in a Spanish jail, Owen was transferred
to a Loretto, Pa., prison Nov. 8 under terms of a treaty that
provides for the transfer of prisoners between the U.S. and Spain
when a citizen of one country is convicted of a crime in another.
   Federal prison officials on Tuesday released Owen for a holiday
furlough. Meanwhile, a plan approved by U.S. Parole Commission
allows Owen to serve the remaining months of his sentence at home
under the custody of his parents, Ernest and Raquel Owen. He will be
eligible for parole in March.
   ``I was always afraid it was only going to be a dream, but it's
true,'' Raquel Owen said of her son's homecoming. ``It's marvelous.
I woke up this morning, and there he was reading the newspaper.''
   On Monday, Owen will report to the Fairfax County Home Detention
Program to be fitted with an electronic device that will monitor his
whereabouts during his period of house arrest. The program is likely
to be quite flexible, allowing for outside employment and recreation
time, authorities said.
   ``Everything we've heard indicates there will be very little
problem,'' said Lt. James Vickery, spokesman for the Fairfax County
Sheriff's Department. ``The Federal Bureau of Prisons will set the
standards, but we don't think there will be employment checks or
unplanned home visits.''
   Owen, a 1986 honors graduate of Syracuse University, formerly
worked as a summer intern in Vice President George Bush's office and
had been admitted to the U.S. Army Intelligence School in Fort
Huachuca, Ariz.
   The parole commission said Tuesday that Owen's role in bringing
cocaine into Spain was ``peripheral'' _ a courier with ``no
managerial or proprietary interest'' _ and reduced his minimum
prison sentence from 40 months to 24 months. A parole hearing is
scheduled for March 12.
</TEXT>
