<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Uganda-AIDS     11-23 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uganda-AIDS,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government to Legislate Against Illegitimate Sex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government plans to legislate against
extra-marital sex and seduction of minors by adults as a part of its
campaign to curb the spread of AIDS, it was reported Wednesday.
   ``Those adults who engage in illegitimate extra-marital sexual
relationships could also be punished, provided that we carry out
some other adjustments in the law,'' the state-owned New Vision
newspaper quoted President Yoweri Museveni as saying.
   He spoke Tuesday at the opening session of a national seminar on
United Nations Draft Convention on the Rights of the Child.
   Museveni also said he had suggested the National AIDS Control
Committee introduce legislation to protect anyone under the age of
21 from contracting the disease through sex abuse by adults.
   ``We should make it a severely punishable crime for any adult to
seduce into illegitimate sexual activities anyoby below 21,''
Museveni said, according to the New Vision.
   He said minors also should not engage in illegitimate sexual
relationships.
   ``If they want sex, they should get married,'' Museveni said.
   Uganda has reported 5,000 AIDS cases, according to the National
Aids Control Committee.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer. It is spread most often through sexual
contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood
or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
