<2ND_LINE>PM-Onassis, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0469,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body Flown to Greece; Exact Cause of Death Not Known</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with plane carrying body leaving.
Pick up 4th pvs, A preliminary.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of Greek heiress
Christina Onassis was put on a flight to Greece today after a judge
ruled that an exhumation would not be necessary to determine the
cause of death, the judge's aides said.
   Federal Judge Alberto Piotti authorized release of the body about
2 p.m. as a group of Ms. Onassis' family and friends waited with the
casket at Ezeiza International Airport.
   Aides to Piotti said authorization was granted because forensic
experts said autopsy evidence was sufficient to determine the cause
of death.
   Ms. Onassis' housekeeper, Heleni Syros, was required to stay
behind to help in the investigation of the death. Ms. Syros
apparently was the first to discover Ms. Onassis' body Saturday.
   The private news agency Diarios y Noticias said judges gave final
authorization after Interior Minister Enrique Nosiglia said delaying
the process might cause diplomatic problems.
   Ms. Onassis' body was put on a Swissair jet to be flown to
Switzerland and then Greece for burial on the island of Skorpios in
the Ionian Sea.
   A preliminary coroner's report said the cause of death was acute
pulmonary edema, or buildup of fluid in her lungs. It did not say
what caused the accumulation of fluid.
   The director of Clinica del Sol Hospital, which initially
received the body, said Ms. Onassis, 37, apparently suffered a heart
attack. But forensic experts and police investigators have worked
since an autopsy was conducted last Saturday afternoon to determine
the exact cause.
   The complete coroner's report is expected in about two weeks, the
newspaper La Nacion reported this morning. It is expected to clear
up details such as precisely where Ms. Onassis died and at what
time, uncertainties that raised questions about whether she died of
natural causes.
   On Tuesday, Federal Judge Albert Piotti said he would allow the
release of the body before final results were in hand if medical
examiners told him they had enough material to establish the cause
of death.
   ``We don't intend to impose bureaucratic obstacles to the
delivery of the body (to relatives), but beforehand we must rule out
any possibility of homicide or suicide,'' said Piotti, who gave an
order barring delivery of the body without his authorization.
   ``We're not going to deliver the body until we are certain an
exhumation won't be necessary,'' Piotti said in an interview with
Radio Continental.
   Diarios and Noticias did not name the judges that it said
permitted the body to leave the country.
   La Nacion said the first doctor on the scene at Tortuguitas
Country Club, 25 miles north of Buenos Aires, told police Ms.
Onassis was dead when he arrived and that her body apparently was
dragged from one room to another.
   It said Dr. Arturo Granadillo Fuentes told police he found Ms.
Onassis lying naked on the floor in a hallway, covered only by a
towel. A check of her eyes, pulse and temperature showed she had
been dead for at least an hour, he was quoted as saying.
   When he attempted to question people in the room who apparently
were speaking Greek among themselves, he was ordered to leave the
premises, La Nacion quoted Granadillo as saying.
   Ms. Onassis inherited a fortune estimated at $500 million from
her father, Aristotle, a shipping tycoon who married Jackie Kennedy
and who died in 1975. She is to be buried in a mausoleum on the
family-owned island next to her father and brother Alexander.
</TEXT>
