<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StuffingandGravy     11-23 0912</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stuffing and Gravy,0943</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkey Is King Here Every Day But Thanksgiving</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Thanksgiving Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARSHALL, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customers can have turkey any day of the
week from mid-March to Christmas Eve at Turkeyville, U.S.A. Any day
except Thanksgiving Day, that is.
   Alan Cornwell, manager of Cornwell's Turkey House, doesn't want
to make his employees work on Thanksgiving.
   The family-run restaurant is the only establishment in what the
unofficial highway sign proclaims as Turkeyville, U.S.A.
   Cornwell started it 20 years ago with his parents, Wayne and
Marjorie, who raised turkeys and sold turkey sandwiches at the
county fair for decades. Now Cornwell has help from his four grown
children and his semiretired parents.
   Every year, 300,000 customers flock to Turkeyville to gobble down
turkey that Cornwell personally prepares.
   ``Turkey is so simple to cook. Of course, I've done it so much,''
said Cornwell, who cooks as many as 15,000 turkeys a year.
   Turkey is the only meat served at the restaurant, but it comes in
everything from turkey hot dogs to turkey chili to turkey ruebens.
   The family got so busy with the restaurant it had to give up
raising its own turkeys in the 1970s. It now buys milk-fed turkeys
raised in Indiana. But 200 birds still strut around for show in warm
weather.
   The peak season is not around Thanksgiving, but in the summer.
But the crowds have never been more than Cornwell could feed.
   ``I've come within five pounds, but I've never run out of
turkey,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Rancher Says Live Turkeys Rid Ranch Of Grasshoppers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH PLATTE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Thanksgiving turkey served at the
Albert Sonneman ranch this year first served as a living insecticide.
   Arta Sonneman said her family began raising turkeys four or five
years ago, when grasshoppers were a major problem. The turkeys did
such a good job removing the grasshoppers from the family garden
that fewer turkeys were bought this year because they've eliminated
most of the grasshoppers.
   ``That's really why we started raising them,'' she said.
   Last year, she said, her husband, Albert, counted 115
grasshoppers in the craw of a turkey while dressing the bird.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Consumers Don't Get Bargain On Home-Grown Thanksgiving Staples</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tar Heel shoppers buying the fixings for
Thanksgiving aren't getting a bargain on turkeys and sweet potatoes,
even though North Carolina leads the nation in their production.
   In North Carolina, it'll cost $30.32 to feed 10 people a
self-basting, 16-pound turkey, stuffing, peas, sweet potatoes,
cranberries, a relish dish, pumpkin pie with whipped cream and
coffee, according to a survey by the American Farm Bureau Federation.
   Of the 14 states surveyed, the cost of the meal in North Carolina
is second only to the District of Columbia, where the meal will cost
$32.25. At $19.95, Texas consumers pay the least.
   ``I don't believe North Carolina is the second-highest place in
the United States to eat a home-cooked Thanksgiving meal,'' Jim
Graham, the state's agriculture commissioner, said Wednesday. ``I've
talked with American Farm Bureau in Chicago and they admit the
survey was not scientific. They simply wanted to sample the states
to get some idea of what was going on costwise.
   ``The Farm Bureau could have hit a store in North Carolina that
was in a high population area and running no specials,'' Graham
said. ``In the low state, Texas, they may have hit the deal of the
century.''
   North Carolina produces 20.1 percent of all the nation's turkeys,
said Ed Woodhouse, executive director of the North Carolina Poultry
Federation. The state also produces about 40 percent of the nation's
yams.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Border residents who celebrated
Halloween instead of Day of the Dead are putting turkey on the table
Thursday in another example of what some Mexicans call ``cultural
penetration'' from the north.
   And next month Santa Claus and his reindeer, virtually unknown
two decades ago in Mexico, will be seen in the most remote villages.
   The infiltration of the American traditions has raised the ire of
some residents who fear their own culture is eroding.
   Last weekend, a college student stood on a platform in a park
with a bullhorn, exhorting crowds to fight ``cultural penetration.''
   ``Why do we celebrate Halloween instead of Day of the Dead? Why
do we allow ourselves to be shaped this way by the North
Americans?'' he shouted to some murmurs of approval from the crowd.
``We are abandoning our own traditions!''
   Juarez Mayor Jaime Bermudez said American and Mexican traditions
intermingle. ``There's a lot of American influence here, and the
other way around. The only thing that separates us is a river.
   ``Mexican traditions will be kept intact; we're not going to lose
them. And what about the tacos they eat over in El Paso? And the
enchiladas?''
   Even as families stock up on turkey and stuffing, they're not
honoring the pilgrims, Bermudez said.
   ``Plenty of them buy turkey because it's very cheap this time of
year. It's not that they're celebrating the holiday _ they might not
even know its significance.''
   That apparently is true. In a story about possible turkey
shortages, the leading newspaper in Juarez, El Diario, explained
Thanksgiving with a new twist.
   ``Eating turkey on this day is a U.S. tradition that goes back
centuries, to when a large group of immigrant families were on the
point of starving to death. Miraculously, they found a flock of
these birds, which saved their lives.''
</TEXT>
