<TEXT>
   Robert Cohan, the American choreographer who
pioneered the modern dance movement in Britain, was invested
Wednesday as an honorary commander of the Order of the British
Empire for his contribution to the arts.
   Cohan, 63, a long-time associate of Martha Graham, came to London
in 1967 to found the London Contemporary Dance Theater, the first
British company to be trained in the Graham technique.
   His honor carries no cash award but much prestige and entitles
him to use the initials CBE after his name.
