<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     11-23 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bhutto Says Delay in Forming Government May Cause Instability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benazir Bhutto, whose party won the
most parliament seats a week ago, said Wednesday a crisis may result
if the president does not choose her as Pakistan's next prime
minister.
   Ms. Bhutto's followers won 93 seats in the 237-seat National
Assembly in the Nov. 16 election, compared with 55 for the
nine-party Islamic Democratic Alliance, which includes supporters of
the late President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq.
   She told a news conference the delay is ``an unfair attempt'' by
the right-wing rivals of her populist Pakistan People's Party ``to
subvert the will of the people.''
   Selecting any other party to form a government ``would be highly
dangerous (and) plunge Pakistan into a deep crisis,'' she said.
   After a two-hour meeting Tuesday with President Ghulam Ishaq
Khan, she quoted him as saying he would make his choice after the
National Assembly chooses a speaker Dec. 5, indicating which party
had the most support.
   At the news conference Wednesday, Ms. Bhutto declared that ``even
a single day is too long'' to wait. She claims to have enough
support in smaller parties to form a majority coalition, but has
offered no evidence of such alliances.
   ``As soon as we're called upon to form the government we will
present proof of our majority,'' said Ms. Bhutto, who would be the
first woman to lead an Islamic nation.
   She accused the alliance of coercion, blackmail and misuse of
public funds, and claimed the purpose of Ishaq Khan's delay is
``simply to give them a longer time to use official money ... to
subvert the will of the people.''
   Alliance leader Nawaz Sharif was chosen by Zia to lead a
provincial caretaker government in populous Punjab. Gen. Zia
dismissed his civilian national government May 29 and established
caretaker administrations at the federal and provincial levels until
the election could be held.
   Zia overthrew Ms. Bhutto's father, Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali
Bhutto, in 1977 and Bhutto was hanged in 1979 after being convicted
of complicity in a murder conspiracy. Zia was killed in a plane
crash Aug. 17.
   Sharif also met with Ishaq Khan on Tuesday, and insisted he still
has a chance to form a coalition government. His alliance would need
64 seats from smaller parties but Ms. Bhutto could achieve a
majority with only 26.
   Ishaq Khan was reported to have held meetings Wednesday with
leaders of smaller parties, including the ethnic Mohajir Qami
Movement, which represents Moslem refugees from India and won 13
seats. Both Ms. Bhutto and Sharif have been courting the party.
</TEXT>
