<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     11-23 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Cross Says Iraq & Iran Set for POW Swap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq and Iran will free 150 disabled
prisoners of war Thursday, the first batch of prisoners they agreed
to repatriate early this month.
   Diplomatic sources said the exchange was delayed by prisoners on
both sides balking at going back to their respective countries.
   Red Cross officials said a DC-9 plane will fly from Tehran
carrying 110 Iraqi POWs. It will fly back to Tehran with 41 Iranian
POWs.
   The plane hired by the Red Cross will shuttle between Tehran and
Baghdad for 10 days to repatriate up to 1,115 Iraqis and 411
Iranians, all sick or wounded according to a memorandum of
understanding signed by both Iraq and Iran with the Red Cross.
   Red Cross representative Paul Henri Morard told The Associated
Press that all preparations for the exchange have been completed.
Iraq has set up special camps to process the arriving prisoners
before they go home.
   Morard, who arrived from Geneva to supervise the operation, said
the Red Cross finished its medical checks and had identified all the
POWs who will be repatriated.
   He also said that the Red Cross has asked each POW if he wishes
to be repatriated or not in line with the Geneva conventions on the
treatment of POWs. Morard refused to say whether any declined
repatriation, saying those prisoners will be processed last.
   But the diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said some prisoners have asked to leave for an unidentified Western
country. Also some of the Iranian prisoners want to join the
Mujahedeen Khalq, the Iraq-based opposition group that seeks to
overthrow the government of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, the sources
said.
   Morard said the Red Cross has already registered 50,182 Iraqi
POWs and 19,284 Iranians, but the total number of POWs estimated by
both countries is about 100,000.
   He said the Red Cross has repatriated 765 Iraqi sick and wounded
POWs and 613 Iranians since 1981.
   The Red Cross official said the DC-9 will fly the shortest route
between Tehran and Baghdad. Despite the Aug. 20 gulf war cease-fire,
many planes avoided flying directly over the joint border.
   The operation will be supervised by 17 members of the Red Cross
staff in Baghdad and 18 in Tehran. It is being paid for by an
unidentified Western nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
