<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SovietUnrest 1stLd-Writethru a0640 11-23 0851</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Unrest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0640,0872</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mobs Kill Three Soldiers, Injure at Least 126 in Azerbaijan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs, ``Armenian activist ...'' with 6 grafs to
UPDATE with rally in Yerevan, other details; SUBS last 4 grafs with
1 graf to conform, shorten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rampaging mobs killed three soldiers, injured at
least 126 people and sacked government buildings and trains in the
worst flare-up of ethnic violence in the Soviet south since early
spring, official sources said Wednesday.
   An ``open confrontation'' had developed between the republics of
Azerbaijan and Armenia ``the consequences of which can be
unpredictably tragic,'' according to the official Bakinsky Rabochi
newspaper of Azerbaijan.
   Azerbaijani officials declared a state of emergency in the cities
of Nakichevan, near the Iranian border, and Kirovabad, and
authorities were urgently trying to restore order, said Musa
Mamedov, chief of information for the republic's Foreign Ministry.
   ``Three soldiers were killed, perhaps by stones, perhaps by
sticks,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   Official Baku Radio said ``hooligan elements attacked social and
administrative buildings. As a result of the disruption of law and
order, 126 people were wounded in Kirovabad and three military
personnel were killed.''
   It was the first official report of soldiers being killed in the
Caucasus region since violence erupted in February.
   Lives also were in danger in Baku, where crimes and looting was
increasing, said the Baku radio report monitored in London.
   Hundreds of thousands of people were protesting in the streets of
Baku and the Armenian capital, Yerevan.
   Arpenay Popoyan, wife of Armenian activist Rafael Popoyan, said
in a telephone interview from Yerevan that at least 500,000 people
had gathered in the city's Opera Square during the day, and at night
the crowd marched to the Central Committee of the Armenian Communist
Party.
   ``Practically the whole city went out to the square _ all the
adults and the students _ that's the number there were,'' she said.
   The crowd demanded that a session of the Armenian Supreme Soviet
interrupted Tuesday because of the sharp increase in tensions be
reconvened.
   The Supreme Soviet, which in the past backed activists' demands
for annexation of the Nagorno-Karabakh region from Azerbaijan, had
not yet gotten to that item when its work was interrupted. Mrs.
Popoyan said a general strike in Yerevan would last until the
session was reconvened.
   Popoyan said Armenians decided at a meeting late Tuesday to form
``self-defense squads'' in areas of their republic where
Azerbaijanis live, but there were no reports of violence in Armenia.
   Calls to Baku did not go through Wednesday night.
   Bakinsky Rabochi reported Wednesday that bus travel between the
two republics had been cut off, and that no one was being allowed
into Azerbaijan from Armenia carrying building materials in their
cars.
   In Moscow, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov
said the siuation in Baku was ``difficult,'' and that there had been
casualties in Kirovabad, but he did not elaborate.
   The two republics are in conflict about control over the
predominantly Armenian region of Nagorno-Karabakh in Azerbaijan.
Residents have been agitating since February to have it annexed by
Armenia, but Azerbaijan officials and Kremlin leaders have rejected
the demand.
   Instead, Moscow has ordered a comprehensive social and economic
development plan for the area.
   At least 32 people were killed in three days of rioting in the
Azerbaijani city of Sumgait at the end of February and March that
followed massive protests in Nagorno-Karabakh and Armenia. Armenia
is predominantly Christian and Azerbaijan is predominantly Moslem.
   Azerbaijanis say hundreds of thousands of people took to the
streets beginning five days ago to protest what they say is an
Armenian effort to send settlers to Nagorno-Karabakh to strengthen
the ethnic Armenian majority there.
   They said Armenian settlers were taken last week to the Shusha
area of Nagorno-Karabakh in official trucks and began building
barracks with materials supplied by the Armenian government.
   Bakinsky Rabochi complained that Azerbaijanis in Nagorno-Karabakh
were not being permitted to work and were deprived of food and
medical supplies.
   Armenian activist Hovik Vassilian reported that Kirovabad was
surrounded by Azerbaijanis who were not permitting Armenians to
flee. He said in a telephone interview from the Armenian capital of
Yerevan that calls to the city would not go through.
   Armenian TV showed footage Wednesday night of a train headed for
Armenia that was surrounded and attacked by a mob near Nakhichevan,
Vassilian said.
   Passengers were taken off the train and transported by bus to
Armenia, but the engineers were hurt and ``not a window or door was
left unbroken,'' Vassilian said. The train was damaged Tuesday and
finally arrived in Yerevan on Wednesday, he said.
   Baku radio said there had been injuries in Nakhichevan, as well
as in Kirovabad, but did not say how many.
   It said ``measures are being taken to maintain legality and
safety of citizens'' in Kirovabad and Nakhichevan.
   An editor for the Azerbaijani news agency Azerinform said 100,000
people, mostly students, were in Baku's Lenin Square on Wednesday,
but that their numbers were expected to swell after work.
</TEXT>
