<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hamadi     11-23 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hamadi Says Taped Exchange Comes From Another Hijacking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Confessed TWA hijacker Mohammed
Ali Hamadi interrupted testimony Wednesday to protest that a tape on
which Arabic-speaking voices threaten to kill hostages was from a
different hijacking.
   The taped exchange between Beirut Airport authorities and
hijackers speaking from a seized plane was used as evidence against
the Lebanese Shiite Moslem accused of murder and air piracy in the
June 1985 hijacking.
   ``I think I recognize now that the last part of the tape concerns
another hijacking that had nothing to do with TWA,'' Hamadi told the
court. He did not say what air piracy he believed the tape referred
to.
   Alen Mousa, the Lebanese who translated the taped conversation
for West German authorities, was testifying when Hamadi interrupted
him. Mousa told the court he could not positively identify any of
the voices as Hamadi's, but said the two men spoke Arabic with
Beirut accents.
   On the tape, which was played for the court, the voices were
heard threatening to kill hostages unless the plane was refueled
immediately.
   One of the hijackers was heard telling the control tower he would
blow up the plane if the demand was not met.
   Hamadi's attorneys made a motion for further examination of the
tape.
   During the 17-day hijacking ordeal, U.S. Navy diver Richard
Stethem was killed and 39 Americans were held hostage aboard TWA
Flight 847, seized en route from Athens to Rome and diverted to
Beirut and Algiers.
   Hamadi has admitted he and an accomplice hijacked the plane, but
he denied killing Stethem. His alleged accomplice, Hassan Ezzeddine,
remains at large.
   Earlier Wednesday, a West German police official testified that
Hamadi told West German investigators he was a member of Hezbollah,
a pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem organization believed to be holding
foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   Bernhard Giese, an FBI investigator who also testified Wednesday,
said Hamadi told interrogators he had often worked under the command
of his older brother, Abdul-Hadi Hamadi, the Beirut security chief
for Hezbollah.
   ``(Mohammed Hamadi) admitted being a member of Hezbollah and said
that he had taken part in many battles in Lebanon,'' Giese told the
court.
   Asked by Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger if he had any comment,
Hamadi said the statement he gave to West German interrogators ``was
made under duress.'' Hamadi has denied in court that he was a member
of Hezbollah.
   Giese told the court, however, that Hamadi made the initial
statement freely.
   ``There was no pressure. The interrogation was made in a relaxed
atmosphere,'' the FBI agent said.
   On Tuesday, Houston businessman Allyn Conwell told the court he
was so ``terrorized that I was virtually immobile'' while on board
the plane. He said he feared the captors planned to shoot him and
other Americans who were taken to hiding places in Beirut.
   Four American servicemen were removed from the plane by members
of Hezbollah, while Conwell's group was taken away by Amal, another
Shiite militia that collaborated with the hijackers.
   ``I was under the impression that Amal absolutely did not approve
of the hijacking and the murder of Stethem,'' Conwell said. ``I
think they acted to the best of their ability in a chaotic
situation.''
   Conwell said members of Amal told him that Hamadi and his
accomplice wanted to ``return all the hostages to the plane and blow
it up.''
   He said Amal officials indicated to him that the two hijackers
were from Hezbollah.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt Airport in January 1987 after
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
</TEXT>
