<HEAD>Penn Museum Reopens After Thefts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Pennsylvania Museum, which
closed temporarily last weekend after three thefts including a
19th-century crystal ball worth about $300,000, has reopened.
   The museum, on the Penn campus, reopened Tuesday after officials
took measures to safeguard objects on exhibit.
   Some of the more valuable exhibits were removed from a
``hands-on'' exhibition, and others were placed in Plexiglas cases.
   Besides the crystal ball, a $300 Sri Lankan mask and a statuette
of the Egyptian god of the underworld were stolen. Osiris, the
satutette, was insured for $15,000 but officials said it was worth
probably three times that amount.
