<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Religious     11-23 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Religious,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chief Rabbis Reject Claims They Dividing Jews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's two chief rabbis on Wednesday
criticized U.S. Jewish groups for making a ``big fuss'' over a
proposed change in the legal definition of who is a Jew.
   At a rare joint news conference, the two Orthodox rabbis stressed
they had no desire to cause a division with adherents of the Reform
and Conservative streams of Judaism which predominate in North
America.
   The proposed ``Who is a Jew'' law would accept only Orthodox
conversions in Israel, and North American Jewish delegates who met
with the rabbis and Israeli leaders this week complained the
proposal causes feelings of anguish among Reform and Conservative
Jews.
   But the chief rabbis argued the changes were designed to affect
only Israel, where virtually all Jews are Orthodox, and would
directly touch only a few non-Orthodox converts who wish to
immigrate to Israel each year.
   ``Because of such a marginal problem they shouldn't have made
such a big fuss,'' said Avraham Shapira, chief rabbi of the
Askhenazim, or European Jews. ``Orthodox, Conservative and Reform,
we are one Jewish people.''
   Rabbi Mordechai Eliahu, who represents Sephardim _ those Jews
from Middle Eastern countries _ called for a halt to public
squabbling over the proposed legislation.
   ``I would like to appeal to all these people and say pleas don't
make problems for the Jewish people,'' he said.
   Eliahu attacked Canadian and U.S. Jews who threatened to curtail
political and financial support for Israel if the changes are
adopted.
   ``Those who give money to the land of Israel are doing themselves
a favor, and I think it's shameful for them to say that for this
reason or that reason they will or will not contribute,'' said
Eliahu.
   Israeli officials said they feared passage of the ``Who is a
Jew'' law could cost Israel $100 million a year. Jews in the
diaspora contribute $400 million to $500 million a year.
   The North American delegation met Wednesday with heads of the
ultra-Orthodox Augudat Israel, a religious party that has led the
campaign for the legislative change.
   Rabbi Menachem Porush, an Agudat parliament member, said he
assured the delegates the law would not affect foreign communities,
only Israel.
   But Walter Hess, executive vice president of the United Israel
Appeal in Canada, said ``no progress at all'' was made toward
bridging the gap.
   ``We emphasized ... that from a diaspora point of view it is the
delegitimization of American Jewry,'' he said in an interview on
Israel radio.
   Another ultra-Orthodox political leader, Rabbi Avraham Ravitz of
the small Torah Flag Party, criticized U.S. Jewish leaders for
interfering in Israel's internal affairs.
   ``Every Jewish group that has enough money to spend a weekend in
a hotel calls themselves leaders of American Jewry,'' he told Israel
radio. ``No one voted for this leadership.''
   Also Wednesday, a group of 38 high-ranking reserve officers sent
a letter to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, urging him not to form a
coalition with three ultra-Orthodox religious parties.
   The officers said a government with religious parties would have
a demoralizing effect on soldiers since many ultra-Orthodox students
are exempt from army service.
   ``Their voters don't fulfill their primary defense obligations
but they will give orders to the Israel Defense Forces over how to
fight and with whom to fight,'' said Meir Zorea, a reserve general.
``They have no right to do this.''
   Shamir needs the three ultra-Orthodox parties, which control 13
seats, to form a governing majority in the 120-seat Parliament.
Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc won 40 seats in the Nov. 1 election.
</TEXT>
