<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-US     11-23 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-US,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italy Suspends Vote on U.S. Military Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's Constitutional Court has suspended the
scheduled Dec. 11 vote on a non-binding referendum in Sardinia that
questions the presence of a U.S. military base on that island.
   A second part of the referendum, scheduled to go before the
voters in April, also asks Sardinians if they want the island to be
declared a nuclear-free zone. The court said it would decide by the
end of March whether voting could be held on the second part of the
referendum.
   The court on Tuesday suspended the December vote, ruling it first
must decide whether it is constitutional to allow Sardinian citizens
to vote on issues that are beyond their control.
   The first part of the referendum asks Sardinians if they are
against the presence of foreign military bases not approved by
Parliament that service nuclear-powered vessels or those carrying
nuclear arms.
   The only foreign base that fits the description is the U.S.
facility at La Maddalena in northeastern Sardinia which provides
minor maintenance and supplies to nuclear submarines and other small
craft.
   The Italo-American bilateral agreement which consented to the
construction of the base in 1972 was never ratified by Italy's
Parliament. The agreement as well as information gathered in
radioactivity monitoring and evacuation plans are all classified
information.
   Spokesmen at the U.S. Embassy in Rome refused to comment on
either the security of the base or the referendum.
</TEXT>
