<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BibleSuit     11-23 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bible Suit,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colorado School District, Principal Sued Over `Bible Censorship'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawsuit to put the Bible back on school shelves
and a teacher's desk has been filed against a principal and school
district.
   The lawsuit charges the principal ordered a teacher to remove a
Bible from his desk and ordered it and other religious books removed
from the library. A spokesman for the district said no books had
been removed from shelves.
   The lawsuit was filed Tuesday by Concerned Women of America, a
conservative Washington-based group. Named were Kathleen Madigan,
principal of Berkeley Gardens Elementary School, and the county
school district.
   A lawyer for the plaintiffs claims the case is the nation's first
``Bible censorship'' lawsuit and likely will set a precedent.
   Concerned Women of America, which claims 500,000 members
nationwide, describes itself as ``conservative, pro-life, protecting
family rights and espousing Judeo-Christian values.'' The lawsuit
was filed on behalf of fifth-grade teacher Kenneth Roberts and
parents Marc and Zay Nelson and Debra Jean White.
   Martin Semple, attorney for Adams County School District 50, said
he had no comment because he has not seen the lawsuit, filed in U.S.
District Court in Denver. A spokesman for Superintendent Mike
Massarotti said no books were taken off shelves at Berkeley Gardens.
   The lawsuit claims that after parents complained in September
1987 about religious books in Roberts' classroom, Madigan ordered
the teacher to remove the books and keep a Bible that was on his
desk out of sight during school hours. In a memo, Madigan wrote that
``the law is clear that religion may not be taught in a public
school.''
   Madigan also removed the only copy of the Bible from the school
library, the lawsuit alleges.
   In addition to unspecified damages, the lawsuit seeks a court
order to stop the alleged censorship and allow Roberts to keep his
Bible on his desk.
</TEXT>
