<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-AIDS     11-23 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-AIDS,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Plans Anonymous AIDS Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain announced Wednesday it plans random
anonymous AIDS tests using blood samples collected at the nation's
hospitals and health clinics.
   Health Secretary Kenneth Clarke said the aim was to determine the
spread of the fatal disease, not to identify those individuals
carrying the AIDS virus.
   Starting in a few months, doctors will be able to screen blood
given by any person attending a hospital or clinic for tests, he
said.
   The only details kept about those screened will be sex, age, the
area where they live, and whether the test was done in a hospital,
casualty department or clinic, he said.
   Clarke said the government saw no legal or ethical objections to
testing blood samples ``taken properly in the first place for
another purpose from a patient no longer identifiable.''
   A Health Department spokeswoman who requested anonymity said the
United States ``has been testing in this fashion at selected
hospitals for some time.''
   The Medical Research Council will select within three months the
groups of people and regions of the country in which anonymous
screening will take place. Likely candidates could be emergency
victims, patients undergoing general surgery, pregnant women, and
those attending drug and sexual disease clinics, the Health
Department said.
   The spokeswoman said ``anyone who has any reason to suspect or
fear they were contaminated with the AIDS virus can say (to their
doctor), `Can I have a test?'''
   She said a Health Department committee that examined the
proposals for anonymous screening had consulted civil liberty
groups, homosexual rights groups, medical, professional and legal
bodies, and members of the public.
   The Terence Higgins Trust, which helps AIDS victims, objected
that anonymous screening cannot show how the virus ``has been
transmitted and is therefore useless in the planning of prevention
efforts.''
</TEXT>
