<DOCNO> AP881123-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1616EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Trade     11-23 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Trade,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Changes Won't be Immediate Under Canada-US Trade Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of the Canada-U.S. free trade agreement
foresee dramatic growth as the two countries move toward greater
economic integration, but changes will not be visible immediately.
   ``There won't be anything that will happen on the second of
January,'' Prime Minister Brian Mulroney cautioned after winning the
parliamentary majority he needs to move forward on the agreement.
   It was signed by Mulroney and President Reagan in January and is
designed to have a gradual effect, notably in the reduction of all
remaining tariffs between the two countries over a 10-year period.
   Eighty percent of trade between the neighbors, already each
other's biggest trading partner, currently is tariff free.
   The Jan. 1 deadline the Canadian parliament will try to meet
after it returns Dec. 12 is the date foreseen for the first annual
round of tariff cuts.
   That date could be postponed if enabling legislation cannot be
completed in time in Ottawa. The U.S. Congress already has approved
all measures needed by the United States.
   Some tariffs will be eliminated immediately, others will be
lowered at a rate of 20 percent a year for five years and some at a
rate of 10 percent a year for 10 years.
   Supporters say explaining U.S.-Canadian trade as being 80 percent
tariff free already is misleading, because much potential trade
simply doesn't occur because of barriers.
   They say the agreement stimulates trade to levels previously
unimaginable as businesses on both sides of the border look to an
expanded market.
   The Economic Council of Canada has forecast the national economy
will be 2.5 percent bigger by 1998 than it would without the
agreement.
   Some adjustment will occur as tariff-protected Canadian
industries close or modify production, affecting some jobs.
   Supporters of the agreement describe it as a modest price for the
new jobs that will be created as the economy expands, a net gain of
as many as 250,000 in the first 10 years.
   Mulroney promised Tuesday that top priority for existing
government programs, like retraining, will be covering anyone
unemployed as a result of the trade agreement.
   ``We're seeking to do anything we can to cushion any blows that
come from this commercial agreement,'' he said.
   Joseph D'Cruz, a business professor at the University of Toronto,
said there will be little immediate impact on jobs or trade flows in
the first phase.
   In a telephone interview, he predicted disputes over steel will
be the first visible area as Canadian producers look to the trade
agreement for protection from what has been seen here as U.S.
harassment.
   The trade agreement also dismantles many investment barriers,
eases the flow of some services and establishes a Canada-U.S. Trade
Commission to settle disputes.
   Much remains to be defined in negotiations that will be spread
over the next five to seven years, including key questions about
what constitutes subsidies.
   Impact is expected to be greatest eventually in the automotive
industry, agriculture and energy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881123-0173 </DOCNO>
