<DOCNO> AP881123-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1738EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusSafety     11-23 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Safety,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kentucky Task Force Seeks New Bus Safety Laws in Wake of Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A governor's task force on Wednesday
recommended 17 changes in the state's bus safety standards,
including a new emergency exit, six months after 27 people died in a
church bus crash.
   Also among the Governor's Task Force on Bus Safety
recommendations were a requirement that privately owned buses meet
federal safety standards and that the state set standards for
bidding on surplus school buses.
   ``We must prevent forever the possibility of another tragedy such
as the one that happened in Carrollton,'' said Gov. Wallace
Wilkinson, who appointed the task force. ``I believe that (the
proposed standards) will result in the saving of lives of children.''
   On May 14, a bus, bought by a church as surplus from a school
district, was carrying people home from an outing. It collided with
a pickup truck on a highway, killing 24 children and three adults.
   If the task force recommendations had been in place before the
Carrollton crash, Wilkinson said, ``I think it's fair to say that
... some lives would have been saved.''
   State Transportation Secretary Milo D. Bryant, who chaired the
task force, said the administration wants to ``make sure Kentucky
takes the lead in the nation in school bus safety. ... We owe it to
our children.''
   Most of the task force recommendations will be implemented by the
governor or by the state Transportation Cabinet, officials said.
Some recommendations, such as one requiring bus drivers to receive
more training and meet minimum federal medical requirements for
motor carriers, may require action by the General Assembly,
according to the report.
   A major recommendation of the task force is that an extra
emergency exit, on the left side, be required after Nov. 1, 1990,
for all but the smallest class of buses. The argument for left-side
exits is that a bus in an accident could roll onto its right side,
blocking exit on that side.
   In the Carrollton crash, the front door was blocked by flames
from the punctured fuel tank, leaving only the rear exit. Forty
people escaped.
   Transportation specialists of the state Department of Education
opposed the recommendation, saying a left-side door would weaken a
bus structurally.
   But Bryant was unmoved.
   ``If we can put men on the moon, I think these people can design
a bus that is structurally sound,'' Bryant said.
   Among other recommended changes, the task force also decided to
seek the repositioning of fuel tanks to make them less vulnerable to
puncture, which caused the fire aboard the church bus.
   The task force also recommended asking bus chassis manufacturers
to redesign fuel systems proven to be a fire hazard on
gasoline-powered buses and to ask the National Highway
Transportation Safety Administration and the state Department of
Education to study again the possible use of seat belts or other
passive restraints on school buses.
   Other recommendations included installing ``pop-out'' windows on
buses seating 16 or more passengers, doubling to four the number of
bus evacuation drills for public school students and establishing
new seating-capacity standards to reduce crowding and make emergency
exits more accessible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881123-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1749EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WashingtonRemembered     11-23 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Washington Remembered,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Recall Mayor Washington One Year After His Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold Washington was remembered as a mayor of
vision and strength and a ``liberal in the best sense'' at a
memorial service Wednesday, one year after a massive heart attack
felled the city's first black executive.
   Some 3,100 people attended a tribute to him at a theater in the
downtown Loop, hearing former Democratic presidential contender
Jesse Jackson, writer Studs Terkel, television talk show host Oprah
Winfrey and U.S. Rep. John Conyers talk of their regard for
Washington.
   ``We miss your presence, your strength of mind, your iron will
and your vision,'' Jackson said.
   ``You challenged us to fairness,'' he said. ``You fought for an
ethics ordinance to remove the sleaze from government, to do
justice, to love mercy.''
   Washington, 65, died the day before Thanksgiving 1987, seven
months into his second term. The jovial, articulate mayor slumped
over his City Hall desk just an hour after attending a mid-morning
groundbreaking ceremony for a housing project.
   He was rushed to Northwestern Memorial Hospital, and two hours
later was pronounced dead, leaving the shocked city without its
charismatic and voluble leader.
   The selection of Alderman Eugene Sawyer, a softspoken former
schoolteacher, as acting mayor by the City Council came a week after
Washington's death and followed raucous meetings among sparring
factions of the Council.
   At least four Democratic candidates have expressed intentions to
oust Sawyer in next year's election, which is expected to be decided
by the primary in heavily Democratic Chicago.
   At the service, Pulitzer-prize winning author Terkel paid tribute
to Washington's unifying vision: ``He saw the block as part of a
neighborhood. He saw the neighborhood as part of a city.
   ``He saw the city as part of a country. He saw the country was
part of a world. They were inseparable. And that's what made him a
mayor with the possibility of being the best.
   ``Certainly he was the most literate mayor Chicago ever had,''
added Terkel, who cited Washington's well-known penchant for reading.
   Winfrey noted Washington's easygoing and affable style, as well
as his contributions to social progress and civil rights.
   ``If we truly want to let the world know, and this city know,
that his life meant something to us, we must in our own lives,
through our own action, carry out his doctrine,'' she said.
   Mary Ella Smith, Washington's longtime companion, paid a tearful
tribute to him as a man who, throughout his life, ``was always
chipping and picking away at some form of inequity and injustice,
always trying to help those who did not have sufficient resources to
help themselves.''
   She was joined in her praise by Sawyer and Conyers, D-Mich., a
close friend of Washington who called him ``a liberal in the best
sense. He took his job seriously, as a representative of his
constitutents.''
   Many of those attending the morning service, one of three planned
for the day, were schoolchildren.
   Letha Robinson, 10, a fourth grader at Robert Healy School, said
of Washington: ``He liked the white people and black people, no
matter what color they were. He said, `They're still people.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
