<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FuelSpill     11-23 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fuel Spill,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inspection Never Made As Claimed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The site of a fuel tank that collapsed early
this year, fouling two major rivers with oil and threatening water
supplies to communities in three states, was never inspected as
claimed by a county official, police said.
   Charles E. Kelly, 58, who was chief inspector in the Allegheny
County fire marshal's office, told authorities he did not visit the
tank owned by Ashland Oil Inc. as he reported in a memo dated May
19, 1986, the county's Assistant Police Superintendent Richard
Winters said Tuesday.
   Kelly resigned Friday. He declined comment on Wednesday.
   More than 700,000 gallons of diesel fuel spilled into the
Monongahela River when a dime-size flaw in a steel wall caused the
tank to collapse. The Jan. 2 accident, called one of the country's
biggest inland oil spills, occurred as the 40-year-old tank was
being filled for the first time since being moved from the Cleveland
area.
   Drinking water was cut off to about 23,000 suburban Pittsburgh
residents, and supplies were threatened in riverside communities in
Pennsylvania, Ohio and West Virginia as the oil slick moved through
the lower Monongahela and down the Ohio River.
   Environmental officials tracked the slick for a month as it moved
hundreds of miles down the Ohio River.
   Fire Marshal Martin A. Jacobs, 38, also resigned Friday. Jacobs
admitted that he lied under oath when he said he knew nothing about
the memo, in which Kelly said approval was granted to build the tank.
   Deputy Fire Marshal Edward Babyak, who revealed the memo to
Ashland attorneys during a deposition last month, refused to resign
and was suspended.
   Ashland officials say the memo confirms their claim that they
received verbal approval to erect the tank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
