<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 2000EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--SiameseTwins     11-23 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Siamese Twins,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heart-Sharing Twins Can't Be Separated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors said Wednesday that 10-day-old Siamese
twins who share a heart and liver cannot be separated.
   ``The final concensus of experts at the University of Maryland
Medical System is that the twins cannot be separated,'' hospital
spokeswoman Rochelle Cohen said.
   ``Separation to save one baby would result in the death of both
babies. The family has been informed and understands this sad news.
Given the malformation of the single heart that the twins share,
doctors do not anticipate the twins will live for a very long period
of time,'' she said.
   She said the babies could live days or months.
   The hospital has not identified the parents and would release no
other information except to say that the twins, born Nov. 13, are in
stable condition.
   Siamese twins occur about once every 100,000 births. Siamese
twins were successfully separated at University Hospital in June
1986. Twins from West Germany, who were joined at the head, were
separated at Johns Hopkins Hospital in September 1987.
</TEXT>
