<NOTE>Eds: Note language in 8th graf, ``A pro-government ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign minister on
Wednesday denounced the U.S. government for its ``arrogance'' in
criticizing the treason convictions of four black activists.
   U.S. State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Monday the
South African government was using protracted legal procedings and
imprisonment to neutralize prominent black opponents. He referred to
the convictions last of week of four prominent activists at the
close of a three-year treason trial.
   ``Several of these defendants are highly regarded spokespersons
for peaceful black opposition to the injustices wrought by apartheid
in South Africa,'' Redman said. ``It's inconceivable that their
political activities would have qualified as treason or terrorism in
this country or any other democracy.''
   Foreign Minister Pik Botha, in a statement released Wednesday
evening, said, ``The arrogance and meddlesome interference of the
U.S. government in this matter is rejected as unwarranted and
thoroughly inappropriate.''
   ``South Africa's ambassador in Washington has been instructed to
convey the South African government's strong protest against this
unwarranted interference to the U.S. government at the appropriate
level,'' Botha added.
   Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee said Redman's statement ``was
unfounded interference which bespoke of an uninformed, if not
biased, mind.''
   ``The entire judicial system does not take second p
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   lace to the
U.S. system or any system,'' Coetsee said.
   A pro-government newspaper, The Citizen, said in an editorial
that the United States should ``keep its damned nose out of our
judicial affairs.''
   ``South Africa is not a banana republic with justice manipulated
by the government,'' it said. ``Our courts are totally independent
and even Mr. Redman would have a fair trial if he were here to
answer a contempt of court charge.''
