<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Homeless-Housing     11-23 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless-Housing,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeless Not Being Given Access to Vacant Federal Land, Group Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group suing the government on behalf of the
homeless said Wednesday that federal agencies are refusing to hand
over vacant properties for housing, despite a judge's order to do so.
   The National Coalition for the Homeless said it has identified
federal buildings, ranging from military barracks to office
buildings, on land in 10 states that could be used for sheltering
the homeless.
   U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch ruled on Sept. 30 that the
government cannot sell surplus real estate until it has complied
with a law requiring it to make vacant property available for the
homeless.
   According to the coalition, property in Virginia, Oregon,
Illinois, Oklahoma, California, Minnesota, Arizona, Pennsylvania,
Rhode Island, Massachusetts and the District of Columbia could be
used to give the homeless a place to live.
   ``Winter is upon us, yet in the almost two months since the court
ruled, the administration has taken absolutely no action to make
property available,'' the group said in a prepared statement.
   The group's report provided no estimate of how many homeless
people could be served by handing over this property.
   Arthur Goldberg, an attorney for the government in the case, said
he did not want to comment on anything to do with the lawsuit.
   At a hearing last week, the judge complained that the government
agencies have not moved quickly enough to make the housing available
as winter approaches.
   ``I know brueaucrats,'' Gasch said in a transcript of the hearing
provided by the coalition. ``The thing you've got to do with
bureaucrats is crack the whip and see to it they do the job.''
</TEXT>
