<2ND_LINE>AM-Church Fire,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Church Arson Suspect Offered No-Jail Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of arson in Florida has been
offered a plea bargain without further prison time on a charge of
setting a 1984 fire that nearly destroyed a landmark church, it was
reported Wednesday.
   Philip Joseph Melanson, 30, would receive a suspended sentence if
he followed his Florida lawyer's advice and accepts the agreement,
the Concord Monitor said. It quoted Kelly Sims, the public defender
who represented Melanson in a series of arson cases in Orlando, Fla.
   Melanson, 30, a former Concord resident, was indicted last week
by a Merrimack County grand jury on charges that he set the fire at
St. Paul's Episcopal Church and six others in the city in 1983 and
1984.
   County Attorney Michael Johnson offered Melanson the suspended
sentence as part of an agreement on all seven fires, Sims told the
paper. Sims said Johnson negotiated the agreement through him.
   Sims said he advised Melanson to accept it.
   Johnson would neither confirm nor deny the agreement, saying he
is barred from discussing evidence before trial. He said only that
``extensive discussions'' between his office and Sims ``were
fruitful.''
   Johnson said that when Melanson gets a lawyer in New Hampshire,
any agreement could be challenged or vetoed by a judge.
   A Concord detective questioned Melanson about six weeks ago on a
tip from Florida investigators. Melanson was convicted this summer
of setting three fires in Orlando, and confessed to setting more
than 50 others, according to Florida investigators.
   He was sentenced to nine years in prison in Florida, but Sims
expects him to serve only three years.
</TEXT>
