<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoriegaProsecutor     11-23 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega Prosecutor,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Prosecutor Resigns From U.S. Attorney's Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor who brought drug indictments against
Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and top leaders of the
Medellin drug cartel resigned Wednesday from the U.S. attorney's
office.
   Richard Gregorie, 41, chief assistant to U.S. Attorney Dexter
Lehtinen, said he planned to join a private law firm that
specializes in civil cases.
   ``I have had the opportunity to investigate, indict and prosecute
the most important cases in the United States, and at all times I
have been able to do what was right,'' Gregorie said in his
resignation letter.
   Noriega, as head of the 15,000-member Defense Forces, is widely
considered Panama's de facto ruler. In February he was indicted by a
grand jury in Florida on drug smuggling charges. Noriega has denied
the accusations.
   Gregorie presented the case to the grand jury in February, and
later fought against a proposal to drop the indictment as part of a
political deal to get the general out of Panama.
   He also brought the first major indictment against leaders of the
powerful and violent Medellin Cartel, believed responsible for up to
80 percent of U.S. cocaine imports, although none of the leaders has
been brought to the country for prosecution in that 1984 case.
   Gregorie initially said he would resign effective Dec. 31, but he
was informed Wednesday that a hearing on a dismissal motion in the
Noriega case had been scheduled for Jan. 3, and he told The
Associated Press he would delay his departure until after that date.
   ``This case is very important to me,'' Gregorie said from Boston
where he was visiting friends.
   Gregorie has been with the Miami office for 17 years.
</TEXT>
