<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Flute     11-23 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flute,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Benefactor Replaces Instrument Stolen From Swedish Musician</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A benefactor put the trill back in flutist Helene
Holmberg's life Wednesday, replacing the rare instrument that was
stolen from her three days earlier.
   ``My flute is my life. ... I'm so grateful,'' Miss Holmberg, a
24-year-old musician from Stockholm, said as she held a handcrafted
Yamaha silver flute in one hand and a check for $5,500 to pay for it
in the other.
   Then she gave her thanks with music, playing two Swedish folk
airs to her benefactor, Michel Roux, president of Carillon
Importers, a liquor importing firm in Teaneck, N.J.
   Roux, a Frenchman who has lived in the United States 22 years and
supports various social and cultural philanthropies, heard about the
stolen flute through news reports.
   ``Whoever took the flute didn't take her will or her talent,'' he
told friends of the flutist in the chapel of the Church of Sweden in
Manhattan.
   Miss Holmberg had come to New York last week under a scholarship
from the Juilliard School of Music. Her Muramatso flute was stolen
during a concert Sunday at a Brooklyn church. When the audience
heard, they passed the hat for her and collected $370.
   The flute, which she played for six years, was insured for only
about half its $8,000 cost in Sweden.
   ``I like this new one very much,'' she said. ``But I have to put
my soul in it first, and that takes time.''
</TEXT>
