<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia     11-23 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Ban Mass Gatherings in Kosovo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Wednesday banned all mass
gatherings in Kosovo after five days of huge public demonstrations
against Serbian meddling in the affairs of the restive southern
province.
   In Skopje, about 15,000 Macedonians demonstrated outside the
Greek consulate about alleged discrimination against the Macedonian
minority in neighboring northern Greece.
   The Kosovo protests were inspired by the forced resignations from
the provincial Communist Party Politburo of two members representing
the ethnic Albanian majority, Kacusa Jasari and Azem Vlasi. Serbia's
Communist Party had pressured for the resignations.
   Kosovo, which borders Albania, is a province of the Serbian
republic but has considerable autonomy. Serbia has been seeking
greater control.
   Since the resignations, crowds of up to 100,000 have demonstrated
for the reinstatement of Jasari and Vlasi.
   A statement by the Serbian leadership, carried by Belgrade radio
Wednesday, said the protests were inspired by ethnic Albanian
``nationalists and separatists.'' Ninety percent of Kosovo's
population is ethnic Albanian.
   Rahman Morina, Kosovo's interior minister, said Wednesday that
``extraordinary circumstances have taken place which threaten public
order,'' the official Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported.
   ``All those failing to comply'' with the ban on demonstrations
``will be subject to all legal and other measures,'' Tanjug said
without elaboration.
   No demonstrations were reported Tuesday or early Wednesday from
Pristina, the provincial capital 240 miles south of Belgrade.
   Communist Party leaders in Kosovo have promised to review the
resignations of Jasari and Vlasi at a meeting tentatively scheduled
for this week.
   Observers said protests may resume unless they are reinstated, so
the ban on gatherings might be pre-emptive.
   Slobodan Milosevic, the Serbian party leader, pressed for the
resignations as part of his campaign for greater control of the
province.
   Kosovo won broad autonomy in the 1974 constitution, which
Milosevic wants changed to protect the Serb and Montenegrin
minorities in Kosovo from alleged harassment by the ethnic Albanian
majority.
   The protest in Skopje was a chapter in the decades-long dispute
over territory and population in Macedonia, now divided among
Yugoslavia, Bulgaria and Greece.
   Officials in Greece and Yugoslavia frequently argue over what
Yugoslavia says is a large Macedonian presence in northern Greece.
Wednesday's protest was organized by the student union of the
university in Skopje, capital of Macedonia.
   Yugoslavia's ever-present ethnic problems have become worse since
an economic crisis and inflation, now running at 236 percent
annually, began cutting into living standards. The nation has a
foreign debt of $21 billion.
   Market-oriented reforms have been introduced to restructure the
state-dominated economy.
</TEXT>
