<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1746EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-Contra     11-23 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Ordered To Specify Secrets To Be Raised At Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra case Wednesday
gave Oliver L. North until Dec. 19 to specify any additional
government secrets the former presidential aide would disclose in
his defense at trial.
   U.S. District Gerhard A. Gesell's order applies to testimony
about foreign policy secrets North's lawyers expect to elicit during
courtroom questioning of government officials called as witnesses in
the case.
   It also referred to any documents in North's possession that he
did not obtain from prosecutors during pre-trial discovery. Several
hundred thousand pages of secret material were turned over to North,
and, of that, he served notice he wished to use about 40,000 pages
at trial.
   Gesell ordered that the list ``shall be particularized and
directed only to those documents or other information he considers
relevant and material to his defense.''
   North's notice should be ``accompanied by the underlying
classified documents and by separate written summaries of any other
testimonial information,'' the judge said.
   Gesell ruled that North's lawyers would not have to show the list
to independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh, thereby preventing
prosecutors from getting a preview of defense strategy.
   The order was issued two days after Gesell delivered a pointed
warning from the bench that he would have ``very little control''
over the testimony of current or former officials ``acquainted with
high-security matters.''
   Gesell warned that secret intelligence or diplomatic initiatives
could be divulged at North's trial, which he predicted might get
under way in late January, unless President Reagan intervenes to
prevent the case from going forward.
   Reagan could invoke the Classified Information Procedures Act to
block secret information from being introduced as evidence,
provoking dismissal of some or all of the charges against North.
   In his comments from the bench, the judge appealed to the Reagan
administration to focus on the problems posed by disclosure of such
secrets at a public trial.
   Gesell had warned that he would be forced to give North's lawyers
``wide latitude'' to cross-examine many of these witnesses about
their ``involvement in sensitive events other than events relevant
under the indictment.''
   The former presidential aide and retired Marine lieutenant
colonel is charged with conspiring with former national security
adviser John M. Poindexter and two arms dealers to illegally divert
U.S.-Iran arms-sale profits to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   Gesell has yet to rule on the prosecutor's motion to strike
North's Nov. 14 filing, and bar him from introducing any of the
secret documents into evidence.
   In a motion to bar defense use of any of the 40,000 pages of
material, Walsh accused North of trying to ``provoke a dismissal''
of the case by threatening to disclose ``some of our nation's most
valuable secrets.'' wants to disclose when the case goes to trial.
   In Wednesday's order, Gesell said that after the additional
notice is filed Dec. 19, ``all classified documents and other
classified testimonial information the defense presently reasonably
expects to disclose at trial will have been covered by some form of
notice.''
   Under the Classified Information Procedures Act, the judge must
determine if any of the secret material is relevant to the case and
admissable as evidence.
   If the government is unwilling to allow disclosure of evidence
that Gesell finds is important to North's case, he could dismiss
some of the charges.
</TEXT>
