<HEAD>Soldiers Wound Nine Young Palestinians in General Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot a 5-year-old boy in the
leg and wounded eight Arab teen-agers Wednesday during a general
strike in the occupied territories, hospital spokesmen reported.
   A 13-year-old boy died of a bullet wound in the head received in
a confrontation with soldiers Saturday in the West Bank village of
Beita, near Nablus, the army said.
   At least 315 Palestinians have been killed in the uprising that
began nearly a year ago in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip,
which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in 1967. Eleven Israelis
have beem slain.
   The leftist organization Peace Now urged Israel to negotiate with
the Palestine Liberation Organization. It was time a large national
group had challenged the government's decision to spurn the PLO
declaration of a Palestinian state.
   Residents of the West Bank and Gaza closed stores Wednesday,
blocked roads and flew outlawed Palestinian flags. Underground PLO
leaders called the strike to protest dozens of deportations by
Israel since the uprising began Dec. 8, 1987, among the 1.5 million
Palestinians who live in the occupied lands.
   Palestinians have conducted dozens of general strikes during the
uprising.
   Israeli soldiers shot the 5-year-old boy during an encounter with
young stone-throwers in the West Bank village of Maythaloon, said
officials at Al Ittihad hospital in nearby Nablus.
   An Arab journalists said soldiers began shooting when stones were
thrown after they entered the village to force residents to
obliterate anti-Israeli slogans.
   The army said it was checking reports that eight teen-agers had
been wounded.
   In an ad in the Jerusalem Post, Peace Now group said to the
government: ``Stop blinding the public! An opening for peace has
emerged; we must widen it. Only through negotiations will we know if
the PLO has really adopted the path of peace.''
   Galia Golan, a leader of the group, said: ``The PLO declaration
doesn't say everything we'd like it to, but they seem to be reaching
a watershed and moving in a particular direction we have to move.''
   Last week in Algeria, the Palestine National Council declared a
Palestinian state and adopted a political statement accepting U.N.
Security Council Resolutions 242 and 338, which implicitly recognize
Israel. The council acts as the PLO legislature.
   Israel immediately rejected the move. Officials said it was
``double-talk'' because it did not include explicit recognition.
   Justice Ministry spokeswoman Etty Eshed said Wednesday a decision
is expected within 10 days on whether Rabbi Moshe Levinger will be
charged in the killing of a Palestinian and the wounding of another.
Levinger founded the Gush Emunim movement for settlements in the
occupied territories.
   Ran Cohen, a member of parliament from the left-wing Citizens
Rights Movement, said he had a letter from police saying
investigators recommended Levinger be tried.
   A 42-year-old shopkeeper was killed and another man wounded when
Levinger opened fire after Palestinians threw stones at settlers in
Hebron on Sept. 30, authorities have reported.
</TEXT>
