<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     11-23 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Indicates Most Israelis Want Joint Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 60 percent of Israelis would prefer a
joint government of the rival Likud and Labor parties that excluded
small extremist factions, according to a public opinion survey
published Wednesday.
   The left-leaning Labor Party broke off coalition negotiations
with the right-wing Likud bloc on Tuesday, but leaders of both
parties hinted on Wednesday that a resumption of contacts was
possible.
   The poll published by the Haaretz daily was based on a telephone
survey of 506 Israelis conducted by the private Telskar Institute
over two days this week.
   It indicated nearly 60 percent wanted an exclusive Likud-Labor
government that would change Israel's electoral system and call new
elections, the paper said. It did not give an exact number or a
margin of error for the survey.
   The poll also was carried by the mass-circulation Maariv daily,
which said most supporters of a joint government were left-wing
voters who feared extremist religious and anti-peace policies could
be expected from a right-wing Cabinet.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, the Likud leader, was charged with
forming the next government after his party won 40 seats to Labor's
39 in the Nov. 1 parliamentary elections.
   Aides said Tuesday that Shamir hoped to build a Cabinet by next
week. But negotiations have grown complicated with the seven small
religious and ultra-right-wing factions whose support Shamir needs
to claim a majority in the 120-member parliament.
   Militant parties are vying for control of the Housing Ministry,
which would enable them to build more Jewish settlements in the
occupied territories.
   The religious parties are demanding a ``Who is a Jew'' law that
would accept only conversions to Judaism carried out by Orthodox
rabbis. The proposal angered American Jewish leaders, raising
concern about a possible erosion of support for Israel in the United
States.
   President Chaim Herzog asked Shamir to include Labor in a
broad-based government, but Labor broke off talks after Likud
refused to concede two out of the three key ministries _ defense,
foreign affairs and finance.
   Labor also sought a more clear-cut commitment by Likud to working
for a resumption of Middle East peace talks.
   Many saw Labor's move mainly as a bargaining tactic and signs
emerged Wednesday that leaders of both parties were maneuvering back
to the negotiating table.
   Israel radio quoted Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, a Labor Party
member, as saying his party ``did not speak of severing contacts but
only of halting them.''
   Cabinet Minister Moshe Arens, who is in charge of Likud's
negotiating strategy, said on the radio that the talks could be
renewed. ``If the other side has the good will and the willingness
to invest time and effort I think it is possible,'' he said.
   Industry Minister Ariel Sharon, a leading far-right member of
Likud, was also quoted as saying he hoped contacts with Labor would
be resumed.
   Maariv quoted Shamir as saying he wanted the talks resumed and
was willing to consider relinquishing the Foreign Ministry portfolio
to Labor.
   Israeli newspapers were divided about prospects of a joint
government.
   ``The last word hasn't been said,'' Maariv wrote in an editorial.
``Even opponents can find some logic to a Likud-Labor hook-up, if
both these parties as a government can prevent the disintegration of
unity in our people.''
   Other newspapers said prospects of Labor and Likud getting
together again appeared slim.
</TEXT>
