<NOTE>EDS: Updates thruout with meeting taking place</NOTE>
<HEAD>Jewish Leaders, New Chief Of Staff Meet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu, George Bush's
choice for White House chief of staff, met Wednesday with leaders of
the American Jewish community and sought to reassure them that he
sympathized with their interests.
   About 30 Jewish leaders met for two hours with Sununu, according
to the host, Long Island Realtor Jack Stein.
   ``It was a very positive meeting. It was the beginning of what we
hope will be a process of continuing dialogue to deal with questions
on the Jewish agenda,'' said Stein. ``The governor's point of view
on them was received well and there was a general wishing of success
and a promise of cooperation to him by the members present.''
   He said Sununu was asked about one issue that has caused
controversy _ Sununu's refusal to sign a pro-Israel proclamation in
1986.
   A Jewish group in Manchester, N.H., had asked Sununu to sign a
proclamation condemning a 1975 United Nations resolution equating
Zionism with racism. Sununu was the only governor in the nation to
refuse to sign.
   At Wednesday's meeting, Sununu reiterated that he had refused to
sign the proclamation because he felt it was wrong for a governor to
make pronouncements on foreign policy. And he repeated that he
opposed the U.N. resolution, according to Stein.
   Stein said Sununu also said he was committed to ``the integrity
and seurity of the state of Israel.'' And he assured the Jewish
leaders that the Bush administration will follow the lead of
previous administrations and assign a liaison to the Jewish
community.
   Stein was a special adviser to President Reagan and led the
Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations from
1971 to 1973.
   ``I wanted to assemble a representative group to introduce
Governor Sununu to the leaders of the Jewish community,'' he said.
</TEXT>
