<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey Recall Rdp,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>30,000 Turkeys Recalled, Grocers Inundated With Calls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grocers played ``musical turkeys''
Wednesday throughout the Northeast, giving customers fresh birds in
exchange for spoiled turkeys just in time for Thanksgiving dinner.
   Two of the country's largest turkey processors announced the
recall of 30,000 possibly spoiled turkeys, which set off a flurry of
last-minute telephone calls and trips to supermarkets from turkey
buyers.
   Norbest Inc., of Salt Lake City, recalled 20,000 fresh turkeys
distributed in eight states because some may have contained spoiled
giblets or necks, the Agriculture Department said Wednesday. Norbest
is the nation's fifth largest turkey processing and distributing
company.
   The turkeys were processed for Norbest in Columbia City, Ind.,
and were distributed in Maine, New Hampshire, Vermont,
Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut, Pennsylvania and Indiana,
officials said. No other Norbest products or frozen turkeys are
involved in the recall.
   Meanwhile, Giant Food supermarkets recalled 10,000 Shady Brook
Farms turkeys in the Baltimore and Washington areas for possible
spoilage.
   One truckload, which contained 1,800 turkeys, was shipped
improperly but the supermarket chain decided to recall 10,000
turkeys because they could not be certain where the bad birds were
sent, officials said.
   Bob Walsh, vice president of sales and marketing for Rocco
Enterprises Inc., parent company of the Harrisonburg, Va., turkey
producer, said only turkeys labeled Shady Brook Farms prime young
turkeys that were sold through Giant Food were being recalled.
   Grocers said they were inundated with calls.
   ``We've had phone calls like you would not believe,'' said Paula
Alward, bookkeeper for the IGA Foodliner in East Providence. She
said 10 to 15 fresh birds were brought back to the store.
   Although Norbest Inc. on Tuesday specifically recalled its
``Family Tradition'' fresh whole turkeys from stores, many customers
called with questions about their frozen Norbest turkeys, she said.
   Norbest recalled the fresh turkeys after three complaints from
grocers about spoiled necks and giblets in the birds. Company
spokesman Mike Korologos said Norbest has not received additional
complaints.
   Mike Ferry, manager of a Star Market store in Providence, said
many returned their Norbest turkeys.
   ``We're playing musical turkeys,'' Ferry said.
   The birds in question carry the USDA number of P-2487, which is
the federal number of Gobbler's Retreat Inc., a Columbia City, Ind.,
plant that processes the turkeys under a packaging agreement with
Norbest, Korlogos said.
   Gobbler's Retreat President Ralph Heine said he shipped turkeys
to Norbest and bagged his own under the Gobbler's Retreat label.
Officials said they did not know how the cause of the spoilage.
   Korologos said the suspected lot was about 0.2 percent of
Norbest's total production.
   But Wes Barter, president of Native Foods in Worcester, Mass.,
which distributed 3,000 of the turkeys in New England, said the
problem may change the public's perception of Norbest.
   ``There are people who will feel uncomfortable about serving a
turkey because it is a Norbest turkey,'' he said.
   In Maine, the only distributor of fresh Norbest turkeys, Wetterau
Food Distributors of Portland and Presque Isle, recalled all the
``several thousand'' turkeys in the affected lot, said Peter Kress,
spokesman for the state Agriculture Department.
   The Shady Brook Farms turkeys may have spoiled because they were
shipped from Harrisonburg on a truck that lost its refrigeration,
Walsh said. Rocco Turkeys is the nation's ninth-largest turkey
processor.
   Barry Scher, vice president of public affairs for Giant Food
supermarkets, said the company learned of the problem after several
customers returned their birds because of a bad odor.
   Shady Brook Farms spokesman Rick Chenoweth said checks at other
supermarket chains in the Baltimore-Washington area, New York and
New England have found no problems.
</TEXT>
