<2ND_LINE>AM-Car-Train Wreck, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0704,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car, Train Collide At Railroad Crossing, Killing Five</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf, `Arlynn Nelson ..., to account
for boy's leaving the crash scene.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VALLEY CITY, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 6-year-old boy who survived a
car-train wreck that killed his parents and three of his sisters and
brothers walked three freezing miles in stocking feet to get help,
police said.
   Wayne Nelson was listed in good condition Wednesday at Mercy
Hospital in Valley City, said Deloris Welken, a nursing supervisor
in the hospital's emergency room. He was being treated for frostbite
on his feet.
   Arlynn Nelson, 41, and his wife, Theresa, 29, and children
Michael, 9; Michelle, 15 months, and Kelly, 6 weeks, were killed
Tuesday afternoon when a freight train smashed into the family car
at a fog-shrouded rural crossing five miles west of Valley City,
authorities said.
   Authorities said the train rolled for about a half-mile beyond
the crash site, and train crew members returned to the crossing
after Wayne had left to get help.
   Five-year-old Melinda Jo and 4-year-old Daniel also survived the
crash and remained hospitalized Wednesday. Daniel was also listed in
good condition at Mercy Hospital, while Melinda Jo was listed as
critical in St. Luke's Hospitals-MeritCare in Fargo, 60 miles east
of Valley City, according to hospital spokeswomen.
   No one on the westbound Burlington Northern train was injured,
said the state Highway Patrol.
   Wayne left the scene in search of help and walked three miles
north along the gravel county road to a farm, where he was
eventually discovered and help was summoned, Patrolman Roger Haga
said, at about 6:50 p.m. The temperature was in the mid-20s when the
accident occurred.
   The engineer of the westbound Burlington Northern train blew the
engine's whistle before crossing the intersection, Haga said. But
the area was shrouded in fog, and Arlynn Nelson, who was driving,
apparently did not see or hear the freight, Haga said.
</TEXT>
