<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChappellChallenge 1stLd-Writethru a0708 11-23 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chappell Challenge, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chappell Files Challenge In Supreme Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to update with court enjoining canvassing
commission, James comment; Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Etta Peterson...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Florida Supreme Court on Wednesday
ordered the state to withhold certification of a congressional race
that 10-term U.S. Rep. William Chappell Jr. had lost in a recount to
a political newcomer.
   Chappell was seeking to have the state Elections Canvassing
Commission invalidate nearly 11,000 votes cast in his home district
of Flagler County because they were filed late.
   The court ordered the delay until noon Wednesday to allow time to
consider the request.
   Republican Craig T. James of DeLand had been certified the winner
of the 4th Congressional District race earlier Tuesday. James won by
a recount by 732 votes in results certified by Gov. Bob Martinez and
two Cabinet members.
   The commission declared James the winner after deciding to accept
ballot box results from Flagler County, even though that county's
elections office did not submit its returns within a seven-day
deadline following the Nov. 8 general election.
   Chappell's petition said the canvassing board was barred by law
from accepting Flagler County's results because they were submitted
Nov. 17, two days after the deadline.
   The Florida Department of State, which oversees elections,
planned to fight Chappell's request because imposing the seven-day
deadline would mean disenfranchising the voters of Flagler County.
   ``We believe that the statute should not prohibit the people of
Flagler County having the results of their vote count,'' said Ken
Rouse, general counsel for the department. ``The Legislature did not
intend such a harsh result'' when it enacted the statute in 1951.
   James, who also was named by Chappell's lawsuit, called the
action a travesty.
   ``The votes were legitimate votes,'' James said, adding that he
was not concerned about losing. ``I'm sure the ultimate result will
be he'll get no relief from the Supreme Court.''
   Etta Peterson, supervisor of elections in Flagler County, called
for comment, was not in her office Wednesday afternoon, said Pat
Crook, an office worker.
   Her office had telephoned the results in time, but they were not
received in the mail until later, said Secretary of State Jim Smith,
who sits on the canvassing commission.
   Martinez, Smith and Agriculture Commissioner Doyle Conner, who
were all named in the petition, accepted the Flagler County results
after hearing an opinion from former state Chief Supreme Court
Justice Alan Sundberg, who said Flagler County residents should not
be denied their right to vote.
</TEXT>
