<DOCNO> AP881123-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1927EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Baltics     11-23 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Baltics,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dispute Over Baltic Autonomy Spreads Across Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The argument over Baltic demands for greater
autonomy spread across this vast nation Wednesday, attracting
official condemnation in two republics and a huge public rally of
support in a third.
   Government executive bodies in the Ukraine and Kazakhstan
condemned Estonia's declaration of independence from central
authority. Their action seemed to presage an official Kremlin rebuff.
   Activists in the free-wheeling southern republic of Georgia,
however, said up to 300,000 people gathered outside the legislature
demanding that the members condemn proposed amendments to the
national constitution they claim will strengthen central control.
   ``People demanded they refuse this project or separate from the
Soviet Union,'' Zviad Gamsachurdjia said in a telephone call from
Tbilisi, capital of Georgia. ``People are supporting Estonia,
Estonia's position.''
   Estonia, Lithuania and Latvia, the three Baltic republics, want
greater economic, political and cultural autonomy as part of
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's call for greater local control. But
they say Gorbachev's own constitutional amendments eliminate the
right to secede and strengthen central control rather than lessening
it.
   On Nov. 16, the Estonian legislature approved a ``declaration of
sovereignty'' in all areas except defense and foreign policy, along
with an amendment to the Estonian constitution giving the republic
the right to reject any new Soviet law.
   That posed a major challenge to Gorbachev _ how to continue his
reform program while keeping ethnic restiveness under control in 15
republics considered equal under the constitution.
   Gamsachurdjia said Georgian legislators protested new
constitutional provisions that end the right to secede and allow
Moscow to declare martial law in the republics. He added, however,
that the crowd outside found that inadequate.
   He said hundreds of people were conducting a hunger strike on the
steps of the legislature building.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, said officials in the
Ukraine and Kazakhstan criticized Estonia's amendment.
   It quoted the executive body of the Kazakhstan legislature as
saying the action ``contradicts the norms of the Soviet
constitution, based on the principles of legislative organization
and the unity of the country, and weakens the economic basis of our
multinational government.''
   National Soviet media have said the Estonian declaration incites
ethnic unrest and accused populist People's Front organizations in
the Baltics of intimidating members of their legislatures.
   A commission of the national Supreme Soviet found Estonia's
legislation in violation of the Soviet constitution but there has
been no final word from Moscow on the question.
   Officials in Lithuania and Latvia managed to hold legislative
sessions without allowing a vote on similar proposals advocated by
the People's Fronts.
   Legislators in Armenia were to consider an amendment on the
Estonian model Tuesday, but their session was adjourned abruptly
because of increasing ethnic tensions in the Caucasus region.
Armenia and neighboring Azerbaijan are involved in a territorial
dispute that has caused riots.
   In Riga, Latvia, the People's Front issued a call Wednesday for a
mass protest of the legislature's failure to vote on autonomy the
previous day.
   People's Front spokesman Janis Dinevich said by telephone that
about 25 officials of the organization met for five hours and
scheduled the protest for Saturday.
   ``People are very bitter that almost 1 million signatures went
without notice,'' he said.
   City officials rejected a request for a demonstration in downtown
Riga and suggested two outlying parks, he said, but the People's
Front had appealed to the Council of Ministers.
   He said the group expects about 100,000 people at the
demonstration.
</TEXT>
