<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Sharpeville-Outcry     11-23 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sharpeville-Outcry,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dooming Sharpeville Six Brought World Outcry, National Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Sharpeville Six, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The six blacks saved from execution
Wednesday were convicted of complicity in the 1984 mob murder of a
black town councilor during anti-apartheid riots.
   No direct evidence emerged that the Sharpeville Six, as they
became known, directly contributed to the victim's death.
   Government leaders, churches and human rights groups around the
world had appealed for clemency for the five men and one woman.
   Black leaders warned that the hangings might provoke violence.
The slain councilman was killed during riotings that launched a
two-year outbreak of nationwide unrest over South Africa's system of
racial segregation, and hundreds died before it ended.
   Last March, Supreme Court Justice W.J. Human, who issued the
death sentences three years earlier, granted a four-week stay of
execution for the six two days before they were to be hanged at dawn
at Pretoria Central Prison.
   He said evidence had surfaced that a key prosecution witness had
perjured himself during the trial.
   But efforts to reopen the trial failed and President P.W. Botha,
who commuted the sentences Wednesday, was the last hope for the
condemned six.
   Human had based his decision on a defense application questioning
the reliability of testimony by prosecution witness Joseph Manete.
Human cited a May 11, 1985 statement in which Manete said police
forced him to identify two of the accused as having been at the
scene.
   Human said he was never made aware of that statement and,
therefore, did not allow the defense to cross-examine Manete on that
point.
   ``If Manete's statement had been available I would have allowed
cross-  examination,'' Human said.
   Botha had told black Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu then that
he would not intervene in the case and that only the finding of
significant new evidence could save the six.
   Both the trial court and the appeal court found no evidence that
the Sharpeville Six committed the murder.
   ``If ever there was a case for the state president to exercise
his discretion, and grant clemency, this is it,'' said defense
attorney Prakash Diar Diar in pleading that the lives of the six be
spared.
   The six were convicted in a non-jury trial by white judges under
the doctrine of ``common cause.'' That held that they were
responsible for the Sept. 3, 1984 death of Sharpeville Deputy Mayor
Jacob Dlamini because they were found to be part of a mob of 100
people who stoned and burned him to death at Sharpeville, 40 miles
south of Johannesburg.
   Black activists frequently targeted black township councilors,
considering them collaborators with the minority white-led
government. The Sharpeville riots were sparked by the local
council's decision to raise rents.
   President Reagan, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain,
and President Richard von Weizsaecker of West Germany were among
world leaders who asked Botha to stop the hangings.
   The government's Information Ministry held news conferences in
Pretoria and Cape Town, showing reporters videotapes of similar mob
killings.
   Referring to appeals for clemency, Dave Steward, director of the
Bureau for Information, told reporters in Pretoria earlier in the
year that more than 700 black South Africans were burned to death by
fellow blacks after anti-apartheid violence and protests began in
1984.
   ``No emergency meetings of the United Nations Security Council
have been held regarding the hundreds who have been killed by mob
violence,'' he said then, adding there had been no international
expressions of sympathy for Dlamini.
   The Sharpeville Six are Mojalefa Sefatsa, Reid Mokoena, Oupa
Diniso, Duma Khumalo, Francis Mokgesi and Theresa Ramashamola. Ms.
Ramashamola is the only woman ever sentenced to death in South
Africa for what many considered a politically motivated offense.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
