<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Scandal     11-23 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Scandal,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scandal Shakes Greek Government, With $300 Million Reported Misused</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigator's report published
Wednesday says the chairman of a leading private bank stole or
misused more than $300 million in a widening scandal that has rocked
the government of Premier Andreas Papandreou.
   Spyros Papadatos, temporary commissioner appointed by the
government this month to investigate, reported that chairman George
Koskotas systematically ``siphoned about $135 million from the Bank
of Crete, which he passed through his own account.''
   His report said the 34-year-old Koskotas also used bank money to
make loans without collateral and give gifts to soccer clubs,
athletes, business associates, journalists and friends. It did not
say if any illegalities were involved in the loans and gifts
totaling $200 million.
   The socialist government has been accused of dragging its feet in
opening the investigation, and the ministers of public order and
justice have been forced to resign.
   Magazines and leading newspapers accused Papandreou's son George,
the minister of education, of being involved in financial dealings
with Koskotas and using his bank to illegally transfer money out of
Greece. The reports also named Agamemnon Koutsogiorgas, who serves
as minister to the premier's office, and senior socialist party
officials.
   However, Wednesday's report did not accuse any political leaders
of wrongdoing.
   Koskotas has reportedly said he fled to Rio de Janeiro, Brazil,
fearing for his life. He disappeared from Greece Nov.6 while under
police surveillance.
   Koskotas was suspended as chairman of the Bank of Crete last
month, and a government commissioner was appointed to investigate
the bank's financial dealings. Later, Koskotas was charged with
fraud and embezzlement.
   Greece and Brazil do not have mutual extradition agreements, but
the government said a warrant has been issued through Interpol, the
international police agency, for Koskotas' arrest.
   However, spokesman Paulo Marra of the Brazilian federal police
said his forces were searching for the banker because Greece asked
Brazilian authorities to locate, but not detain him.
   Under Brazilian law, Koskotas could be extradited to Greece only
by a special order of Brazil's Supreme Court.
   The commissioner's report said Koskotas used bank funds to build
up a publishing empire including five magazines and three national
daily papers. Later, he bought a controlling interest in a soccer
club.
   Koskotas gained control of the bank in 1984, two years after he
joined its accounting department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
