<DOCNO> AP881123-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 2122EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Church-Suicide     11-23 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church-Suicide,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Not Liable in Youth's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California Supreme Court dismissed the
state's first ``clergy malpractice'' case Wednesday, ruling that a
church can't be held responsible for the suicide of a man who had
sought counseling.
   Groups representing more than 6,000 churches around the country
had written to the court in support of the church's position.
   The court unanimously threw out a lawsuit brought by the parents
of Kenneth Nally, 24, who shot himself to death in 1979 after years
of counseling at a fundamentalist church and one previous suicide
attempt.
   They were seeking $1 million from the Grace Community Church of
the Valley, contending the pastors who counseled him for several
years knew he was suicidal and should have sent him to a
psychiatrist, and that their method of counseling, which allegedly
stressed sin and guilt, worsened his depression and helped cause his
death.
   In a key portion of the ruling, the court ruled 5-2 that a church
counselor, or other non-professional counselor, has no legal duty to
refer a patient to a psychiatrist or take other steps to prevent
suicide.
   ``Neither the Legislature nor the courts have ever imposed a
legal obligation on persons to take affirmative steps to prevent the
suicide of one who is not under the care of a physician in a
hospital,'' said the opinion by Chief Justice Malcolm Lucas.
   Imposing legal duties on pastoral counselors would be
``impractical, and quite possibly unconstitutional,'' since those
duties ``would necessarily be intertwined with the religious
philosophy of the particular denomination,'' Lucas said.
   Nally, a former honor student and high school baseball star,
received counseling in 1978 and 1979 from several church counselors,
including pastor Richard Thomson.
   Nally took an overdose of antidepressant drugs in 1979 and was
hospitalized, telling two pastors the next day he was sorry he
hadn't killed himself.
   He was released the next week and saw several religious
counselors as well as a psychologist during the next few weeks; the
court said his parents resisted doctors' suggestions that he be
committed to a mental hospital.
   He was found dead in a friend's apartment.
   ``I'm surprised anybody would say they don't have a duty to save
a boy's life once they agree to be a suicide counselor for the
boy,'' said Edward Barker, a lawyer for the parents.
   Barker said he didn't know whether the ruling contained any
federal constitutional issues that could be appealed to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
   The 10,000-member Grace Community Church in the Los Angeles
suburb of Sun Valley is the largest Protestant church in Los Angeles
County, and includes on its staff counselors who advise parishioners
and non-members on spiritual and emotional problems, teach classes
and sell books and tapes on biblical counseling. The counseling is
free.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881123-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 2123EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola     11-23 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Ready to Sign Angolan Accord Next Month</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release 11 p.m. EST Wednesday, Time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa said Wednesday it
is ready for a formal signing of a regional peace accord in early
December, though it is still working out aspects of the U.S-brokered
pact with Cuba and Angola.
   The plan, endorsed by South Africa on Tuesday, calls for
withdrawal of the more than 50,000 Cuban troops in Angola. It also
provides for South Africa to set in motion a process for granting
independence to South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   Cuba and Angola announced acceptance of the proposals last Friday.
   In his brief statement Wednesday, Foreign Minister Roelof Botha
gave no specific date for a signing ceremony, but said it would be
held in Brazzaville, Congo, which served as site of several rounds
of the peace talks.
   Botha said his country was still meeting with Angola and Cuba in
New York to work on ways of verifying the proposed Cuban pullout and
related issues.
   The plan, drafted by negotiators in Geneva last week, calls for a
phased withdrawal of the Cuban troops. They have been supporting
Angola's Marxist government in its war with rebels backed by South
Africa and the United States.
   No reports surfaced that the plan directly addresses the
13-year-old civil war. Washington says it will continue to support
the rebels.
   But sources have said the proposal calls for the Cubans to
withdraw over a 27-month period. The process leading to Namibian
independence would likely begin early next year, leading to
elections in August or September, the sources said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
