<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SewageSpill     11-23 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sewage Spill,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Power Failure Allows 9.5 Million Gallons of Waste to Seep Into
Harbor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 9.5 million gallons of untreated
sewage flowed into New Bedford Harbor when the power failed at a
city sewage treatment plant, officials said Wednesday.
   The sewage spill forced the closing of 500 acres of shellfish
beds by the state Division of Fisheries and Wildlife, officials
said. About 8,000 acres of shellfish beds are now off limits due to
pollution.
   The outage began about 8:30 p.m. Tuesday and lasted 14 hours,
affecting both the facility's main power line and its emergency
generator, said Mayor John K. Bullard.
   ``We had about 4 hours worth of storage capacity, so for about 10
hours we were discharging directly into Buzzards Bay,'' he said.
   The plant, built in 1970, has broken down frequently and ``is one
of the major lemons of the waste water treatment business,'' Bullard
said.
   The mayor said he has signed a consent decree with state and
federal authorities to have a second $200 million plant in place by
1994.
   Bullard said the state's tight finances and the federal
government's withdrawal from funding waste treatment is jeopardizing
completion of the new plant.
</TEXT>
