<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DEACorruption 1stLd-Writethru a0718 11-23 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DEA Corruption, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0718,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DEA Laments Alleged Corruption of Three Agents; Unveils New
Firepower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 11th, `U.S. Attorney ..., to UPDATE with
affidavit unsealed with details on home purchased by former agent
and trips to Europe; picks up 12th graf: `Bonner and ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outgunned and outmanned by international drug
dealers, U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration officials lamented
Wednesday that three of their own may have gone bad, but vowed to
end corruption and continue the war on drugs.
   ``We are not naive. We realized that tragic situations like this
can occur,'' said John Zienter, agent-in-charge of the DEA's office
here.
   It has been an especially rough year for the Los Angeles DEA. In
February, agents Paul Seema, 52, and George Montoya, 34, were shot
to death and agent Jose Martinez, 25, was wounded during an
undercover drug operation in Pasadena. Two of the drug dealers were
killed and a third was wounded.
   On Tuesday, three former Los Angeles DEA agents were charged with
laundering more than $608,000 _ apparently accumulated while dealing
in the narcotics trade, authorities said.
   By Wednesday, Zienter and agents tried to overcome the bad news
of the previous day by focusing attention on their latest weapon in
the drug war, a Colt 9mm submachine gun to help combat drug runners'
automatic weapons.
   Zienter said the new weapons are necessary because of ``the
tremendous danger involved in the narcotics business and enforcing
narcotics laws.''
   Reporters wanted to know what made three law enforcement officers
sworn to fight crime allegedly decide to join forces with the
criminals instead.
   ``It certainly makes good police officers sick,'' Zienter said.
   Former DEA agents John Jackson, 39, of Claremont and Wayne
Countryman, 45, of Walnut were arrested Tuesday and arraigned on a
charge of conspiring to defraud the United States by obstructing the
duties of the Internal Revenue Service.
   The third ex-agent, Darnell Garcia, 41, of Rancho Palos Verdes,
remained at large. Authorities believe he may have fled to Madrid.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Bonner said the three are charged with
conspiracy to launder the cash and transferring the funds to
Switzerland. They are accused of allegedly hiding unreported income
by transferring U.S. currency to Switzerland between 1984 and 1987.
   Internal Revenue Service agent John Anderson said the
investigation ``uncovered evidence that supported the allegation
that the three former DEA agents were involved in money laundering
and narcotics trafficking during and following their employment as
special agents.''
   The affidavit was filed in support of a search of Garcia's Rancho
Palos Verdes home. The affidavit stated Garcia bought a home in 1987
for $580,000, paid for in full. Jackson bought one in 1988 for
$750,000, the affidavit stated.
   The 22-page affidavit unsealed Wednesday included witness
statements saying that two narcotics traffickers who are fugitives
from Detroit frequented an apartment that Garcia rented in Los
Angeles. The affidavit also detailed numerous trips to Europe in
which the former agents allegedly bought cashier's checks made
payable to Swiss banks.
   Bonner and Assistant U.S. Attorney Joyce A. Karlin refused to
disclose any details about the source of the money, but Bonner said
``the corrupting effects of drug trafficking'' was to blame. Zienter
refused to discuss the case.
   Mary McMenimen, spokeswoman for Bonner's office, said the
investigation is continuing to determine if others were involved in
the corruption.
   DEA chief John Lawn in Washington issued a statement saying the
charges ``reveals the integrity'' of the agency's internal policing
mechanisms.
   ``While three former employees have been charged, the focus
should remain on those DEA men and women who risk their lives daily
to enforce the law against anyone who violates the law,'' Lawn said.
   Jackson, who prosecutor Karlin claims has associated with drug
kingpins, was ordered held without bail and Countryman was released
on $120,000 bail late Tuesday.
   If convicted of the conspiracy charge, each defendant would face
a maximum of five years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
</TEXT>
