<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 2229EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolsProbe     11-23 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Schools Probe,0706</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chancellor Suspends Bronx School Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schools Chancellor Richard Green on Wednesday
suspended all eight members of a Bronx school board after disclosure
of an investigation of alleged theft and drug use among its members.
   Bronx District Attorney Paul Gentile said at a Wednesday news
conference that Community Board 9 in the Bronx was ``the focal
point'' of a grand jury probe into the activities of Bronx community
school boards.
   ``It is far more extensive than has been previously reported,''
Gentile said of allegations of board wrongdoing. He refused to give
details of specific allegations raised in published reports.
   Green called the suspension of the members of Community Board 9
an unusual step, but said it was necessary because of the
investigation and the recent arrest of a principal who worked in the
district on drug charges.
   ``I do not by suspending them allege that they are guilty of
anything,'' he said. ``I would hope the due process works in their
behalf.''
   Gentile said investigators from his office, city police and
members of the Board of Education's inspector general's office are
conducting the probe. He said it will cover:
   _ The alleged use and distribution of drugs by school board
members and their subordinates.
   _ The alleged extortion of money under the guise of fund raising
for school board members running for re-election.
   _ Whether principalships, assistant principal jobs and other
posts under the control of the school board are being sold, or if
the jobs are being awarded on a patronage basis.
   _ How school custodians operate after-school programs and if they
have been accepting money to keep schools open illegally or failed
to report alleged drug parties.
   _ The buying and handling of school equipment, specifically
computers, word processors and furniture and whether it ends up in
the schools or in someone's house.
   Green announced the suspensions at a news conference after he met
for two hours with the members of Community Board 9.
   He said their suspensions were indefinite, but that they could
appeal to the central Board of Education and that they probably
would be eligible to be candidates in at the next school board
election in May.
   Suspended board member Carmelo Saez also addressed the news
conference and said the suspensions were unfair because they had not
been accused of wrongdoing. He denied that board members had used
drugs or misappropriated school equipment.
   Green said he has appointed four trustees to oversee the business
of Community Board 9. The trustees are two Bronx lawyers and two
Board of Education employees.
   The Village Voice, in its latest issue released Wednesday,
detailed allegations of drug use by several board members at regular
Friday night gatherings at P.S. 64 over the past two years.
   The New York Times, New York Post, The Daily News and New York
Newsday contained similar charges.
   The published reports included accounts of school equipment
allegedly being sold to support board members' drug habits and
charges that principal's jobs were sold for as much as $10,000.
   The reports also said teachers and district employees were often
pressured into buying fund-raising tickets for board members running
for reelection.
   Curtis Johnson, head of Community School Board 9, was not in the
office Wednesday and could not be reached for comment.
   The city's school system, which has some 900,000 students, has 32
decentralized school districts. The Board of Education sets
curriculum and general policy but the districts are responsible for
day-to-day operations.
   Board members, who are elected to their post and are paid a
modest stipend of about $100 a month, are responsible for appointing
principals, assistant principals and district superintendents.
   District 9 has about 26,000 students in 34 schools in the
predominately black and Hispanic South Bronx.
   Gentile said a grand jury has been investigating the matter for
some time, but ``no indictments are expected any time soon.''
   He said since the arrest of P.S. 53 principal Matthew Barnwell on
cocaine charges Nov. 3, his office has been flooded with calls about
abuses in the system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
