<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Peru-Rebels     11-23 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Rebels,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers, Rebels Clash in Jungle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist guerrillas ambushed two military trucks
in Peru's cocaine-producing jungle territory, killing or wounding at
least 16 soldiers, officials said Wednesday. Police in a nearby city
said the ambush killed 22 soldiers.
   Guerrillas from the Shining Path movement also assassinated a
government official in a port city and blew up two bridges on the
nation's most important railroad, police said. The rail attack cut
links between the mineral-producing Andean highlands and Lima, the
capital.
   The attacks followed an upsurge in guerrilla violence that left
at least 41 other people dead since Saturday, including rebels,
police, troops and civilians.
   A top anti-insurgency official in the government told The
Associated Press 16 soldiers were killed or wounded when rebels
ambushed two truck loaded with troops Tuesday near Aucayacu, 220
miles northeast of Lima.
   But police in Tingo Maria told reporters 22 soldiers were killed.
   The government official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said he had no information about rebel casualties.
   Aucayacu lies in the Upper Huallaga Valley, the heart of Peru's
illicit cocaine trade. The region is under direct military control
under a state of emergency imposed more than a year ago to fight
drug traffickers and the heavily armed guerrillas who safeguard the
drug flow.
   Rebels killed Carlos Soto, deputy administrator of Pisco, by
cutting his throat before dawn Wednesday as he slept in his home
there, police said. Pisco is a fishing port 120 miles south of Lima.
   Soto, a member of the governing center-left Aprista Party,
controlled police forces in the area.
   No one was injured in the bridge attacks, which occurred around
midnight Tuesday.
   The national railroad company Enafer said service was suspended
on freight and passenger trains running between coastal Lima and the
mountain city of Huancayo, 130 miles east, until the bridges could
be repaired next week.
   The Shining Path has been fighting since May 1980 to impose
Marxist rule. Violence has claimed more than 12,000 lives and caused
damage of more than $10 billion, according to government figures.
</TEXT>
