<HEAD>17 Massacred in Church Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen surrounded a church in a
mountain village and opened fire, killing 17 worshippers inside and
injuring nine, the military said Thursday.
   The government news agency said the dead included at least three
children under 9 years and five women.
   Lt. Col. Jose Ayap, a military command spokesman, blamed
communist rebels for the attack late Tuesday on Cebu Island near the
town of Asturias, 340 miles southeast of Manila. He said
investigators were unsure of the motive.
   The government-run Philippines News Agency quoted a survivor,
Feliciano Yongco, as saying villagers were gathered in the church
for evening prayers when armed men surrounded the building and
opened fire.
   Yongco said the attackers also sprayed a nearby home with
automatic gunfire before fleeing into the hills, the agency said.
   The news agency said survivors were to be airlifted later
Thursday to a hospital in Cebu City, 40 miles away.
   Both New People's Army guerrillas and government-backed
anti-communist vigilantes are active on Cebu Island. The communist
rebels have been waging a 19-year insurgency to establish a Marxist
state.
