<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 2247EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SharpevilleSix 3rdLd-Writethru a0749 11-23 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sharpeville Six, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0749,0845</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha Commutes Death Sentences of Sharpeville Six</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs to reflect the execution was stayed, sted
of
commuted. PICKS up 3rd pvs: The Justice Ministry...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha commuted
the death sentences Wednesday of the Sharpeville Six, who were
convicted in a 1984 riot that marked the start of two years of
nationwide unrest.
   The attorney for another man, whose case is similar to the
Sharpeville Six, said the justice minister stayed his client's
execution early Thursday, just hours before he was to hang.
   The Justice Ministry said the six blacks _ five men and a woman _
will serve prison terms ranging from 18 to 25 years. The death
sentences in 1985 caused worldwide protest.
   Botha's announcement came hours after the Appeal Court in
Bloemfontein, the nation's highest tribunal, unanimously rejected a
petition to reopen the trial.
   The Sharpeville Six were convicted of murder in connection with
the September 1984 killing of black town councilor Kuzwayo Dlamini
by a mob in Sharpeville, a township south of Johannesburg.
   No evidence was presented that they contributed physically to his
death. They were convicted under the common purpose doctrine, on
grounds of being active participants in the mob that killed Dlamini
during rent riots.
   Jack Viviers, a spokesman for Botha, refused comment when reached
by The Associated Press and the Justice Ministry gave no reason for
the president's action.
   Botha also commuted the death sentences of four white policemen
and three black men, all of whom had been sentenced to hang for
murder convictions, the Justice Ministry said. They will serve terms
ranging from 15 years to 25 years.
   Prakash Diar, lawyer for the Sharpeville Six, said: ``I think the
state president might have underestimated the international pressure.
   ``Very important heads of state ... have personally intervened on
their behalf and I think that has made a difference,'' Diar said. He
named President Reagan, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain
and Chancellor Helmut Kohl of West Germany among those who
interceded on behalf of the Sharpeville Six.
   ``I am happy for my clients that the state president has sought
to reprieve them, but I am astonished at the number of years they
are going to be spending in prison.''
   Diar said after Wednesday's court ruling that only Botha's
intervention could save his clients. The president turned down a
previous clemency request but said he would consider the matter
again ``as a human being'' once the judicial process was complete.
   Hassie Mokgesi, father of Sharpeville Six defendant Francis
Mokgesi, said, ``They should have decided to let the boys come
home.''
   Anti-apartheid groups in South Africa, international human rights
organizations and numerous foreign governments had urged Botha to
grant clemency to the Sharpeville Six.
   The U.S. Embassy issued a statement saying of Botha: ``By
choosing to commute these death sentences he has acted in the
interests of South Africa as a whole.''
   In London, a spokesman for Britain's Foreign Office praised
Botha's decision to commute the death sentences, saying it was
``news that we welcome very much.''
   The Sharpeville Six are: Mokgesi, 31; Reid Mokoena, 24; Oupa
Moses Diniso, 32; Duma Joshua Khumlao, 28; Reginald Sefatsa, 32; and
Theresa Ramashamola, 27.
   The group, convicted in 1985, had spent 1,076 days on Death Row.
   The riots in Sharpeville and neighboring townships marked the
start of more than two years of nationwide black unrest. Activists
frequently targeted township councilors for attack, saying they were
collaborators with the white-led government and its apartheid
policies of racial segregation.
   Two of the policemen who received clemency Wednesday, Leon de
Villiers and Patrick Goosen, were convicted of fatally shooting a
black youth in the Eastern Cape province after severely beating him.
The attack took place after an all-night drinking bout by the two
men and other members of their unit.
   The other two policemen, Johannesburg officers Jack LaGrange and
Robert van der Merwe, were convicted of carrying out the hired
killings of two suspected drug dealers in the Soweto township
outside Johannesburg.
   Attorney Roshan Dehal said Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee granted
an indefinite stay of execution to his client, Paul Setlaba, who was
scheduled to hang Thursday morning, the independent South Africa
Press Association reported.
   The 23-year-old Setlaba, a black, was convicted of murder with
two younger defendants under the doctrine of common purpose in a
1985 killing during a consumer boycott.
   The Appeal Court on Wednesday rejected a last-minute appeal by
Setlaba.
   The stay came shortly after the U.N. Security Council urged South
Africa to halt the hanging, said United Nations spokesman Francois
Giuliani in New York. He said U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar earlier had made a personal appeal to Botha for clemency for
Setlaba.
   Six other people were scheduled to hang Thursday morning.
   So far this year, 110 people, including three whites, have been
hanged in South Africa.
</TEXT>
