<HEAD>Steinberg Examined by Psychiatrist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A psychiatrist examined accused murderer Joel
Steinberg Wednesday to prepare for a possible switch from an
innocent plea to an insanity defense in the beating death of his
adopted 6-year-old daughter, sources said.
   However, legal restrictions on such pleas make it unlikely that
state Supreme Court Justice Harold Rothwax will allow the switch
this far into the month-old trial.
   Steinberg, a disbarred lawyer, is charged with second-degree
murder in Lisa Steinberg's death. The bruised and battered child was
removed unconscious from Steinberg's apartment on Nov. 2, 1987. She
died three days later.
   He says she fell unconscious after choking on food she had
vomited and that the bruises on her chest and back resulted from his
trying to revive her.
   Steinberg, 47, was seen by ``one of the city's most prominent
forensic psychiatrists'' in a room at the state Supreme Court
building in the borough of Queens, the sources said.
   Steinberg's lawyers, Ira London and Adrian DiLuzio, want the
psychiatrist, whose name was withheld, to try to explain the
defendant's ``flat emotional affect'' after he allegedly beat the
child to death.
   Witnesses, including police officers, paramedics and St.
Vincent's Hospital doctors and nurses have testified that Steinberg
seemed unconcerned and made inappropriate comments while the child
lay bruised and comatose.
   Hedda Nussbaum, Steinberg's longtime live-in companion, told a
hospital psychiatrist that Steinberg acted strangely and made
bizarre comments after the child fell unconscious.
   The law requires that a defendant notify the court within 30 days
of indictment if he intends to put forth a defense of mental disease
or defect.
