<HEAD>France Conducts Nuclear Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France on Thursday conducted its
seventh nuclear test this year on Mururoa Atoll in the South
Pacific, scientists in New Zealand said.
   The explosion measured about 40 kilotons, the equivalent of
setting off 40,000 tons of TNT, said Warwick Smith, superintendent
of the Seismological Observatory.
   He said the blast, monitored in Raratonga, Cook Islands, was the
102nd on Mururoa Atoll since France began underground testing there
in 1975.
   Smith said the explosion was recorded at 7:01 a.m. (4:01 p.m. EST
Wednesday). France on average conducts eight nuclear tests a year.
There already have been two tests this month.
