<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of inmates are going home for Thanksgiving prison
furloughs that are business as usual in a majority of states,
including most that voted for the man who made such programs a
heated issue, President-elect George Bush.
   While some officials concede that such programs can be abused by
inmates, many insist furloughs are an effective way to relieve
prison overcrowding and promote rehabilitation.
   ``The inmates really protect the program,'' said Ed Ligtenberg,
an associate warden in South Dakota, where 18 minimum-security
inmates are going home for Thanksgiving. ``It's good for the inmates
because it gradually reintegrates them to the outside.''
   But, he added: ``It's not a right. ... They have to earn it.''
   Furloughs have ``proven to be productive on a national scale,''
said Tom Powers, the warden of the North Dakota State
Penitentiary,where 15 prisoners are going home for Thanksgiving in
what he calls an ``extremely conservative'' program.
