<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 25,0608</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday, Nov. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>Taxes and Such Are Nothing New</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Year after year, enterprising Americans and other
bright folks around the world rediscover old truths and put them
back to work.
   In business, for example, American companies are learning the
rudimentary truth that survival in a service society demands
service, or to put it another way, that the customer won't come back
unless the business provides.
   The lesson has been known, of course, from the beginning of
economic society, and the proof was everywhere _ in the sound
companies that didn't forget and prospered, and the poor companies
that forgot and went bankrupt.
   Now, in a service society, many companies that allegedly provide
service are learning the hard way that the public expects them to
follow through, not just in their advertising brochures but in
customer satisfaction.
   Manufacturers have been learning a lesson too. Remember quality?
A massive segment of U.S. manufacturing tended to forget that a
deterioration of product quality eventually would show up in the
bottom line.
   Twenty years ago, for example, some of America's biggest
manufacturers, including carmakers, decided that quality was too
costly on high-speed production lines. They sent out imperfect
products, and depended on a secondary industry to repair those
defects. The concept failed.
   Instead of accepting imperfect cars that were sold with repair
guarantees, Americans opted for foreign cars that were made properly
the first time. Detroit recovered, but not before it had permanently
lost much of its market.
   The string of lessons learned, forgotten and relearned goes on
and on.
   In today's credit society, some people may have forgotten that
credit has to be repaid. In social welfare areas, there's a
reawakening of the realization that a person's responsibility for
himself can be assigned to nobody else.
   It took a crisis in Social Security to make people aware that
they must pump more money into the fund if they expected to take it
out later. And some seers claim that 30 years from now it will take
another crisis to remind them.
   In health insurance benefits it is becoming increasingly clear
that the more money provided to workers in corporate and union plans
the higher becomes the cost of medical care, offsetting that route
to painless good health.
   And in politics, people are face to face with their own creation,
a mammoth government they allowed to evolve, allegedly to serve but
which instead is sopping up tax money at a rate beyond their means.
   This latter conflict, which can be matched throughout history, is
once again the big issue in Washington, with a president-elect
promising no new taxes while an intellectual elite insists that
taxes must be raised.
   The latest tax drama has a somewhat different script, new actors
and a fresh presentation _ but it is the same old story: government
cannot provide services expected of it for the revenues offered
without cutting somewhere.
   Right now, an outpouring of papers and statements urging a tax
increase is emerging from all corners of the country, and their
authors are running into a president-elect who has promised to avoid
doing that very thing.
   President Reagan wanted to do that same thing, but he didn't
succeed. Taxes were raised throughout his term. Bit by bit, the tax
reform passed early in his term was completely undone by the end of
his second term.
   If George Bush succeeds...? Well, that indeed might be something
new.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, Nov. 25.</NOTE>
</DOC>
