<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Nov. 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   EPWORTH_BY_THE_SEA, Ga. (AP) _ The United Methodist Council of
Bishops has sent President-elect George Bush assurance of their
prayers and hopes for his ``compassion, courage, strength and wisdom
to lead the people into paths of righteousness and peace.''
   ``You have committed yourself to work for a kinder, gentler
nation,'' the bishops told him. ``Your words bear a message of hope
to a world torn by oppression, poverty and violence...''
   In New York, Morris B. Abram, chairman of the Conference of
Presidents of Major American Jewish Organization, said he has
``great personal confidence'' in Bush. ``I look forward to the Bush
administration continuing the strong alliance and friendship beteen
Washington and Jerusalem.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NANJING, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese bookstore chain recently put
10,000 Bibles on sale in its stores, and sold out within a month.
   Peter MacInnes, manager of Amity Press, set up with aid of the
worldwide United Bible Societies and which now prints Bibles here,
called the sales a ``breakthrough,'' adding:
   ``In the long term, the most efficient avenue for distributing
Bibles in China is not through church agencies, but through
bookstore chains.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, VA. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Baptists soon will have to reduce
foreign missionary appointments unless a sharpening financial pinch
is resolved, says the president of their Foreign Missions Board.
   The Rev. R. Keith Parks says that the squeeze threatens to reach
the point at which the board ``cannot continue to appoint all the
qualified missionary candidates that are ready to go.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II says the worsening shortage
of priests should not push the church into ordaining women or
relaxing its rule requiring priestly celibacy.
   He told a group of Canadian bishops that ``if we are being
brought to our knees, so to speak, by the need for more priests,''
it might be a divine test that will leave the priesthood
``strengthened, purified and renewed.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STONY POINT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The general secretary of the Philippine
Council of Churches says the ecumenical movement is increasingly
under attack in that country by military officers and politicians.
   The Rev. Feliciano V. Carino told a consultation of
representatives of the Philippine council and the U.S. National
Council of Churches:
   ``What has put the ecumenical enterprise in the Philippines and
many churches as well under the firing line of the military and
political powers is the decision to root themselves in the primary
reality of Philippline society'' _ the poor.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BERGEN, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lutheran Church of Norway, at a meeting
of its synod here, said ``the mystery of faith and the meditative
tradition'' need renewed emphasis in modern society.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randall A.Terry, founder of the
``Operation Rescue'' movement to block entrances to abortion clincs,
predicts more than 500,000 arrests in the movement in the next 12
months.
   In a story in the Christian Herald, a non-denominational monthly
published here, he said that the movement wants to increase social
tension and strain about the issue to the point that abortion is
again outlawed.
   About 9,000 people have been arrested in the movement in the last
six months, about l,000 of them in Atlanta.
   Robert K. Skolrood, executive director of the National Legal
Foundation in Virginia Beach, Va., told the magazine that straining
the system would require a half million people being arrested ``on a
continuing basis.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs Nov. 25.</NOTE>
