<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0541</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sharp increases for fall and winter clothing
have put consumer price inflation back in the 5 percent annual range
last month despite the smallest monthly increase in food costs since
February, according to the government.
   The Labor Department reported Tuesday that consumer prices rose
0.4 percent in October, or at an annual rate of 5.1 percent.
   More than half of the gain came from a 1.8 percent boost in
apparel prices and sharp increases in auto insurance and financing
charges.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has issued its final
economic forecast, predicting that the economy will expand at a
robust 3.5 percent annual rate next year.
   Private economists said Tuesday's projection was far too rosy and
would spell big headaches for President-elect George Bush in his
efforts to reduce the federal budget deficit.
   The administration also was optimistic on the outlook for
inflation, and predicted it would ease next year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government started its fiscal year
by posting a $27.4 billion budget deficit in October, the largest
since March but down 10.9 percent from a year earlier, the Treasury
Department reports.
   The $3.4 billion decline from October 1987 was more than
accounted for by a $2.3 billion drop in farm subsidy payments and a
$2.6 billion shrinkage in military pay, which was artificially high
last year, the department said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's biggest airlines are going through
with previously-disclosed plans to boost most of the lowest discount
air fares and eliminate cheap fares booked a few days before a
flight.
   The changes, announced last week, revamped the popular
advance-purchase ``MaxSaver'' fares used by most vacation travelers.
They also dropped the so-called ``junk fares'' available four to
seven days before a flight, which are used mainly by business
travelers.
   The changes went into effect at midnight Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sex harassment complaints by female employees
have been reported over the past year at 90 percent of big
corporations that responded to a survey by Working Woman magazine.
   In addition, the survey released Tuesday found more than a third
of the 160 companies had been sued by victims, a quarter had been
sued repeatedly, and each spent an average of $6.7 million a year in
sex-harassment related costs.
   Among other findings, the survey said two-thirds of complaints
are made against immediate supervisors and upper management and that
most cases of sexual harassment are found to be valid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Friends Service Committee has
filed suit in federal court seeking a religious exemption to new
immigration laws which require employers to fire undocumented aliens.
   Steven G. Cary, chairperson of the board of directors, said
Tuesday that the group, commonly known as Quakers, was acting on
behalf of ``the dispossessed and the undocumented,'' those who have
been driven from their countries by war and economic deprivation.
   The lawsuit seeks to exempt the AFSC as an employer from the
employer sanction requirement of the Immigration Reform and Control
Act of 1986.
</TEXT>
