<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0560</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission has
defended its record on ridding the market of dangerous toys but is
urging parents to consider safety when shopping for their children
this holiday season.
   The commission said Tuesday that its joint effort with the U.S.
Customs Service has resulted in the seizure of 891,000 toys that
failed to meet federal safety guidelines between Oct. 1, 1987 and
Sept. 30, 1988, and 162,668 toys since Oct. 1 of this year.
   But commission officials urged parents to heed the age
recommendations and warning labels on toys.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Ferris, whose dream of making Allegis
Corp. a complete travel company fizzled, has announced a new venture
_ a source book for vacations ranging from dude ranches to beach
resorts.
   The former Allegis chairman is a chief investor and partner in
``The North American Vacation Brochure Directory,'' which unites
some of the travel industry's major leaders, including the Travel
Industry Association of America and Family Vacation Services, a
major supplier of vacation brochures.
   The $4.95 booklet will be available in February, Ferris said
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IBP Corp., the nation's second largest
meatpacker, has agreed to pay a reduced penalty of $975,000 to
settle record total fines assessed against a single employer for job
safety violations.
   The United Food and Commercial Workers union said in a news
release Tuesday that the settlement would be signed today at the
Occupational Safety and Health Administration's offices in the Labor
Department.
   The union, which represents some 4,800 IBP workers at the
company's packinghouses in Dakota City, Neb., and Joslin, Ill.,
called the accord ``historic and sweeping.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ceiling on the size of home mortgages
purchased by secondary mortgage-market agencies likely will rise
from $168,700 this year to $187,600 next year, the government says.
   That could mean cheaper mortgages, by a quarter point or so, for
many homebuyers.
   The changes outlined Tuesday must be approved by the boards of
the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp., known as Freddie Mac, and the
Federal National Mortgage Association, or Fannie Mae.
   The government established both agencies to buy mortgages and
repackage them into securities for sale to investors, in order to
help provide money for loans at competitive interest rates home
buyers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney says his party's
election victory is a ``clear mandate'' for the free trade agreement
with the United States, and he hopes to implement it on schedule
Jan. 1.
   Mulroney said Tuesday that Parliament would be called into
session the week of Dec. 12 to complete necessary legislation.
Action in the U.S. Congress has been completed.
   His Progressive Conservative Party won 170 of the 295 House of
Commons seats in Monday's election.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged higher Tuesday. The Dow Jones average of
30 industrials rose 11.73 points to 2,077.70.
   The dollar continued to fall against all major currencies. Gold
prices rebounded.
   Bond prices fell due to inflation fears sparked by the weaker
dollar and rising oil prices.
   Oil futures prices surged, helping trigger moderate gains in
precious metals futures and lifting silver futures from 20-month
lows.
</TEXT>
