<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SexHarassment-Questions     11-23 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sex Harassment-Questions,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>What Constitutes Sex Harassment?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Sex Harassment Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are examples of questions about what
constitutes sex harassment, contained in a survey of major
corporations reported Tuesday by Working Woman magazine.
   The questions present hypothetical situations and ask corporate
personnel executives to say whether each constitutes sexual
harassment and to rate the severity. Answers are in parentheses:
   _A male supervisor asks a female staff member out on a date.
Although she refuses, he continues to ask her. Is this sexual
harassment? (Yes _ 97 percent; severe _ 23 percent; moderate _ 47
percent; subtle or ambiguous _ 27 percent.)
   _A manager is having an affair with her boss but wants to break
up. He says that she will not get the promotion she's been expecting
if she does so. Is this sexual harassment? (Yes _ 99.5 percent;
severe _ 98 percent; moderate _ 0.5 percent; subtle or ambiguous _ 1
percent.)
   _Two men and a woman enter an elevator. The men make comments
about the woman's anatomy. Is this sexual harassment? (Yes _ 99.5
percent; severe _ 46.5 percent; moderate _ 41 percent; subtle or
ambiguous _ 12 percent.)
   _A group of men paste nude photos from Playboy onto biographies
of new women employees that the company includes in its newsletter.
Is this sexual harassment? (Yes _ 100 percent; severe _ 71 percent;
moderate _ 25 percent; subtle or ambiguous _ 4 percent.)
   _Company administrators show the X-rated movie ``Deep Throat'' at
a company sales meeting after telling employees that they would show
an educational film. Is this sexual harassment? (Yes _ 97 percent;
severe _ 77 percent; moderate _ 10 percent; subtle or ambiguous _ 10
percent.)
</TEXT>
