<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RJRNabisco-Workers Bjt   11-23 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RJR Nabisco-Workers, Bjt,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nabisco Workers Face Uncertainty Of Multibillion-Dollar Bidding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAIR LAWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Antoni Noles wasn't that happy three years
ago when tobacco company R.J. Reynolds Industries Inc. bought
Nabisco Brands Inc., his employer at the factory that makes Animal
Crackers, Oreos and other cookies and crackers.
   ``Smoking and cookie-making don't really mix,'' said Noles, a
batter mixer from Ridgewood with 18 years at the company.
   For Noles, history is repeating itself with the $20 billion-plus
auction of RJR Nabisco Inc., which could result in the sale of
assets such as the cookie plant to pay for debt incurred by the
eventual purchaser.
   ``You don't know where you're going to go from here,'' Noles said.
   Echoing many of the workers interviewed Tuesday morning at the
plant's gates, Ed Nesbihal said he was taking the bidding battle one
day at a time. He said that's what happens ``when you're at the
bottom of the ladder and you got money men at the top.''
   Many at the plant have put in long stints. Nesbihal has spent 15
years, most recently as a grounds maintenance man.
   Nesbihal said employees at Fair Lawn generally were happy, having
weather the buyout by Reynolds, cost cutting that reduced the
1,400-strong workforce at the plant to about 800, and the continuing
threat of layoffs because of modernization.
   ``We enjoy working here. But it's not up to us whether we stay,''
he said.
   It could be up to one of three groups that may have to sell
assets.
   The bidders are senior RJR Nabisco managers backed by Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. and Salomon Inc.; Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.,
backed by Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and Merrill Lynch & Co.; and
First Boston Corp. and Resource Holdings Inc. The bids all exceed
$21 billion.
   Art Scala of Haskill, who works in the plant's maintenance stock
room, said he hoped a new owner would take into account the welfare
of the company and its people, ``not just money.''
   The plant, one of nine Nabisco cookie and cracker factories, was
built in 1959. Less than 20 miles from New York City in affluent
Bergen County, the plant's prominent Nabisco sign looms over a busy
roadway and baking odors fill the air.
   The plant may be one of Nabisco's more secure operations because
it makes some of its best known products: Ritz crackers, Oreo
cookies and Fig Newtons.
   It also is the world's only source of Barnum's Animals crackers,
producing 50 million boxes a year, or 7 million cookies a day, said
Nabisco spokeswoman Caroline Fee at corporate offices in Parsippany.
   Nabisco has about 100 manufacturing facilities worldwide, with
about one-third of them in the United States. About half its 47,000
employees work overseas, Ms. Fee said.
   Noles said money has become a concern of many workers who feel
uncertainty because of the Wall Street bidding war.
   ``Everybody is mostly saving everything they can,'' he said.
Noles said that after the Reynolds purchase in 1985, management told
plant workers that it would be the last change in ownership.
   ``We don't know who to believe,'' he said.
   Not all who stopped outside the plant's gates were troubled by
the financial developments involving Nabisco.
   ``We've been producing,'' said Carl Vetter, a mixer who lives in
Butler. ``We don't see 'em,'' he said, referring to the company's
owners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
