<DOCNO> AP881123-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 0048EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Electronics-Television     11-23 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Electronics-Television,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Says U.S. Participation in High Definition TV Market Critical</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lackadaisical approach to developing
high definition television could have a ripple effect that would
doom several other key U.S. high technology industries, according to
a trade group.
   The technologies are so closely linked that failing to
aggressively pursue the high definition TV market _ which experts
predict will total $40 billion within 20 years _ could devastate the
U.S. share of the personal computer, semiconductor and automated
manufacturing equipment markets, according to an economic impact
study released Tuesday by the American Electronics Association.
   ``HDTV will provide the very lifeblood for existing and future
technologies,'' said Pat Hill Hubbard, vice president of the
industry group. ``Non-participation means a loss of both broad
technological know-how and an expanded potential for skilled
electronics employment.''
   Nations that take the lead in the emerging field will claim
leadership in research and development, design and manufacturing,
she said.
   The Japanese have spent $700 million on high definition
television technology in the last 20 years compared to the ``very
little'' spent by U.S. companies, said AEA spokesman John Hatch.
   The result of the research is a television picture with the
quality of a 35 millimeter photographic slide will be marketed for
between $3,000 and $5,000 by 1991 at the latest, Hatch said.
   ``We feel we have 5 to 10 years to catch up with the Japanese
market penetration because of the high cost...and the inability for
it to be shown on regular TVs,'' said Hatch.
   The Japanese high definition television uses a different
broadcasting standard than the U.S. standard and so will likely be
available initially only on cable, videotape recorders and
satellite, he said.
   Although the start-up costs are high and profits will be low or
non-existent for up to 10 years, the group called for cooperation in
the field by industry, government and academia in order to preserve
U.S. competitiveness.
   ``It's a case of putting up a pretty hefty investment and not
getting anything back for 5 to 10 years,'' said Hatch. ``U.S.
companies are not used to that so it's going to take a different
mindset.''
   Hubbard called the report a ``working document'' that is subject
to refinement. But she said the trends were clear.
   The U.S. share of the personal computer market would drop from 70
percent currently to 35 percent by the year 2010 if U.S. firms
obtain less than 10 percent of the high definition television
market, the report said. To maintain its 70 percent market share,
the U.S. must claim 50 percent of the new television market, the
report said.
   Similarly, the U.S. share of the world's automated manufacturing
equipment market could drop from the current 35 percent to 28
percent unless the United States holds 30 percent of the new
television market.
   And the United States' semiconductor market share would drop from
41 percent to 21 percent by 2010 if the U.S. fails to capture more
than 10 percent of the emerging market.
   The AEA represents 3,500 high technology firms throughout the
country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
