<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Drift Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower in early European trading
today. Gold prices also fell slightly.
   Trading volume was low, with Japanese markets closed for a
national holiday and many American traders expected to head home
early for Thursday's Thanksgiving holiday.
   ``People are scared of the banks coming in,'' said one trader in
Milan, Italy, recalling last week's coordinated intervention by
central banks to prop up the American currency.
   Dollar rates in London at midmorning, compared with late
Tuesday's rates, included: 1.7220 West German marks, down from
1.7230; 1.4475 Swiss francs, down from 1.4545; 5.8840 French francs,
down from 5.9090; 1.9426 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9480; 1,279.50
Italian lire, down from 1,285.00; and 1.2015 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.2002.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8312 compared with $1.8305
late Tuesday.
   The dollar was also quoted in London at 121.55 yen, compared with
121.78 yen in Tokyo at the end of Tuesday's business day.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $418.30 a troy ounce,
down from $419.65 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $417.95.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $418.00, down from $418.90 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.83 to close at a bid $419.87.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.10 a troy ounce,
down slightly from Tuesday's $6.11.
</TEXT>
