<2ND_LINE>PM-Offshore Gambling,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferryboat Gambling Plan Again Afloat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state lawmaker says he wants to give a
whole new meaning to the term ``floating craps game'' by legalizing
ferryboat gambling on Lake Michigan and Lake Superior.
   State Sen. Joseph Andrea said Tuesday he would re-introduce a
measure to allow the gambling. And he said the odds of it passing
are good.
   The Democrat from the Lake Michigan port city of Kenosha said his
proposal would apply as soon as a ferry was 1,000 feet or more away
from Wisconsin's lakeshores.
   There now is only one ferry operation on the lakes. It runs on
Lake Michigan between Ludington, Mich., and Two Rivers, Wis.
   ``Ferryboat gambling would bring in waves of tourists to
Wisconsin,'' Andrea said. ``The additional tourist trade would be a
real boon to local businesses and to the state treasury.''
   In Wisconsin, allowing ferryboat gambling would require a
constitutional amendment, which would have to clear two successive
sessions of the Legislature and a statewide referendum.
   Voters last year approved amendments permitting a state lottery
and pari-mutuel gambling. Those proposals had passed successive
sessions of the Legislature, which begins a new session in January.
   The state lottery began operation in September, but plans for
pari-mutuel betting are still being worked out.
   Andrea lamented that a ferryboat gambling proposal several years
ago sank when a 59-36 vote shipped it to committee, and it never
re-emerged.
</TEXT>
