<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-BritishSteel     11-23 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-British Steel,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Steel To Be Sold For 2.5 Billion Pounds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shares in British Steel PLC will be offered to the
public at 125 pence, or $2.29 each, valuing the state-owned steel
maker at 2.5 billion pounds or the equivalent of $4.6 billion, the
government said Wednesday.
   Closing date for applications for the 2 billion shares being
offered is Dec. 2.
   Dealings in the shares are due to commence simultaneously in
London, New York and Toronto on Dec. 5, the government said in
disclosing details of the previously announced privatization.
   Privatization is a process whereby ownership of a company held by
the government is transferred to the public.
   The share price was at the bottom end of market expectations that
ranged from 125 pence to 140 pence, or $2.56.
   Analysts said the government was likely to set a low price to
ensure a successful sale for the first privatization since the
government's troubled sale of its remaining stake in British
Petroleum PLC, which coincided with the 1987 stock crash.
   The market price of existing BP shares fell below the offering
price of the new shares, killing the incentive for investors to buy
the newly issued stock, which was left in the hands of underwriters.
   ``There has been an excellent response to the share offer
roadshows in the U.K. and around the world,'' said Paul Richards, a
director at the London investment firm Samuel Montagu & Co. Ltd.,
advisers to the government on the sale.
   ``The offer has been fully underwritten and we are confident of a
successful sale.''
   The British Steel sale also precedes some of the biggest and most
complex privatization attempts to date, as the government moves to
sell off Britain's water and electricity industries beginning late
next year.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative government has
sold off billions of pounds worth of state assets since she came
into power in 1979. Her aim in selling off such companies as Jaguar
PLC, British Gas PLC, and British Airways PLC has been to promote
capitalism and share ownership.
   The British Steel shares will be payable in two installments. A
first payment of 60 pence, $1.10, a share will be made on
application and an additional 65 pence, $1.19, a share paid by
September 1989. There is a minimum size application of 400 shares.
   British Steel has forecast pretax profit for the current year
ending April 1989 of at least 550 million pounds, or $1.01 billion,
up 31 percent from last year.
   About 23 percent of the shares will be offered to the British
public and to British Steel employees and pensioners. British
institutional investors will initially be offered 44 percent of the
shares. The remaining 33 percent of the shares are to be offered in
the United States, Canada, Japan and continental Europe.
</TEXT>
