<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Chrysler-Bidwell     11-23 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler-Bidwell,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Sells Out of Spirit and Acclaims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. has received orders
for 60 percent more Dodge Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim cars than the
company will be able to build, a Chrysler executive says.
   Production of the new four-door sedans began a month ago at
Chrysler's Newark, Del., plant and the cars are sold out for the
model year, Chrysler Motors Corp. Chairman Bennett Bidwell said in
an interview Tuesday.
   ``Maybe the last time I was able to say it with some finality was
with minivans. That's kind of a nice feeling,'' said Bidwell, who
was named chairman of Chrysler's car-making arm Nov. 10.
   Chrysler began the recent popularity wave of minivans with the
introduction of the Dodge Caravan and Plymouth Voyager in 1983. More
than half of the vehicles sold in the United States are made by
Chrysler.
   ``Our only problems (with Spirit and Acclaim) today would relate
to production volumes,'' Bidwell said.
   The Delaware plant had been shut down for 16 weeks while the
company completed $205 million in renovations.
   ``On the Dodge Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim we've got fleet orders
on the order of magnitude of 40,000,'' he said. ``We've got dealer
orders over and above that for about 160,000.''
   But Chrysler will be able to build less than 125,000, he said.
   Bidwell also talked about the company's joint venture with
Mitsubishi Motors Corp., incentives and the possibility of Chrysler
going to private ownership or being a takeover target.
   Chrysler and Mitsubishi began producing cars at their
Diamond-Star Motors plant in Normal, Ill., on Sept. 1. Production
will be split, for now, half and half between Plymouth Laser and
Mitsubishi Eclipse.
   Bidwell said that mix may change, depending on dealer demand, and
since Chrysler has a larger dealership network than Mitsubishi's, it
stands to sell more of the cars.
   ``We won't hit any real kind of a stride until May,'' he said.
``We'll be building something on the order of 20,000 Plymouth
Lasers. ...
   Despite the apparent success of the Spirit-Acclaim and the Laser,
Chrysler still faces some rough financial roads, Bidwell said.
   ``I think if we had these two vehicles (from Diamond-Star and the
Newark plants) available in volume production today, we would be
able to hold and perhaps even further improve market share,'' he
said.
   However, with the discontinuation of some of the company's older
models, ``we're in a little bit of a transition over the next four
or five months ... when we're going to have to struggle a little
bit.''
   Chrysler's third-quarter earnings this year fell 54.3 percent
compared with the third quarter of last year. Through the first nine
months of the year, the company's earnings were down 34.4 percent
this year from the same period last year.
   One of the reasons is incentives.
   Chrysler has used the enticements to lure car buyers into
showrooms and to move excess stock from dealership inventory lots.
They took their toll on profits.
   Now, said Bidwell: ``We don't anticipate leading an incentive
parade.''
   Bidwell discounted rumors that the company may go to private
ownership or be in the bull's eye of a takeover target.
   ``Anybody would be crazy to take on that kind of debt load, and
still turn around and face the capital expenditure requirements that
you've got to do to stay in business in this business.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
