<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BlinderProbe     11-23 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Blinder Probe,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds End Search Of Blinder, Robinson; Craps Table, Slot Machine
Seized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents have ended a four-day
search of financial records at Blinder, Robinson & Co., and police
revealed a craps table and slot machine were seized from the penny
stock brokerage firm.
   The company's staff of 150 were allowed to resume normal
operations on Tuesday, and Internal Revenue Service agents at the
end of the day finished examining thousands of documents concerning
16 companies and 53 investors.
   IRS and Securities and Exchange Commission agents entered
Blinder's office Saturday morning on a warrant issued by the U.S.
attorney's office in Denver, and they have refused to comment on the
raid. Blinder executives said the warrant was based on an affidavit
from an IRS agent in Las Vegas, Nev.
   No charges have been filed against Blinder, Robinson, and the
company's name did not appear on the search warrant.
   Police revealed Tuesday that they seized the expensive casino
craps table and nickel slot machine from brokerage owner Meyer
Blinder's 10th floor penthouse office during the weekend raid.
   While Blinder officials describe them as collector's items,
possession of the gambling devices could mean added trouble for the
penny-stock magnate.
   Blinder faces an investigation of a possible misdemeanor
violation of Colorado's gambling laws and deeper scrutiny from the
Nevada Gaming Commission, which is reviewing his license application
for the proposed Cattle Baron casino in Henderson, Nev., authorities
said.
   ``We'll wait and see what transpires with the feds in their
investigation,'' said police Detective Bob Arthur. ``We need to
determine who owns the table and the slot machine.''
   Steven Theys, senior vice president for Blinder, Robinson, said
the seizure showed an overzealousness on the part of federal agents.
   ``Yeah, it's real big-time gambling _ a whole nickel slot
machine,'' he said. ``I don't know what right they have to take that
because it wasn't covered in the search warrant. They took that out
of Mr. Blinder's personal den.''
   Arthur said that while it is not against the law to own a craps
table, possession of a slot machine manufactured after 1950 is
illegal. The machine seized in Blinder's penthouse was made in 1973,
he said.
</TEXT>
