<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher on Reports of Soviet Grain Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened slightly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade on speculation that the United
States and the Soviet Union were preparing to sign a new long-term
grain sales agreement.
   The previous 5-year agreement expired on Sept. 30 and the lack of
a new pact has had a depressing effect on the grain markets,
especially on wheat prices.
   Analysts said today's early rally was prompted by a news
service's report that U.S. officials would travel to Moscow on
Monday to sign a 2-year agreement covering wheat and corn sales to
the Soviets.
   One of the sticking points in the negotiations has been a Soviet
demand that an agreement include wheat subsidies under the
Agriculture Department's Export Enhancement Program, said Ted Mao,
grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Technicalanalysts said the grain markets were due for a rally
after hitting the bottom of a price cycle on Monday.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 2} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.16\ a bushel; corn was \
cent to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.64 a bushel; oats were }
cent to 2 cents higher with December at $2.10 a bushel; soybeans
were 1 cent to 2} cents higher with January at $7.53 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were moderately higher of the brothel and
the days during which a customer could have been exposed.
   Russell Reed of the Nevada Brothel Industry said owners want to
keep their houses as free of sexually transmitted diseases as
possible but fear the notification rule might cause unfounded public
concern.
   Prostitutes in Nevada's three dozen brothels have been tested
weekly for AIDS and other sexually transmitted diseases for about
two years. None has tested positive for the AIDS virus.
