<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru   11-23 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru,0733</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Gyrate On OPEC Indecision</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES with 7 grafs to show prices up; OPEC meeting
postponed; picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``Other contract...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices shot up again today after fluctuating
wildly on Tuesday in response to conflicting reports from Vienna,
where OPEC ministers are trying to negotiate a new production
agreement.
   In the first two hours of trading today, prices fluctuated
between 34 cents and 74 cents higher. At 11 a.m. EST, the January
contract was trading at $14.30 a barrel, up 44 cents, in brisk
trading.
   Prices started drooping on word that the OPEC ministers had
postponed until Thursday a full meeting of the cartel, analysts
said. The ministers have been meeting in small groups since Monday
and were scheduled to convene in full session later today.
   Analysts said the market was remaining optimistic that the OPEC
meeting would produce some type of agreement to limit oil output.
The current excess on world markets have kept prices weak.
   ``The market opened stronger on followthrough volume from
yesterday,'' said Andrew Lebow, senior broker and analyst with
E.D.&F. Man International Futures Inc. ``It's basically optimistic
that OPEC is going to come up with an agreement. However, the
meeting has been postponed so there is a little uneasiness.''
   Analysts said volume on the New York Mercantile Exchange was
heavier than normal in the first hour of trading but had tapered
off. The exchange is scheduled to close earlier than normal today in
advance of the Thanksgiving Day holiday and will be closed on Friday.
   On Tuesday, the January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark grade of U.S. crude, closed 88 cents higher at $13.86 a
barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. The contract had traded
as high as $14.40 a barrel during the day.
   Other contract months also finished sharply higher.
   Futures prices for refined products also soared on Tuesday. The
December contract for unleaded gasoline settled 1.01 cents higher at
45.33 cents a gallon. Contracts for next July and August closed 1.99
cents higher.
   Heating oil for December closed the day up 1.97 cents at 45.44
cents a gallon. Other contract months also rose, with next
September's contract up 2.40 cents.
   The 13-member Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries is
trying to reach an agreement to limit output and raise world crude
prices. But Iran and Iraq have been unable to settle a dispute over
how much Iraq should be allowed to produce, a key hurdle to any
accord.
   Analysts said Iran Oil Minister Gholamreza Aghazadeh's remark
that, ``I think we can reach an agreement'' ignited an early buying
frenzy, as many investors and analysts were talking of a possible
impasse at the Vienna meeting, which continued today.
   ``It just goes to show how volatile this market is that prices
could go up more than $1 on just a little optimism from Iran,'' said
Peter Beutel, an analyst with Elders Futures Inc.
   But in a reversal late in the day, Aghazadeh said he would
``never concede'' to quota parity.
   That remark sent crude prices tumbling more than $1 off their
highs in the final hour of trading, but prices rebounded before the
close.
   ``Virtually all the action particularly these sharp reversals can
be traced to the statements of Iran's oil minister,'' said Bob
Baker, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   OPEC's current production system gives Iran a quota of 2.4
million barrels of oil a day, compared with 1.5 million for Iraq,
with which it fought a bitter 8-year war. But Iraq has ignored its
quota, saying it will not participate until it is given parity with
Iran, which has refused.
   Analysts cite three reasons for Iran's intransigence:
   _Historically, it has been a higher volume producer than Iraq and
wants to maintain its No. 2 position behind Saudi Arabia in the
cartel.
   _Iran claims its internal needs are higher since its population
is triple that of Iraq.
   _It claims it has more oil reserves than Iraq, one of the
criteria used by OPEC to set its quotas.
   Although Iraq is producing more than 2.4 million barrels of oil a
day and has said it will continue, analysts have predicted some kind
of an agreement beyond strict parity is possible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
