<DOCNO> AP881123-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1237EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-PersonalFile-Weill Adv25   11-23 1047</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Personal File-Weill, Adv 25,1080</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday Nov. 25 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dealmaker Sandy Weill Doesn't Forget Where He Came From</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A picture of a simple yellow house in Brooklyn
hangs in the plush Manhattan offices of entrepreneur Sanford I.
Weill, who grew up on the home's second floor.
   The 55-year-old Weill also recalls his struggles to pay the
milkman and the diaper service as a young career man who married
straight out of college.
   Such memories provide the inspiration that propels this Wall
Street dealmaker, who having built and sold one financial empire is
trying to work another miracle.
   Weill says the pending merger of his Commercial Credit Inc. with
Primerica Corp., headed by his old friend Gerald Tsai Jr., is as
much of a challenge as starting out more than 30 years ago.
   ``When I started I was really scraping and when we decided to get
into business, we (he and his wife Joan) put all of our money into
it except $1,000,'' said Weill. ``I think doing something like this
merger gives us the opportunity to do that again.''
   That first business was Carter, Berlind, Potoma & Weill, which
grew steadily through mergers and became what is today the giant
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   It was only the first big success for Weill, whose initial job
out of Cornell University was as a messenger in a brokerage firm. He
moved on to become a ``quote boy'' and later a stockbroker before
going into business himself.
   He sold Shearson to American Express for nearly $1 billion in
stock in 1981. Shortly after that, Weill joined American Express and
became president. There he played a major role in the company's
attempt to turn around its troubled Fireman's Fund, a large property
and liability insurer. He left American Express in 1985.
   He participated in _ but dropped out of _ bidding for E.F. Hutton
Inc., which was eventually purchased by his former firm, Shearson
Lehman.
   In 1986, Weill lost an attempt to acquire BankAmerica Corp. But
later in the year, he joined Baltimore-based Commercial Credit after
reaching an agreement with Control Data Corp. to spin off its
subsidiary in a public stock offering.
   Analysts say the Commercial Credit-Primerica transaction marks
the re-emergence of Weill as a major force in financial services.
Some say Weill is determined to build Commercial Credit into a giant
rivaling American Express, with interests in a wide range of
consumer credit and retail brokerage services.
   Weill says he entered the market now for the fun and challenge of
the turbulent times in the financial industry, which is still trying
to right itself after the shock of last year's stock market crash.
   ``I think I'm going to have a lot of fun,'' Weill said. ``I like
to keep busy and work with bright people,'' he said, adding that
``the best time to do something, not necessarily for the immediate
results, is when there's some sort of turmoil in the marketplace.''
   Weill also scoffs at reports that he left American Express
because he was not selected chief executive officer.
   ``The person was younger than I am and had different talents and
different abilities,'' Weill said. We just had a different
philosophy about management style and we agreed to disagree.''
   He says he doesn't look at the incident as a failure.
   ``I thought it was great to be president of American Express. ...
I grew up in Brooklyn in this house,'' he said pointing to the
photograph of his modest boyhood home.
   ``It's absolutely true that I was disappointed or I wouldn't have
left American Express. But it doesn't say any place that life has to
be a bowl of cherries,'' he said.
   Those who know Weill are watching his latest moves with interest.
   ``Sandy Weill has had an extremely successful career and he seems
to be capping it off with a very interesting and exciting
transaction,'' said Jeffrey Lane, president of Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc.
   ``Normally one judges the ability to succeed based on past
performance and given Sandy's past, one should assume the odds are
in his favor,'' Lane said. ``The task is certainly daunting ...
(and) his record is outstanding.''
   Anthony Pearce-Batten, securities analyst with Legg Mason Wood
Walker, Inc. in Baltimore, describes Weill as fairly conservative
``who doesn't over pay for anything,'' a detail man and one who
keeps an eye on the big picture in the industry.
   Looking at Weill's decision to leave American Express and his
failure to buy BankAmerica and E.F. Hutton, Pearce-Batten said:
``They speak well of the man. He is not driven to buy something at
any price. And, clearly he is not someone who spends a lot of time
in the headlines.
   ``I get the sense that price comes before pride.''
   Commercial Credit agreed to acquire Primerica in a cash-and-stock
deal valued at $1.65 billion. Along with Primerica, comes the
struggling brokerage firm Smith, Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   The revival of Smith Barney, a mid-sized investment bank
specializing in retail brokerage and municipal finance, is
considered key to the future success of Commercial Credit. Frank
Zarb, a prominent Wall Street figure who served as energy czar under
President Gerald Ford, was recently named to head the brokerage.
   Pearce-Batten says some on Wall Street are skeptical about
Weill's chances for success, noting that Commercial Credit's stock
has weakened sharply since the deal was announced.
   ``The simple way to put it _ and I don't suggest this is the way
I think _ is that if Tsai couldn't run it, why should we believe
Weill can,'' Pearce-Batten said. ``I think there are a lot of
reasons, but that's some of the conventional wisdom.
   ``And the management has an unusually strong incentive to get the
stock price up because they have a stock option package. With the
stock going down, their potential wealth is materially affected and
while that's distressing, it's nice to know they're in the same
boat.''
   Weill says the merger is probably his biggest challenge ever.
   ``I wouldn't say it scares me as much as when I was beginning,''
he mused. ``If I made a mistake then, it would have been the end of
the career.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday Nov. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
