<1ST_LINE>u f PM-PrimeComputer     11-23 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prime Computer,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Computer Files Counterclaim Against Group Making Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. has filed a counterclaim in
U.S. District Court seeking a ``fair disclosure'' of two companies'
$20-a-share tender offer for the computer company's stock.
   MAI Basic Four Inc. and Choice Corp. announced their offer last
Tuesday for Prime, based in Natick, Mass.
   In the counterclaim filed Tuesday, Prime alleges that MAI and
Choice have ties to investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and
that some principal owners of MAI were investigated by the Security
and Exchange Commission for allegedly overstating a former company's
income.
   Prime issued a statement urging its shareholders to reserve
action until the company's board of directors announces its
recommendation on the offer. The recommendation is to come no later
than Nov. 29, the statement said.
   Earlier this fall, Prime announced a so-called ``poison pill''
defense against takeovers. The defense gives each shareholder the
right to purchase an additional share of common stock in the event
of a hostile takeover.
   MAI has filed a lawsuit in Delaware Chancery Court seeking to
block Prime's shareholder rights plan.
   Prime said Tuesday it would delay the issuance of certificates
for additional common stock purchase rights until Dec. 13.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
