<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OPEC 3rdLd-Writethru   11-23 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OPEC, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0729</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Deliberations Spark Oil Market Price Gyrations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 new grafs with OPEC meeting delayed until
Thursday; picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``But after...; SUBS 7th graf pvs
to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC announced today it has postponed
until Thursday its anxiously awaited meeting while ministers
continue secretive negotiations aimed at reaching a new production
accord.
   Petroleum prices, which had fluctuated wildly in the previous
session on conflicting reports about the progress of the talks,
turned in another erratic performance before settling slightly
higher. U.S. markets closed early for the Thanksgiving Day holiday
and were not scheduled to reopen until Monday.
   OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman, Nigeria's oil minister, said the
cartel ``is working towards'' an agreement in small bilateral and
multilateral sessions.
   He also indicated that a dispute between Iran and Iraq, one of
the main stumbling blocks to an agreement, had yet to be resolved.
   On Tuesday, the price of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, rocketed up $1.42 a barrel from the previous
day's close Tuesday after Iran's oil minister sounded an optimistic
note about prospects for a new agreement at OPEC's ongoing winter
conference. Talks resume today.
   But after hitting a high of $14.40 a barrel for the near-month
contract on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the price tumbled once
the minister, Gholamreza Aghazadeh, left a meeting with other OPEC
officials empty-handed.
   ``There has been no progress,'' said a senior member of an OPEC
delegation, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   After falling more than $1 off the day's high, West Texas
Intermediate rebounded to finish at $13.86 a barrel, up 88 cents
from Monday's close.
   In early trading today, prices were up more than 40 cents, with
the near-term contract trading at $14.32 a barrel, up 46 cents.
   Earlier, OPEC oil ministers had said they would delay for several
hours today's formal talks in an apparent effort to give them more
time to try to work out a new production accord.
   Saudi Arabian Oil Minister Hisham Nazer told reporters the formal
session of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would
resume in early evening Vienna time. The meeting had been
tentatively scheduled for an earlier start.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries is attempting
to curtail its overproduction and lift weak crude prices. The talks
have been stalled by a dispute between Iran and Iraq over how much
oil each will be allowed to produce under any new pact.
   Iraq has insisted on having the same, higher quota as Iran, but
Iran has refused.
   Aghazadeh repeated his opposition to such a deal Tuesday after a
nearly hour-long meeting with ministers from Venezuela, Nigeria,
Algeria and Indonesia, and said he would ``never concede to parity.''
   Aghazadeh said no single proposal was on the table, but he
intended to remain at the talks.
   Oil futures had soared around midday after Aghazadeh, in response
to reporters' questions, said, ``I think we can reach an agreement.''
   OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman, who is Nigeria's oil minister,
said ``We will not end without an agreement.''
   Aghazadeh wants Iran's share of total OPEC output maintained at
the current level of 13.5 percent, the second-largest after Saudi
Arabia's 25.6 percent, and said that demand was firm.
   Iraq's share in the current production accord, worked out in
1986, is third largest at 11.7 percent.
   The new production agreement would set a ceiling on 1989
production.
   The current accord caps OPEC's total output at about 15 million
barrels a day. A senior member of one delegation, who demanded
anonymity, said a consensus appeared to be building for a new
ceiling of about 18.5 million barrels a day.
   Analysts estimate OPEC production soared to about 21 million
barrels in October, reflecting the production that has caused a
worldwide glut and depressed prices.
   Most countries, analysts say, have been exceeding their quotas in
recent months.
   Under the current accord, Iran has a quota of 2.4 million barrels
a day. Iraq was given a ceiling of 1.5 million, which it has refused
to accept.
   OPEC members are Saudi Arabia, Iran, Iraq, United Arab Emirates,
Venezuela, Ecuador, Kuwait, Libya, Gabon, Indonesia, Algeria,
Nigeria and Qatar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
