<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later trading, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished higher Wednesday in active
trading on the London Stock Exchange, boosted by a takeover bid and
speculation that other offers would emerge.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index settled 15.8
points, or 0.9 percent, higher at 1,837.1, near the day's best level
of 1,838.5. The index hit a session low of 1,830.3 soon after the
opening at 9 a.m. local time.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 10.1 points at 1,497.4
at the close.
   Volume totaled 581.8 million shares, up from 486.4 million shares
Tuesday.
   The market was pushed up by news that shares in state-owned
British Steel will be offered to the public at 125 pence, or around
$2.29, each, suggesting that the government pegged the price low to
ensure a successful flotation. Market expectations had ranged from
125 pence to 140 pence, or $2.56.
   Shares in retailer Storehouse PLC rose 13 pence to 213 pence on
heavy volume, fueling speculation that a takeover or reorganization
of the company was imminent.
   The Financial Times 500-share index rose 7.05 points to 1,042.73
at the close.
</TEXT>
