<1ST_LINE>u f BC-AutoSales 1stLd-Writethru f0117 11-23 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Auto Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0117,0336</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: REWRITES throughout to CORRECT year-earlier figures and
percentages; AMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks by the
Big Three automakers rose 2.5 percent in mid-November compared with
the same time last year, makers reported Wednesday.
   The automakers said they sold 245,097 domestically made vehicles
during the Nov. 11-20 period this year compared with 268,843
vehicles during the same period last year.
   The comparison is made on the basis of vehicles sold per selling
day. There were eight sales days during the period this year and
nine last year.
   For the year, General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler
Corp. have sold 7.2 percent more cars and light trucks in 1988 than
in 1987. The companies said they sold 9,834,544 vehicles during the
Jan. 1-Nov. 20 period this year compared with 9,174,729 cars and
light trucks sold during the same time last year.
   Truck sales by the Big Three in mid-November showed a 3.2 percent
gain in 1988 over 1987, and car sales rose 2.1 percent during the
period this year compared with last year.
   After a lull during October last year, automakers began returning
incentives to car deals in November, helping push up the year-ago
sales figures.
   Chrysler and Ford showed declines in mid-November car sales while
GM was the only of the Big Three to show an increase in car sales
during the period.
   The largest drop in mid-November car sales came at Chrysler. The
No. 3 automaker sold 22,933 cars during the period this year, down
2.6 percent from the 26,484 cars it sold during the same time last
year.
   Ford's mid-November car sales fell 1.9 percent, going to 47,450
for the period this year compared with 54,442 last year.
   GM reported a 6.4 percent rise in car sales _ to 76,291 during
mid-November this year from 80,628 cars sold during the same period
last year.
</TEXT>
