<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Markets Rise on Talk of Soviet Grain Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mostly
higher Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade on reports that
announcement of a new long-term U.S.-Soviet grain deal was imminent.
   One financial news service reported that U.S. officials would fly
to Moscow to sign a 2-year pact on Monday. The agreement was rumored
in the grain markets to be an extension of the 5-year contract that
expired on Sept. 30, guaranteeing Soviet purchases of 9 million
metric tons of U.S. grain each year.
   A new agreement has been widely expected but speculation about
the timing of the announcement has increased the volatility of the
grain markets in the past six weeks, analysts said.
   But with most forward-looking market players already fairly well
convinced that an agreement was at hand, Wednesday's price movement
tended to reflect disappointment over the lack of other large-scale
grain sales on the horizon.
   As for the timing of an announcement about a Soviet grain deal,
``It makes no difference if it's Friday, Monday, Wednesday _ it's
just around the corner,'' said Katharina Zimmer, grain market
analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc.
   At the close of trading, wheat was 2{ cents lower to 4} cents
higher with the contract for delivery in December at $4.17} a
bushel; corn was } cent lower to { cent higher with December at
$2.63\ a bushel; oats were } cent to 2} cents higher with December
at $2.11} a bushel; soybeans were \ cent lower to 5\ cents higher
with January at $7.56 a bushel.
</TEXT>
