<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rise $1.07 Billion to Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 460 money market mutual
funds rose $1.07 billion in the latest week to a record $280.40
billion, the Investment Company Institute said Wednesday.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday followed a
revised $4.64 billion increase in the funds' assets the previous
week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund trade group.
   The previous high for the funds' assets was $280.02 billion in
the week ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 229 general purpose funds rose $660.5 million to $89.90
billion, assets of 100 broker-dealer funds increased $906.9 million
to $118.23 billion, and assets of 131 institutional funds fell
$501.5 million to $72.28 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 7.68 percent from 7.60 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 7.60 percent from 7.57 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 37
days, unchanged from a week earlier, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.10 percent as of Wednesday from 6.08 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, stood at 5.12 percent, unchanged for the third week.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 7.93
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 7.88 the
previous week. Yields were 8.21 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.17
percent; 8.39 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.35 percent; and 8.60
percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.55 percent.
</TEXT>
