<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-23 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Weaker, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed lower against all key foreign
currencies Wednesday in thin pre-holiday trading.
   Gold prices were mostly higher. Republic National Bank quoted
bullion at $419 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up $1 from late
Tuesday.
   Currency dealers said reports of dollar-buying by the Federal
Reserve on Wednesday and fears of further central-bank intervention
prevented the currency from falling even further.
   But they said the markets remained bearish toward the dollar,
with most money traders preoccupied with how President-elect George
Bush will deal with the huge U.S. trade and federal budget deficits.
If left unchecked, traders fear, both gaps could hurt the economy.
   ``Until we hear something specific, we're going to see a further
decline in the dollar,'' said Earl I. Johnson, a trader with Harris
Trust & Co. in Chicago.
   Johnson said Wednesday's session was very quiet as many traders
decided to get a jump on the Thanksgiving Day holiday Thursday.
   The Tokyo markets were closed for a national holiday Wednesday.
But in London, the dollar traded at 121.30 Japanese yen, down from
121.78 yen at Tuesday's Tokyo close. Later, in New York, the dollar
stood at 121.175 yen, down from 121.315 yen Tuesday.
   In London, the British pound, which has gained more than 10 cents
against the dollar in the past six weeks, cost $1.8355 late
Wednesday, more expensive for buyers than Tuesday's $1.8305.
Sterling fetched $1.8360 in New York, up from $1.83375 Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday,
included: 1.71775 West German marks, down from 1.71855; 1.44155
Swiss francs, down from 1.44575; 1.19875 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2008; 5.87125 French francs, down from 5.8765; and 1,276.375
Italian lire, down from 1,277.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Tuesday: 1.7155 West
German marks, down from 1.7230; 1.4415 Swiss francs, down from
1.4545; 5.8685 French francs, down from 5.9090; 1.9365 Dutch
guilders, down from 1.9480; 1,276.50 Italian lire, down from
1,285.00; and 1.1982 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2002.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery
rose to $420 a troy ounce from $417.70 late Tuesday.
   The late bid price in London was $419.25 a troy ounce, down from
$419.65 Tuesday, and in Zurich, $419.30, up from $418.90.
   Earlier, gold closed in Hong Kong at $419.87 an ounce, up from
$418.04.
   Silver was slightly more expensive. On the New York Comex, silver
bullion rose to $6.083 a troy ounce from $6.061 on Tuesday. It rose
in London at a late bid of $6.12 an ounce, up from $6.11 late
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
