<HEAD>OPEC Postpones Resumption of Talks for a Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: M'Pouho Epigat in 13th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC oil ministers canceled a formal
session of their winter meeting Wednesday as they grappled behind
the scenes again in an attempt to break a deadlock between Iran and
Iraq over production quotas.
   Petroleum markets remained cautiously optimistic about the
chances for the cartel reaching an agreement to limit its output,
however, as prices rose for a second day although prices again swung
wildly.
   The 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
recessed its formal talks after a brief session Monday, opting
instead for small, private meetings. The full plenary session was
rescheduled for Thursday.
   ``We're working towards (an agreement),'' said OPEC President
Rilwanu Lukman, who is Nigeria's oil minister.
   He said the ministers were still trying to resolve the dispute
between Iran and Iraq that has stalled an overall agreement. Iraq,
which fought Iran in an 8-year war that ended in August, has been
seeking a production quota equal to Iran's, but its former foe has
adamantly opposed parity.
   Lukman met for lunch with Oil Ministers Hisham Nazer of Saudi
Arabia, Issam Abdul Raheem al-Chalabi of Iraq and Ginandjar
Kartasasmita of Indonesia.
   Afterward, al-Chalabi quipped, ``We're always near an agreement,
but how near I cannot tell.''
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark grade of U.S. crude, ended the day at $13.97 a barrel, up
11 cents after trading as much as 74 cents above Tuesday's close.
The price had soared more than $1.40 on Tuesday before finishing up
88 cents.
   Oil brokers said trading was relatively light Wednesday in
advance of a four-day Thanksgiving Day holiday.
   The oil ministers are trying to fashion a new production
agreement that would reduce the world oil glut and help raise crude
prices.
   ``There is an arrangement in (the) works but I don't know when
the work is going to be completed,'' said Mana Saeed Otaiba,
petroleum minister for the United Arab Emirates during a stroll in
the chilly Vienna weather.
   ``I think we have to finish before the end of the week. There's
no reason to stay longer,'' he said.
   In addition to settling the dispute between Iran and Iraq, the
ministers also are trying to decide how much oil the cartel as a
whole should produce to keep prices at a profitable level.
   Although several OPEC members have stepped up their production,
oil revenue has declined because of the slump in prices, which have
been running about 25 percent below OPEC's goal of $18 a barrel.
   Julien M'Pouho Epigat, Gabon's minister of hydrocarbons, said
OPEC members were focusing on two possible ceilings for total output
_ 18.5 million barrels a day and 19 million barrels.
   M'Pouho Epigat said an accord that held production to 18.5
million barrels would result in prices ranging between $15 and $18 a
barrel.
   Otaiba also said that a cap of 18.5 million barrels a day for
total production ``is what they are talking about.''
   But, Lukman, when asked about such a ceiling, said, ``Sounds
good, but (it's) not necessarily the right one (number).''
   The new production accord would replace a 2-year-old agreement
that set a ceiling of 15 million a barrels a day for 12 of OPEC's
members. Iraq was not included because it refused to abide by a
quota that was less than Iran's.
   Despite that agreement, OPEC's members are estimated to be
producing more than 20 million barrels a day.
   Iraq argues it needs a quota as big as Iran's because it needs
revenue to rebuild an economy shattered by their long war.
   Iranian Oil Minister Gholamreza Aghazadeh has repeatedy told
reporters he would never agree to parity with Iraq.
   Aghazadeh offered to allow Iraq ``export parity,'' which would
give the two countries the same total for overseas sales. He said
the more populous Iran should retain a bigger overall quota because
of its higher internal demand for oil.
   Aghazadeh said Iran's share of total OPEC output be maintained at
the current level of 13.5 percent, second after Saudi Arabia's 25.6
percent. Iraq's share is third at 11.7 percent.
</TEXT>
