<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PrimeComputer 1stLd-Writethru f0188 11-23 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prime Computer, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0188,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LeBow Presses Effort to Acquire Prime, Target Sues to Block Him</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7 and 9 to UPDATE with closing stock prices and no
comment from Prime officials</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Bennett LeBow intensified efforts
Wednesday to buy Prime Computer Inc., releasing a letter aimed at
assuring its management he has no hidden agenda in the $970 million
hostile takeover attempt by his much smaller computer business, MAI
Basic Four Inc.
   ``Contrary to speculation from certain quarters about MAI Basic
Four's intentions, the only motive for MAI Basic Four's tender offer
for Prime shares is to acquire Prime,'' LeBow wrote to Prime
president Anthony Craig.
   ``The combination of MAI Basic Four and Prime ... will produce a
powerful competitor in the rapidly maturing computer industry,''
LeBow wrote.
   ``We firmly believe the combined companies will be far more
successful than either of us can be alone, and a prompt consummation
of our acquisition will best serve the interests of our respective
stockholders, employees, customers and suppliers,'' he wrote.
   Natick-based Prime is second to International Business Machines
Corp. in the field of computer-aided design and manufacturing
systems. In February it acquired Computervision Inc. for $435
million.
   MAI Basic, a small concern based in Tustin, Calif., owns 4.1
percent of Prime's 48.5 million shares outstanding and is offering
$20 a share for the rest in a tender offer to shareholders. The
offer, valued at $970 million, was made Nov. 15.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, Prime closed unchanged
Wednesday at $16 a share. MAI Basic fell 62{ cents a share to $8.25.
   There has been some speculation that LeBow undertook the takeover
attempt to induce Prime to buy his company instead, in what is
commonly called a Pac Man defense of acquiring the suitor.
   Prime officials had no comment on the letter, said spokesman
Richard Eckels. However, their intent to resist LeBow was
demonstrated forcefully Tuesday when the company sued MAI Basic on
grounds that its takeover offer was illegal and flawed.
   The suit filed in U.S. District Court alleged improprieties in
the tender offer, including failure to disclose the uncertain nature
of its financing and that some owners of MAI Basic have been
investigated by the Securities and Exchange Commission for allegedly
overstating the firm's income.
   The suit also alleges full disclosure was not made of the role in
the tender offer played by Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., which has
been sued by the SEC on urelated securities fraud charges.
   MAI Basic said in response that the suit is groundless and the
company was ``disappointed that Prime has resorted to this legal
smokescreen apparently before the Prime board has made a decision
about the merits of our offer.''
   Prime has asked shareholders to wait until the company's board of
directors announces its recommendation on the offer, which is
expected by Nov. 29.
   Prime also announced Tuesday it has delayed until at least Dec.
13 the activation of its shareholder rights ``poison-pill'' defense,
which is designed to make an unwelcome takeover prohibitively
expensive.
   MAI Basic has filed suit in Chancery Court in Delaware, where
Prime is incorporated, seeking to block the defense.
</TEXT>
