<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   11-23 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auto Sales Up But Analysts Pessimistic</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. car and light truck sales were up 3.5 percent
in mid-November compared with the same period last year, but the
figures announced Wednesday were lower than expected.
   The seven automakers said they sold 259,725 vehicles during the
Nov. 11-20 period this year, compared with 282,177 during the same
time last year.
   The comparison is based on the daily average of vehicles sold in
the period, which included eight selling days, one less than last
year.
   Car sales rose 3.7 percent this year over mid-November last year,
and truck sales were up 3.3 percent.
   Despite the gains, analyst Donald DeScenza of Nomura Securities
Inc. of New York was pessimistic about the industry's performance.
   This year, he said, there was no ``end-of-model-year blowout
incentive programs'' like last year when buyers planning to purchase
a new car in October or November moved up their plans and hit the
showrooms in September.
   ``You'd have a tremendous burst in sales in August and September
and a counterbalancing weakness in October and November,'' he said.
   But that didn't happen in 1988, and sales figures for October and
November of this year should be much higher than figures from the
same time last year.
   ``The fact is that they weren't up much at all, and you'd have
expected them to be,'' he said. ``The fact that it isn't way ahead
of (last year's pace) is surprising.''
   Among the Big Three car makers, General Motors Corp. showed the
only gain in mid-November this year, compared with the same time
last year _ rising 6.4 percent on a daily rate. During the period
this year, GM sold 76,291 cars compared with the 80,628 cars it sold
during the period last year.
   Ford Motor Co.'s car sales fell 1.9 percent to 47,450 in
mid-November this year compared with 54,442 last year. Chrysler
Corp.'s car sales fell 2.6 percent to 22,933 this year from 26,484
last year.
   So far this calendar year, though, all the Big Three showed sales
gains, with Chrysler leading the way, followed by Ford and GM.
   Chrysler, the nation's No. 3 automaker, sold 953,390 cars between
Jan. 1 and Nov. 20 of this year, up 11.3 percent from the 856,442 it
sold during the same time last year.
   Ford showed a more modest increase, going up 9.2 percent to
1,970,528 cars this year from 1,805,212 last year.
   GM's year-to-date car sale figures showed a slight 0.9 percent
increase, going to 3,243,423 this year from 3,214,423 last year.
</TEXT>
