<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1913EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Peru-Economy     11-23 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Economy,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peru Government Doubles Food Prices, Boosts Wages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has doubled food prices and
devalued Peru's currency 50 percent in a further effort to combat
rampant inflation and boost exports.
   The program, announced late Tuesday by Finance Minister Abel
Salinas, was the fourth emergency economic package this year aimed
at pulling Peru from a sharp recession.
   It included wage increases of about 50 percent for most Peruvian
workers.
   A similar package of sweeping austerity measures announced in
September failed to slow inflation. It did spark widespread street
protests and some sporadic looting.
   Economists and opposition politicians labeled the new package
contradictory and said it would not end a severe food shortage or
the wave of strikes stemming from the recession.
   For a month housewives and others have been forced to wait for
hours in lines of several blocks to buy daily rations of such basic
food stuffs as bread, sugar and rice.
   Salinas said the program continues government efforts to phase
out subsidies of food and consumer and industrial goods and thus
reduce the nation's burgeoning deficit, considered the major cause
of inflation.
   Consumer prices have soared 932.5 percent since January and are
expected to surpass 1,200 percent for the year. The previous highest
annual inflation rate was 158.3 percent in 1985.
   Salinas said a currency devaluation of 50 percent, dropping the
value of the Peruvian inti from 250 to 500 intis to the U.S. dollar,
would restrict imports and serve as an incentive to manufacturers to
boost exports.
   Independent analyst Alejandro Toledo said the center-left
government of Alan Garcia ``must now pay the bill'' after financing
two previous years of growth with government subsidies.
   On taking office in July 1985, Garcia limited payments on the
nation's foreign debt and used money owed international banks to
finance an economic recovery program.
   The economy grew 8.5 percent in 1986 and 7 percent in 1987. But
the government's dollar reserves ran out a year ago and the economy
fell into a recession this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881123-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1740EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Bonds     11-23 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bonds,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bonds Narrowly Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices drifted in a narrow range and
finished mixed Wednesday in quiet pre-holiday trading.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year issue edged up 1-16 point, or
less than $1 for every $1,000 in face amount. Its yield slipped to
9.10 percent from 9.11 percent late Tuesday.
   Analysts said bond prices weakened early in the day as oil prices
advanced, suggesting that value-eroding inflation could accelerate.
   But they said bonds recovered some lost ground later as oil
prices fell off their highs amid indications that OPEC may have a
tough time coming to an agreement on production limits.
   Elliott Platt, research director for Donaldson Lufkin & Jenrette
Securities Corp., said the market appeared to shrug off the
government's report that durable goods orders rose 2.4 percent in
October.
   He said even though the increase was bigger than expected, it
reflected a sizeable rise in defense orders which many economists do
not view as an indication of underlying economic strength.
   Platt said the pace of trading trailed off sharply in the
afternoon as many traders got a head start on Thursday's observance
of Thanksgiving.
   Meantime, the Treasury sold $7.5 billion in five-year, two-month
notes at an average yield of 8.97 percent, down from 9.04 percent at
the Aug. 24 auction and the lowest since five-year notes averaged
8.77 percent on May 26.
   In the secondary market, prices of short-term government issues
were unchanged, intermediate maturities fell 3-32 point and 20-year
issues rose [ point, according to figures provided by Telerate Inc.,
a financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Daily Treasury Bond Index, which measures
price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities
of a year or longer, fell 0.42 to 1,134.52.
   In corporate trading, industrials gained ground. Moody's
Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price
movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or
longer, rose 0.07 to 293.74.
   In tax-exempt trading, prices declined 1-32 point, according to
the Bond Buyers Municipal Bond Index.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 8.25 percent with
the discount down 3 basis points at 7.98 percent. The yield on
six-month bills was unchanged at 8.52 percent as the discount held
at 8.07 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 8.68 percent as
the discount fell 1 basis point to 8.05 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted late in the day at 8 5-16 percent, down from 8]
percent late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
