<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-23 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copper Prices Rocket On Renewed Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Renewed fears of tight supplies ignited an explosion in copper
futures prices Wednesday on New York's Commodity Exchange as hedgers
and speculators bought heavily ahead of the Thanksgiving weekend,
driving prices to record highs.
   On other markets, rumors of a U.S.-Soviet grain-sales agreement
supported grain and soybean futures while prices of sugar, crude
oil, precious metals, livestock, meat and stock-index futures all
advanced.
   Wednesday's 8 percent rise in the price of copper for December
delivery, along with Tuesday's 6 percent gain, appeared to end a
three-week period of consolidation and seemed to signal that the
restless market was again on the upswing, analysts said.
   Copper settled 4 cents to 11.8 cents higher on the Commodity
Exchange with December at $1.546 a pound and the spot November
contract at $1.60 a pound, an all-time high for Comex copper.
   Copper's long-term bullish factors include dwindling on-hand
supplies, expanding consumption and declining production in several
key countries including Peru, where a miners' strike is in its sixth
week.
   But fresh developments had been scarce until Wednesday, when the
Comex reported a 24 percent decline during the past week in its
warehouse stocks of copper to a record-low 5,957 short tons.
   The decline of nearly 1,900 tons shocked traders who had become
accustomed to weekly offtake figures between 500 and 1,000 tons,
said Bette Raptopoulos, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. in New York.
   ``Suddenly now you're seeing a sharp decline to under 6,000 tons
and that spells lack of availability,'' she said.
   Analysts said the market expected both the Comex and the London
Metal Exchange to report further drops in warehouse stocks next week.
   Fred Demler, metals economist with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in
New York, said copper production in Peru, the world's sixth-largest
producer, was down 17 percent through the first three quarters of
this year while production in both Zambia and Zaire was down 20
percent and Chilean shipments declined 7 percent.
   ``So these production problems are persisting and likely to
disrupt output over the next two quarters,'' he said.
   Prices of most grain and soybean futures advanced on the Chicago
Board of Trade amid reports that announcement of a new long-term
U.S.-Soviet grain deal was imminent.
   But with most forward-looking market players already fairly well
convinced that an agreement was at hand, Wednesday's price movement
was dampened by disappointment over the lack of other large-scale
grain sales on the horizon.
   As for the timing of an announcement about a Soviet grain deal,
``It makes no difference if it's Friday, Monday, Wednesday _ it's
just around the corner,'' said Katharina Zimmer, grain market
analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc.
   Wheat settled 1 cent lower to 5 cents higher with December at
$4.18 a bushel; corn was } cent lower to { cent higher with December
at $2.63\ a bushel; oats were 1} cent to 3\ cents higher with
December at $2.12\ a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 4{ cents
higher with January at $7.55\ a bushel.
   Sugar futures prices rallied to new three-month highs on New
York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange on bullish fundamental and
technical factors, analysts said.
   The active March contract topped the key resistance point of 11
cents a pound in intra-day trading.
   Sugar settled .25 cent to .29 cent higher with the active March
contract at 10.94 cents a pound.
   Energy futures prices gyrated with each new development from the
OPEC meeting in Vienna but ended mixed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 16 cents
higher with January at $13.97 a barrel; heating oil was .28 cent to
.84 cent higher with December at 45.72 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .87 cent lower to .06 cent higher with December at
44.46 cents a gallon.
   Precious-metals futures advanced on the Comex in line with crude
oil.
   Gold settled $1.80 to $2.30 higher with December at $420.10 a
troy ounce; silver was 2 cents to 4.3 cents higher with December at
$6.095 a troy ounce.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled .35 cent
to .70 cent higher with December at 73.47 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .32 cent to .73 cent higher with January at 82.35 cents
a pound; hogs were .47 cent lower to .47 cent higher with December
at 39.90 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .33 cent to .63
cent higher with February at 42.80 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures advanced modestly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 settled .90 point higher at 269.25.
</TEXT>
