<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pillsbury     11-23 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Up After Saying It Will Consider Selling Self As Two
Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. stock climbed Wednesday after
the company reportedly indicated for the first time since becoming
the takeover target of Britain's Grand Metropolitan PLC that it may
sell itself and its Burger King Corp. unit as separate companies.
   The possible defense tactic was included in a Securities and
Exchange Commission filing, The Wall Street Journal reported
Wednesday.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Pillsbury stock rose
$1.12{ a share to $57.
   ``If Burger King and the company were sold as separate entities
in the future (although no decision has been made to sell Burger
King or the company in the future) there would be additional
potential buyers and substantially greater values could be realized
for stockholders,'' the SEC filing said.
   But the filing also said Pillsbury directors believe now isn't
the right time to sell, partly because Smith only took over in
August and partly because ``greater values could be realized in the
future as a result of the restructuring efforts presently under
way.''
   Pillsbury is resisting the $5.23 billion hostile takeover bid
from Grand Met, a British distilling, gambling and specialty
products conglomerate.
   On Monday, Pillsbury announced it was delaying the planned
spinoff of its Burger King subsidiary by 2{ weeks.
   Pillsbury's board of directors pushed the date of the spinoff
back to Dec. 19 from Dec. 2, at the request of the Delaware court
that is hearing Grand Met's challenge of the plan, Smith said Monday.
   The proposed spinoff, which would make Burger King a separate,
publicly traded concern held by current Pillsbury shareholders, is a
key element in the company's attempts to thwart Grand Met's bid.
   A hearing on the Grand Met challenge is scheduled for Monday
before Chancellor William Allen in Delaware Chancery Court.
   Grand Met is seeking court orders to overturn the spinoff as well
as an anti-takeover provision in Pillsbury's bylaws. Grand Met also
has said it might have to lower its $60 a share offer if the spinoff
occurred because the new Burger King would present a huge tax
liability.
   Grand Met said Monday more than 72 million shares of Pillsbury
common stock, representing about 84.6 percent of outstanding shares,
have been tendered and not withdrawn.
   Pillsbury's board of directors has rejected Grand Met's offer as
inadequate, and urged shareholders not to tender their stock.
   At a weekend meeting, the Pillsbury board affirmed Smith's
decision to decline a personal meeting with Grand Met Chairman Allen
Sheppard, Pillsbury said Monday. Sheppard renewed the plea in a
letter to Pillsbury on Tuesday, but Pillsbury did not comment on its
strategy.
</TEXT>
