<FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 2002EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     11-23 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise on Cautious Optimism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum markets remained cautiously optimistic
in the face of continued uncertainty over whether OPEC will reach an
agreement to curtail oil production.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Wednesday, the January
contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude, closed at $13.97 a barrel, up 11 cents from Tuesday's
settlement price. The contract had traded as much as 74 cents
higher. Other contract months also rose.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries apparently
remained deadlocked Wednesday in its efforts to reach a new
agreement on reducing the cartel's output and boost world crude
prices.
   The ministers from the 13-nation cartel meeting in Vienna,
Austria, postponed until Thursday a planned formal meeting scheduled
for Wednesday but continued to meet in small, informal groups.
   Analysts said oil prices opened sharply higher in brisk trading
but then began to backtrack after the announcement that the OPEC
ministers had postponed their plenary session for the second time
since Monday.
   Minutes before the early Thanksgiving eve closing at about 1 p.m.
EST, a wave of frenzied selling drove prices sharply off their
highs, analysts said.
   Nevertheless, the market closed with a ``positive bias,'' said
Mike McDermott, an analyst with Benchmark Futures Inc.
   ``(Investors) think there is going to be an agreement but they're
not sure so they don't want to have an outright position'' going
into the long weekend, he said. The U.S. oil markets will remain
closed until Monday.
   In other futures trading, the prices of refined crude products
finished the day mixed, with unleaded gasoline down sharply and
heating oil up.
   The December contract for unleaded gasoline fell 0.87 cent a
gallon to 44.46 cents after rising more than a penny on Tuesday.
Analysts said the drop was in response to an American Petroleum
Institute report showing gasoline stocks rose 6.5 million barrels
last week.
   Bob Baker, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., said
the higher gasoline supply reflected sharply higher imports and
weaker consumer demand.
   ``There had been talk of unseasonably high demand for gasoline,''
Baker said. ``In fact, we have not had that kind of change. Gasoline
consumption trends are moderate and the market is selling off
because of the adjustment.''
   Heating oil for December rose 0.28 cent to 45.72 cents a gallon,
pulled up by the higher crude prices, analysts said.
   Despite the Thanksgiving Day holiday, analysts said some trading
would continue Thursday and Friday through the London International
Petroleum Exchange.
   Analysts said they expect OPEC either to reach some kind of
agreement by Friday or adjourn the meeting.
   ``A couple of ministers have said they will return home by the
end of this week,'' Baker said, ``so most probably the time for a
solution is Friday. They can't see staying around if they don't have
an agreement by then.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
